lead_paragraph: we learn that Gen. GILLMORE'S batteries, after three weeks' silence, had commenced working again, and kept up a slow fire against the ruins of Fort Sumter. The same paper reports that Gen, BURNSIDE'S forces had burned the railroad bridge at Carter's Station, twenty miles from Bristol, Tenn., and were retreating toward Knoxville, followed by the rebel cavalry. Affairs on the Rapidan were reported quiet on the 26th, but considerable anxiety was expressed for the safety of LEE's army, in case Gen. MEADE should attack because of its greatly decreased strength.

abstract: The beautiful weather of yesterday was improved in a manner at once instructive and agreeable to our Muscovite guests, the officers of the Russian squadron now at anchor in the North River. The Pilot Commissioners of this port had with happy tact, conceived that a visit to our fortifications and a trip around the harbor under fair skies and with fresh ...
lead_paragraph: The beautiful weather of yesterday was improved in a manner at once instructive and agreeable to our Muscovite guests, the officers of the Russian squadron now at anchor in the North River. The Pilot Commissioners of this port had with happy tact, conceived that a visit to our fortifications and a trip around the harbor under fair skies and with fresh breezes cooling the atmosphere, would be an entertainment that the Russian officers would relish, and which would, also, be most approppriate to their taste and their profession. Acting upon this idea they, within a few days, invited the strangers to make the tour of our upper and lower bay under their auspices, and the courtesy having been cordirlly accepted, at 10 o'clock yesterday morning, a goodly company of notables from our City and its neighborhood, assembled at the foot of Whitehall-street and embarked on board the steamer Travelier Capt. MCNEIL.

abstract: -The New-York correspondent of the London Times is amusing the English "nation of shopkeepers" with what their hearts most delight in -- a statement of the profit and loss of various great transactions that they have been reading about. abstract: -- They are getting some very fancy articles on the European Stock market. They have already the great Confederate fifteen million loan, whose fluctuations have been so curious. In addition to this, it seems by to-day's European news, the rebels propose to raise another great loan -- how great is not yet announced. In addition to these, and equally fancy, we learn from the Diplomatic Memorial that a "Mexican personage of elevated rank" has had interviews with the financial notabilities of Paris and London, and has settled the bases for a loan of five hundred million francs, for the sustenance of the new usurpation of MAXIMILIAN, -- for the purchase of crown, sceptre, throne, royal robes and such things for the new King, -- and for the payment of the JECKER bonds, and other outstanding and outside expenses. In the words of the organ: "One portion of the loan will be devoted to the repayment of the expenses of the French expedition, another portion for the benefit of English creditors, another will be capitalized, and the remainder used to supply the expenditures of the Mexican Government." It may be that both these loans will be taken. European speculators are fond of just such fancies, as the history of the past proves. But if they don't get badly "bit" yet by both the rebels and the usurpers, we shall be very much mistaken indeed.

lead_paragraph: The Pilot Commissioners of this port yesterday conducted the officers of the Russian squadron on a grand aquatic tour through the Upper and Lower Bay, visiting all the fortifications as far is Sandy Hook. The Russian Admiral was not present, but was represented by a large number of his subordinates. In compliance with a general order, the Admiral's salute was fired from all the forts approached by the steamer Traveler, on board of which the party embarked between 10 and 11 A.M., returning toward dusk. A large company of City and State notabilities accompanied the guests of the day, and in the afternoon a handsome collation was enjoyed on board of the steamer, with a long list of appropriate toasts and responses by Mayor OPDYKE, Gen. CANBY, Rev. Drs. BELLOWS and CHAPIN, and others. The Muscovite officers were evidently greatly [???]ased and interested.

abstract: There  is a strong effort to throw the blame of ROSECRANS' defeat in the late battles in Georgia on the Washington military authorities, under pretence that the advance from Chattanooga was ordered contrary to the judgment and wishes of the Commanding General. The charge, from whatever motive it is made, reveals an utter lack of appreciation of the military situation.
lead_paragraph: There is a strong effort to throw the blame of ROSECRANS' defeat in the late battles in Georgia on the Washington military authorities, under pretence that the advance from Chattanooga was ordered contrary to the judgment and wishes of the Commanding General. The charge, from whatever motive it is made, reveals an utter lack of appreciation of the military situation. An advance beyond Chattanooga was, for Gen. ROSECRANS, an absolute necessity for securing his position at Chattanooga. The possession of Chattanooga secured the salient of the upper line of railway communication between the East and West, but it left a secondary line running from Richmond, by way of Charleston and Atlanta. To have left this line, with its salient at Home, Ga., leading up to within immediate striking distance of Chattanooga, in rebel possession, was simply to invite concentration against him by the enemy. To seize this was the object of Gen. ROSECRANS' advance. Indeed, we know positively that, at the very outset of the campaign, when the Army of the Cumberland was set in motion from Murfreesboro, the ultimate objective which Gen. ROSECRANS had in his mind's eye was not Chattanooga, but, through it, to seize Dalton, Rome or Atlanta, any one of which points would plant him on this line and enable him to make himself secure at Chattanooga. The misfortune was that he was not able to push on with such celerity as to seize one of these points before the rebels were able to make the line available for reinforcements to BRAGG. Given after this, it was an error to have left ROSECRANS with a force inadequate for the object in view, and the Government's failure to reinforce him doubtless subjects it to blame; but an advance beyond Chattanooga was an absolute military necessity, and to blame the Washington authorities for this, displays the sheerest ignorance, to say the least.

abstract: COLLISION ON THE RIVER. -- Yesterday morning, during the prevalence of the fog, the ferry-boat Jersey City ran into the United States revenue cutter Tishoga, which resulted in damaging the latter vessel to a considerable extent. The cutter was stuck on the starboard bow, displacing some of the planks and knees. The ferry-boat escaped uninjured. The cutter had her powder, stores and crew on board ready [???] for Fortress Monroe, but this accident will delay her for several days.

abstract: CITY MISSIONS.--On Tuesday evening, the Tract Society, laboring by missionaries and visitors, in the streets and lanes of the City, held a meeting in the Fifteenth-street Presbyterian Church, A.R. WETMORE, Esq., presiding.
lead_paragraph: CITY MISSIONS. -- On Tuesday evening, the Tract Society, laboring by missionaries and visitors, in the streets and lanes of the City, held a meeting in the Fifteenth-street Presbyterian Church, A.R. WETMORE, Esq., presiding. There were many circumstances related showing the good done to the body and the soul, like the following: A woman whose husband is in the United States Army, whose son is at sea, is found weeping on the dying bed of her only daughter; the missionary lifts up the sorrowing heart, and administers to the wants of the departing; the funeral services are properly conducted and the dead decently buried. Subsequently the bereaved mother found the house of God to be the home of the afflicted, and the words of Jesus the life of the soul!

abstract: The Copperheads are, of course, trying to make all they can out of the reverse which the Army of the Cumberland has sustained. All is fish that comes to their net, and as they could not but admit before the battle that such a reverse would give them aid in the...
lead_paragraph: The Copperheads are, of course, trying to make all they can out of the reverse which the Army of the Cumberland has sustained. All is fish that comes to their net, and as they could not but admit before the battle that such a reverse would give them aid in the approaching State elections, it is not to be wondered at if they do not profit by it. These outcries of the Copperheads are not the first instance on record of a robber trying to escape by crying "Stop thief!" History will lay the blame of it in great measure upon the Copperheads themselves, and no small part of it upon the Governor of our own State.

abstract: --The  sneer of the World at the entertainment given to the Russian Admiral LISOVSKY, by a Western gentleman, in this City, a few evenings ago, is ill-mannered and impertinent. It is a free country, and any man who wills may invite friends to meet him and order dinners, provided only he pays for them--and it is nobody's business.
lead_paragraph: -The sneer of the World at the entertainment given to the Russian Admiral LISOVSKY, by a Western gentleman, in this City, a few evenings ago, is ill-mannered and impertinent. It is a free country, and any man who wills may invite friends to meet him and order dinners, provided only he pays for them -- and it is nobody's business. Capt. EADS did not pretend to act in any other character than that of a private gentleman in the courtesies he extended to the Russian Admiral. It was for the latter to judge whether the relations between the parties were such as to justify the invitation he received. The fact that the Admiral accepted the invitation to dinner, and was honored with an elegant entertainment -- that he met fit company there, including the most distinguished hero of our own navy, and that he toasted his host as his "old friend," whose "courtesy and hospitality" he had often before enjoyed, and which he pronounced "creditable to his country," ought to put this question at rest.

abstract: Union Mass Meeting at Cooper Institute; (Vice-President) Speech at Union Mass Meeting in New-York
snippet: Union Mass Meeting at Cooper Institute; (Vice-President) Speech at Union Mass Meeting in New-York
lead_paragraph: The mass meeting held at the Cooper Institute last evening, to ratify the nominations of the Union Syracuse Convention, was one of the largest and most enthusiastic gatherings ever seen in this City. Long before the meeting was called to order, every seat in the large hall was occupied, as well as every foot of standing room in the aisles and lobbies. In addition to the immense throng that filled the hall inside, an audience equally large of those who were unable to gain admittance, assembled around the various stands outside, where they were addressed by distinguished speakers. It was, in fact, a spontaneous outpouring of the people, without distinction of party, and augured well for the success of the Union and anti-partisan ticket which it was called on to ratify. The hall inside was beautifully decorated with the Stars and Stripes, and with banners on which were inscribed patriotic sentiments like the following:

abstract: CAPT. JOHN DUNNE. -- The remains of Capt. JOHN DUNNE, who died of disease contracted in Virginia, were conveyed to his last resting-place in the Cemetery of the Holy Cross, at F[???]bush, yesterday. A grand requiem high mass was celebrated at St. James Cathedral. The deceased was formerly a Sergeant in the Forty-fourth British infantry, and participated in the battles of the Crimes and at the seige and capture of Set[???]as[???], where he was twice wounded. He came to this country some eight years ago and engaged in mercantile business. When the war broke out he raised a company, but, in consequence of some difficulty, abandoned it, and subsequently raised another for the One Hundred and Sixty-fourth regiment, with which he marched to Suffolk, Va., where he was appointed an aid to Gen. [???]ORAN. The cause of his death was typhoid fever. The deceased leaves a wife, but no children. He was in the thirty-third year of his age. Rev. Father FREEL delivered the funeral discourse.

abstract: A letter received by the Louisvillie Journal from a high source at Chattanooga, dated on the 23d inst., speaks with confidence. The writer says:  "It is now I think settled that Gen. ROSECRANS...
lead_paragraph: A letter received by the Louisvillie Journal from a high source at Chattanooga, dated on the 23d inst., speaks with confidence. The writer says: "It is now I think settled that Gen. ROSECRANS will hold his position in Chattanooga against all the combined forces of the Confederates brought from Charleston, Richmond, Mobile, &c. Our position is more than equal to all the force they can bring against this army. Three days have enabled Gen. ROSECRANS to make his position immensely strong. Chattanooga has much more practical and natural advantages for defence from the south side than from the north, and, as the enemy cannot get in our rear, we are very strongly posted. Full confidence and great cheerfulness exist among the whole army. The enemy were so badly hurt that they have not been disposed to press forward."

abstract: Recognition and Abolition, Proposals for by
snippet: Recognition and Abolition, Proposals for by
lead_paragraph: A nice question to settle between the French and the Confederates, prior to recognition, is that of Slavery. Nearly all the French official and semi-official writers (which means all the writers in France) who urge recognition, urge it on the ground that the Emperor will be able to make the abolition or modification of Slavery a consequent, concomitant or condition of the favor of recognition. Even Monsieur CHEVALIER, who has taken the boldest stand of any man in France in favor of recognizing JEFF, DAVIS, declares that "France will use her influence to bring about the gradual emancipation of the slaves;" that "the emancipation of the blackamoors, the complete abolition of slavery, will be the work of peace and time," and that "the European Power which shall be the first to recognize the Confederate States will have the right to obtain on behalf of the blacks far more than would the Federal Slates;" and one of his strongest points against the North is that "the men of the North, if victorious, would not cut into the quick of the Slavery question," for they would value too highly the cotton culture.

abstract: Grund, Francis J.
snippet: Grund, Francis J.
lead_paragraph: The death of FRANCIS J. GRUND, which was mentioned in the TIMES of yesterday, is an event of considerable political as well as personal interest. He was a man of very great ability, and for many years exerted through the newspaper Press a very marked influence on the course of current events. He was a man of learning -- not only speaking several languages with facility, but familiar with their literature and master of their philosophy. He was an able mathematician, having filled for some years the Professorship in that Department in one of our leading classical schools, and having punished text books on several of its branches. Many years ago, however, he left science and letters for the more congenial field of political discussion, and although his labors were mainly exerted through the unconspicuous channels of anonymous journalism, they were always zealous, persevering and effective. He was always connected with the Democratic party, though not unfrequently, as at the very last, he had left its service in disgust at some flagrant departure from its principles or some suicidal surrender of the patriotic sentiments which have always animated the mass of its members. By his political opponents, whether of his own party or not, he has always been denounced as unreliable and as serving the side that would pay him best; but we know nothing in his character or his public conduct which should separate him, for special censure in this respect, from the class of journalists to which he belonged. He always wrote with great clearness and force, and his access to the best sources of information gave special value and interest to his political correspondence. His knowledge of European politics was full, precise and comprehensive, and his judgment of current events abroad as well as at home was marked by a just and impartial appreciation of men and measures. During the Italian war in 1859, he wrote a view of European Politics as related to that event and to the policy of the French Emperor, which was by far the ablest and most instructive treatise on that subject published on either side the Atlantic. He was a genial companion, excellent and interesting in conversation in spite of a slight tendency to dogmatism, and full of fresh and valuable knowledge upon almost every subject. As one of the ablest and most vigorous and influential of the contributors to the newspaper Press, his death is a substantial loss to the profession of journalism.

abstract: AMERICAN GRAPE EXHIBITION--The largest display of native, hardy grapes yet made in this City, are to be scan at No. 41 Park-row. Forty-one grape growers from different parts of the country have contributed to this handsome and interesting exhibition,...
lead_paragraph: AMERICAN GRAPE EXHIBITION -- The largest display of native, hardy grapes yet made in this City, are to be scan at No. 41 Park-row. Forty-one grape growers from different parts of the country have contributed to this handsome and interesting exhibition, and the result of the comparison of the several kinds will prove of great value in the culture and improvement of vines. The exhibition is under the auspices of the Fruit Growers' Association of New-York. Those who find interest and pleasure in such matters will be more than compensated by witnessing the collection. The judges on grapes have made the following report, awarding prizes to the exhibitors: Best native Seedling, which has never before taken a prize, $10, to PETER B. MEAD, of New-York, for "Iona." Best collection of native grapes, $10, to A.S. FULLER, of Brooklyn. Second best collection of native grapes, $5, to M. OLM, Flushing, gardener to ORANGE JUDD, No. 41 Park-row, N.Y. Best six varieties of native grapes, $4, to F.F. MERCERON, Catawissa, Pa. Second best six varieties of native grapes, $2, to GEORGE W. MARTIN, Brooklyn, E.D., N.Y. Best four varieties native grapes, $4 to W. BROCKSBANE, Hudson, N.Y. Second best four varieties native grapes, $2, to FRED, BAUMEISTER, East Newark, N.J. Best five bunches native grapes of any kind, quality to rule, $2, to J.W. BAILEY, Platisburgh, N.Y., for "Adirondac." Best five bunches Delaware, $2, to E.O. EATON, Troy, N.Y. Best five bunches Diana, $2, to F.C. BREHN, Waterloo, N.Y. Best five bunches Catawba, $2, to W.B. WESTCOTT, New-York, (grown in City yard.) Best five bunches Concord, $2, to S.H. YOUNG, Poughkeepsie, N.Y. Best five bunches Hartford Proli[???]e, $2, to W. TAFT, Fordhain, N.Y. Best five bunches Herbemont, $2, to C.F. ERHARDT, Ravenswood, L.I. Best five bunches Allen's Hybrid, $2, to JOHN HOAG, Newburgh, N.Y. Discretionary prize of $1, to GEORGE W. MARTIN, Brooklyn, N.Y., for Brinkley, grown out of doors. Discretionary prize of $1, to PETER RAABS, Philadelphia, Pa., for Loomis' Honey, in point of flavor. Discretionary prize of $3, to N. ARMSTRONG, Bergen, N.J., for collection of hot-house grapes. None of the prizes were awarded for foreign grapes, there being no competition under the schedule. For the only lot (containing one bunch of each kind) the Committee have recommended a discretionary prize. With regard to native grapes, the Committee are much gratified, particularly with the quality of the fruit, considering the present unfavorable season, and are disposed to commend not only the design of the New-York Fruit Growers' Society, in arranging for this display, so interesting and instructive, but also the public spirit and enterprise of Mr. ORANGE JUDD, Editor of the American Agriculturist, who placed his rooms at the disposal of the Society, and contributed the prize money and entire expenses of the exhibition. Chas. Downing, D.S. Dewey, John Dailledouze, Wm. Chorlton, Isaac Buchanan, Committee of Judges.

abstract: -- "S.," or SPENCE, who has labored in England for the rebels, in season and out of season -- in the London Times, on the Stock Exchange, in the "Southern Club," and everywhere else -- has not only been ignominiously dismissed from his post of Financial Agent of the Confederacy for Great Britain, but is getting for his pains the maledictions of the rebel Press. They accuse him of arguing the cause of the Pro-Slavery Republican Anti-Slavery grounds, and the accusation is undoubtedly true, even judging of it by his articles in the Times. Like the French supporters of the Confederacy, he tried to win over the support of European opinion to the rebel cause by showing that its success would ultimate in the abolition of Slavery -- a [???] which we will not at this moment deny, any more than we will deny the converse proposition, that the failure of the rebels will have the same result. The rebels endured all this for a long time, but at last it was found to be too much for them. The Richmond Enquirer concentrates all possible scorn and contempt upon the late agent, by characterizing him as "SPENCE, that notable agent of Mr. BENJAMIN -- we say distinctly of Mr. Benjamin," and adds: "Let any 'agent' who dares to offer our honor for sale, or who basely invites, or acquiesces in, or hints at any possible negotiations to that end, cease to be our agent, or there will be a storm." Let Monsieur CHEVALIER, who is following in the footsteps of poor SPENCE, read this last sentence, and let him take warning in season.

abstract: The State Election and the Mass Meeting of Sept. 30
snippet: The State Election and the Mass Meeting of Sept. 30
lead_paragraph: The resolutions adopted at the Cooper Institute meeting, on Wednesday night, justly define the nature and importance of the political contest in this State. Its result decides the position which New-York is to hold for the next year, in the struggle for the preservation of the nation's life. Last year a combination of circumstances made Mr. SEYMOUR Governor of the State. Nothing contributed more to this result than the tardy and unsatisfactory progress of the war. Reverses had overtaken the Union arms in some quarters, and in all, failures to achieve their aims had followed their efforts. The Administration had gone just far enough to incur immense and oppressive responsibilities, while it had not done enough to secure the confidence and support of an impatient and exacting people.

abstract: Grand Ovation to Russian Naval Officers in New-York
snippet: Grand Ovation to Russian Naval Officers in New-York
lead_paragraph: Yesterday was a memorable one in the history of the City, as having been set apart for the formal reception of the Russian Admiral LISOVSKY and the Officers of his Fleet, and as being the occasion of welcome exceeding in warmth and earnestness any that busy and big-hearted New-York has extended. The day was beautiful, and the feeling of the people hospitable and exuberant. There was evidently a desire among all to extend to out distinguished guests an unmistakably hearty and cordial welcome. The desire was more than fulfilled, for, from the lancing of the Officers until their departure from the City Hall, the ovation was one of the most brilliant, hearty and gratifying character. Of course, it was not to the individuals so much as to the Sovereign and People of the great empire they represented, whose consistent and sincere friendship has been appreciated by the public heart. abstract: Russian Naval Officers' Reception in New-York
snippet: Russian Naval Officers' Reception in New-York
lead_paragraph: Our City was the scene yesterday of one of those grand civic but semi-military pageants, which can be produced in no other nation of the globe so successfully as in ours. The occasion was the reception by the Municipal authorities of New-York of the Russian Admiral LISOVSKY and other officers of the Russian naval squadron, now at anchor in New-York Bay. Twice before in quite recent history have similar pageants been presented in this City. When the Japanese Embassy was received in this country, New-York put forth special efforts to please and entertain the nation's guests. That demonstration was memorably successful -- though it must be admitted that it was as a pageant only that it had its success. It possessed neither moral nor political significance, and was bound to subside into comparative oblivion. What was or is Japan to us, or we to Japan? Nothing before -- certainly little, if anything, since. The reception of the Japanese, splendid as it was, was too barren of real feeling or fruits for the efforts put forth on the occasion.

abstract: Hunt, Major E. B., U. S. A.
snippet: Hunt, Major E. B., U. S. A.
lead_paragraph: The death of Maj. E.B. HUNT, which occurred yesterday at the Brooklyn Navy-yard, will cause profound regrets among a large and devoted circle of friends, both in the army and private life. Maj. HUNT had, it is well known, been engaged for many months in the construction of a new submarine battery of his own invention, which promised to give the most important results. Yesterday, it is stated, that in making experiments on the vessel a shell burst, and the gas evoked so affected him that he fell down into the hold, producing concussion of the brain. He was carried to the Naval Hospital and died during the day.

abstract: The British bark Winthrop, Capt. MOULTON, from Matamoras, arrived at this port last evening. She reports that on Sept. 21, lat. 30° 25′ lon. 78° 40′ at 9 A.M., a vessel was seen with a flag of distress living. Kept off for her, and she proved to be the sloop Eliza, of Nassau, with mast and rudder gone, and in a sinking condition. Took off the Captain and crew, and brought them to this port. The Captain, THOS. GEO MOLLO, of the Eliza, reports that he sailed from Green Turtle Key Aug. 29, bound to Key West, with a cargo of pineapple-slips, and on the 9th September, off the Great Bahama Bank, in a gale from southeast and east-southeast, was blown off and lost rudder; tried to get inside the northwest part of Matainiila Reef on the 16th., but it was blowing so heavy from east-southeast and southeast was compelled to scud before the wind. At 5 P.M. cut away the mast, it then blowing very heavy from southeast At 8 A.M. a man was washed overboard, but they succeeded in recovering him with a line. The crew was engaged twelve days steering with oars. On the 16th the sloop sprung alcak, and could not be kept free. On the 21st, lat. 30° 26′, lon. 79°, was taken off by Capt. MOULTON, of the bark Winthrop, of Beranda.The Eliza was eight tons burden, and her crew consisted of a Captain and two men.

abstract: Neutrality--Rebel Rams in England
snippet: Neutrality--Rebel Rams in England
lead_paragraph: We trust the British Government is in earnest in its purpose to prevent the departure from its ports of war vessels for the rebel fleet. It is quite time that the responsible rulers of that country began to realize that they have something to do in this matter beside splitting hairs and lamenting the looseness of acts of Parliament. They can scarcely expect to dwell and deal in sophistries forever. The obligations of neutrality do not rest solely on the requirements of municipal law. Whether it be forbidden by British statutes or not, it is clearly an act of hostility toward this country to lend active aid to its enemies in their war upon it. Whether the British Government can or cannot prevent its citizens from doing so, is a matter of purely domestic concern. If it can, it will consult its own interests by doing so. If it cannot, we have no alternative but to do it ourselves.

abstract: Mason and Slidell in England
snippet: Mason and Slidell in England
lead_paragraph: The Confederate emissaries, MASON and SLIDELL -- MASON in England and SLIDELL in France -- have met with very different treatment from the respective Governments to which they were accredited. SLIDELL has been on the most intimate terms with members of the Emperor's Cabinet -- has maintained the closest semi-official relations with the French Government -- has hob-nobbed with the Emperor, and followed him up in all his trips and tours -- has even got on the best footing with the Empress, and had long interviews with her Majesty. He lives in splendid style, gives grand banquets, drives unsurpassed horses, has plenty of money, and the only thing lacking to his happiness is that he should be known in Paris by his Louisiana title of the "Duke of Houmas."

abstract: --The Richmond Examiner  remarks that there is very little rejoicing at the South over their victory at Chickamauga, for, though certain defensive ends were subserved, such as the temporary salvation of Georgia and Alabama, "the enemy hold Chattanooga and East Tennessee, which were the ...
lead_paragraph: -- The Richmond Examiner remarks that there is very little rejoicing at the South over their victory at Chickamauga, for, though certain defensive ends were subserved, such as the temporary salvation of Georgia and Alabama, "the enemy hold Chattanooga and East Tennessee, which were the prizes of the battle." This is perfectly true, and JEFF. DAVIS himself expressed the idea with equal force, if with less elegance, when he said before the battle that his purpose was to "snatch Tennessee from the clutch of the Abolitionists." Failing to obtain a foothold in that State, BRAGG's victory was a disaster, and the fact that, though a fortnight has elapsed since the battle, no renewed attempt has been made to carry out the design, would indicate that JEFF. DAVIS will soon again have to make the mournful confession he made eighteen months ago, that the Confederacy "has undertaken more than it has the means of achieving."

abstract: THE KINGS COUNTY BOARD OF SUPERVISIONS. -- At a meeting of the Board held yesterday afternoon, the Committee on Court-house reported in favor of canceling the contract with the carpenters on the new Court-house, and making a new one for $18,874. The contract for furnishing the Supervisors' room in the new building was awarded to J. WOLF at $2,625. A communication from the State Comptroller was received, stating that the amount of State tax to be raised the current year in the County of Kings would be $490,738 02, being 5 mills on the dollar.

abstract: Europe is trou  bled with sensation rumors as well as our own country. Among the most recent was one prevailing at Paris that MAXIMILIAN I., Emperor elect of Mexico, had recognized the independence of the Confederate States. But  this rumor was pronounced improbable from ...
lead_paragraph: Europe is troubled with sensation rumors as well as our own country. Among the most recent was one prevailing at Paris that MAXIMILIAN I., Emperor elect of Mexico, had recognized the independence of the Confederate States. But this rumor was pronounced improbable from the fact that MAXIMILIAN had not yet been formally offered the crown by the deputation from Mexico charged with the duty of tendering it. This does seem a bar sinister to the report that has doubtless ere this given much joy in Dixie.

abstract: THE BURNING OF THE BAKERY IN FULTON STREET.--The examination in this case was resumed yesterday, before Justice DOWLING, at the Tombs. The testimony adduced was mostly of a rebutting character.
lead_paragraph: THE BURNING OF THE BAKERY IN FULTON STREET. -- The examination in this case was resumed yesterday, before Justice DOWLING, at the Tombs. The testimony adduced was mostly of a rebutting character. Several witnesses testified to the general quarrelsome and vindictive habits of Mrs. MARGARET LARKIN, the complainant in the case, Some of them had often heard her make threats against Mr. WILSON and his bakery. Two respectable witnesses swore that during the riots in July last, they heard Mrs. L. harangue a mob, and urge the crowd, in strong language, to burn Mr. WILSON's bakery in Cherry-street, Mr. JOHNSON, the night-watchman of the establishment, whom the complainant alleges was present on the night in question, and aided in setting fire to the building -- testified that he was that evening in Second-avenue, making New-Year's calls, and knew nothing of the fire until he was informed of it by the driver of a Second-avenue car; that he immediately hastened down to the bakery, and arrived there at 10 P.M., an hour and a half after the fire broke out, and long after the whole building was enveloped in flames.

abstract: We have received files of the Nassau Guardian to the 23d ult. Of news these journals are entirely barren. The shipping intelligence column shows a great falling off of the contraband traffic with the Southern States. Few steamers are reported, and the fact is corroborative of the recent rumor that the vigilance of our cruisers in the Bahama latitude had driven the blockade runners to transfer themselves to St. George's and Hamilton, Bermuda, where, at present, there seems to be less risk of capture. The Guardian, of the 23d, states that news had reached Nassau by the West Indian steamer Venezuelan, of the sinking of the United States gunboat Vanderbilt, by the rebel pirate Georgia, after an engagement of fifteen minutes. The date of this alleged occurrence is not given, and we are inclined to believe that it is nothing more than the revival of an old rumor.

abstract: On Monday last, as we learn  from the Richmond Examiner, Gen. LEE sent an official dispatch to JEFF. DAVIS, announceing that the "Eleventh and Twelfth corps of the Army of the Potomac had been sent to reinforce ROSECRANS."
lead_paragraph: On Monday last, as we learn from the Richmond Examiner, Gen. LEE sent an official dispatch to JEFF. DAVIS, announceing that the "Eleventh and Twelfth corps of the Army of the Potomac had been sent to reinforce ROSECRANS." The public have not yet been informed from Washington whether or not Gen. LEE'S information was perfectly accurate, or whether the War Department had succeeded in putting him off the scent. But, in a hundred years from now, when the history of this war shall be written, and it will be safe to reveal the movements of regiments and divisions, if it should be found that LEE knew when we were sending regiments from his front, where we were sending them to, and what regiments we were sending, it may be asked why our authorities did not know when LEE was sending reinforcements to BRAGG, and what number of regiments he was sending. If, then, however, it shall be seen that LEE was misinformed, and acted upon his misinformation, some of our Generals or functionaries may be credited by the historian with a wonderful deal of shrewdness.

abstract: Position of in Regard to Chattanooga
snippet: Position of in Regard to Chattanooga
lead_paragraph: Prior to the secession of South Carolina, and also after the State had seceded, its citizens boasted among themselves that their State was safe from invasion. The "Abolitionists "would have a long way to travel before they got there, and, whether they attempted it from the east or the north, they would find the task equally hopeless. When Fort Sumter was surrendered, it was thought that, as it was the first, so it would be the last battle in South Carolina, during the war for secession. When Virginia had passed her ordinance of secession -- almost, in fact, before she had passed it -- South Carolina hastened to send a regiment of troops to the Old Dominion, mainly that the war might be opened upon Virginia soil, and kept there, far away from her territory, if it were to be fought in the South at all; and it must be confessed that in this selfish purpose South Carolina has thus far pretty well succeeded. She has been horribly insulted and harassed, it is true, for two years, by the operations on her Southern coast; but she has taken comfort in the thought that the nature of her soil and defences made it unlikely that the Yankees would ever penetrate any further than the coast.

abstract: The Joint Committee of the Common Council on the reception and entertainment of our Russian guests met yesterday to arrange the preliminaries for the grand banquet to be given to the officers of the fleet. The Committee were in session two or three hours, but adjourned without fixing the time for the banquet, or deciding upon the place in which it is to be held. The appropriation for the purpose will require further action on the part of the Common Council, and it was decided to defer the completion of the arrangements until the meeting of the two Boards on Monday next. The Committee have been told by those competent to judge, that at least ten days will be required to prepare the table ornaments and other decorations suitable to the occasion, so that the banquet will not take place before the middle of next week -- say the 14th of 15th of October. The place for holding the banquet will probably be the Academy of Music, which will afford an opportunity for a larger number of our citizens, including ladies, to join in the festivities. As the Russian fleet will remain in our harbor for some time to come, there is no occasion for haste, in any of the means that may be adopted for the entertainment of its officers. Among other things, it is in contemplation to take them on a tour of inspection of the Public Institutions. This will probably take place some day this week. Meanwhile, the officers, as well as the crews of the squadron, are enjoying themselves in their own way in viewing the sights of the City, and partaking individually of the hospitalities of our citizens. Last evening, Admiral LISOVSKY, accompanied by a number of the officers of the fleet, visited Niblo's Theatre to witness Mlle. VESTVALI's personation of the Jewish Mother.

abstract: In ordinary times such an election as New-York is about to make would excite no particular interest. But these are not ordinary times. We are in the midst of a mighty civil war, and are threatened with foreign war. It is not a question of men. The election will be one of the "signs of the times," an omen of the future. The Administration and its enemies both make this election a trial of great national questions, and its consequences bear an important relation to our national well-being.

abstract: The Progress of the War
snippet: The Progress of the War
lead_paragraph: The proportions of the Japanese war are expanding. The Daimios seem determined to push matters to extremities. Instead of directing hostilities solely against the English, the Daimios have proscribed all outside barbarians, not excepting even the Dutch, who for over two centuries had been privileged to sojourn in and trade with Japan. Nor have these aristocrats been content with ordering all foreigners out of their country; they have been so rash as to assail all, and they have forced them all to espouse the cause of the British. Hence, it is no longer with one European nation that Japan is at war, but with all the Christian Powers which have at any time made treaties with her. The recklessness of the Daimios has driven the English, French, Hollanders, etc., into a confederacy for Japan's humiliation, and though she may prove a more troublesome foe than China or India, yet with such odds against her, the ultimate result cannot be doubtful.

abstract: Steamboat Burning at the West
snippet: Steamboat Burning at the West
lead_paragraph: -- The frequent incendiarism of steamboats in the West affords strong ground for the belief that an organized conspiracy exists for the destruction of that class of property. But whether the incendiaries are specially in the interest of the rebels, or are setting fire to boats with merely the vague hope of robbing in the confusion that always attends such burnings, is not yet clearly established. We think the latter more likely to be true than the former. But the guilt is as great in one case as the other, and should equally meet with the most condign and summary punishment.

abstract: An inquest was held on Friday, by Coroner RANNEY, at Bellevue Hospital, on the body of a Polish exile, named GEORGE GROSKE. The deceased was seized with an apoplectic fit on Thursday while in a restaurant in Leonard-street. No one knew him, and he not being able to give his name or residence, the Police conveyed him to the Hospital, where he died soon after. He was dressed very poorly and slovenly, and every one who saw him supposed him to be a pauper of the lowest class. At the time of the inquest, inquiry was made at the saloon where he was taken ill, but no satisfactory information could be obtained there. The proprietor stated that for the last three years the deceased had been in the habit of taking his meals with him, but he knew nothing about him -- not even his name. After much questioning it was at length ascertained that the supposed pauper had occupied a garret-room in White-street. A search was made of these premises, and the result was the discovery of a trunk. The contents not only revealed the name of the deceased, but the further fact that he was worth at the least $8,000. Four bank books were found, -- one which showed that he had $378 56 to his credit, in the Bank of Commerce, and three Savings' bank books which indicated that he had sums ranging from $500 to $800 in each of them. In addition to this, fifty certificates of stock in the Bank of Commerce, for $100 each, were found among his papers. Other personal property of considerable value was also discovered. The deceased was about 60 years of age, and is believed to have been a resident of this City for about seven years. There was abundant evidence, among the letters and papers found in the trunk, to show that he was a Polish exile. Notwithstanding his means, it was his uniform custom to go around apprently in a state of the most abject poverty. What his business was, or how he spent his time no one seems to know. That he has no relatives in this country is doubtless true. For this reason all his effects have been placed in the hands of the Public Administrator, to be disposed of according to law. The jury rendered a verdict in accordance with the facts. The deceased was buried yesterday in Greenwood Cemetery.

abstract: The United States steamer Massachusetts arrived to-day from Charleston Bar last Wednesday night. Our works on Morris Island were progressing rapidly. abstract: Thanksgiving Proclamation for Nov. 26
snippet: Thanksgiving Proclamation for Nov. 26
lead_paragraph: The year that is drawing toward its close has been filled with the blessings of fruitful fields and healthful skies. To these bounties, which are so constantly enjoyed that we are prone to forget the Source from which they come, others have been added, which are of so extraordinary a nature that they cannot fail to penetrate and soften even the heart which is habitually insensible to the ever-watchful providence of Almighty God. In the midst of a civil war of unequaled magnitude and severity, which has sometimes seemed to invite and provoke the aggressions of foreign States, peace has been preserved with all nations, order has been maintained, the laws have been respected and obeyed, and harmony has prevailed everywhere, except in the theatre of military conflict, while that theatre has been greatly contracted by the advancing armies and navies of the Union. The needful diversion of wealth and strength from the fields of peaceful industry to the national defence have not arrested the plow, the shuttle or the ship. The ax has enlarged the borders of our settlements, and the mines, as well of iron and coal as of the precious metals, have yielded even more abundantly than heretofore. Population has steadily increased, notwithstanding the waste that has been made in the camp, the siege and the battle-field; and the country, rejoicing in the consciousness of augmented strength and vigor, is permitted to expect a continuance of years with large increase of freedom.

abstract: Delegation, the, a radical nuisance
snippet: Delegation, the, a radical nuisance
lead_paragraph: The friends of the Administration in this City who unfortunately gave countenance to the "Missouri delegation" of so-called "radicals," who laid their story before the public last Friday night, should make haste to wash their hands of the association. And the "loyal people of Missouri," if they have any cause of grievance at Washington, should send persons to represent them who have at least equal courage with more discretion, equal earnestness with a deeper attachment to the Constitution, and an intelligent devotion to the Union. We confess to amazement at the position they placed themselves in on Friday night.

abstract: The reply of Princh GORTSCHAKOFF to Earl RUSSILL's last dispatch is published in to-night's Gazette, dated Sept 7. Prince GOETSCHAKOFF says: From the moment that this discussion could only end in establishing and in confirming the divergence of our views. It would be too contrary to our conciliatory disposition for us to seek to prolong it. He professes to share in the desire of the British Government for the reestablishment in Poland of a state of things which shall restore tranquility; and the Emperor, he says, continues to be animated by the most benevolent intentions toward Poland. The dispatch concludes as follows: "As regards the responsibility which may be assumed by his Majesty in his international relations, those relations are regulated by public right; the violation of those fundamental principles can alone involve responsibility. Our august master has constantly respected and observed those principles with regard to other States; his Majesty has the right to expect and to claim the same respect on the part of the other Powers."

abstract: The steamer George Washington, from New-Orleans Sept. 26, bringing four days' later news, arrived yesterday. The Era states that on Sunday morning, the 13th ult., at 9 o'clock, the gunboats Calhoun, Jackson and Genesee, which had the day before run ashore and destroyed the steamer Fox, were headed for Grant's Pass, near Mobile, and at 11 o'clock A.M. they were within two miles of the fort. Near the fort was the rebel iron-clad gunboat Gaines, long TOM HUNTER, Commander, and a steam transport. The Genesee opened with her famous 100 pound Parrott, and soon the rebel commander was compelled to retire behind the Fort to save his vessels.

abstract: Militia, where is the
snippet: Militia, where is the
lead_paragraph: Sophistry, in lieu of argument, has been exhausted upon every phase of a question that lies in the compass of a few words. It is upon the decision as to what constitutes the militia of the States that all action in reference to the conscription law must turn. Let it be admitted at starting, for the purpose of giving the adversaries of the law something on which to hang an argument, that if our national troops, raised within their respective States, can be shown as the militia of those States, then, to a certain degree, their relations to the State executives will vary.

abstract: In detaining the two war steamers building in the Mersey, till further inquiries can be made respecting their ownership and destination, the Government have done no more than given another conspicuous evidence of their prudent resolve to maintain a strict neutrality between the two belligerent parties across the Atlantic. These vessels are not to be supposed to have been condemned according to the powers conferred by the Foreign Entistment act.
lead_paragraph: In detaining the two war steamers building in the Mersey, till further inquiries can be made respecting their ownership and destination, the Government have done no more than given another conspicuous evidence of their prudent resolve to maintain a strict neutrality between the two belligerent parties across the Atlantic. These vessels are not to be supposed to have been condemned according to the powers conferred by the Foreign Entistment act. They are retained for further inquiry. Every one acquainted with the law, knows full well that it is only upon evidence produced by the complaining parties, that is to say, sufficient evidence, that the authorities are empowered to act in subjecting an an armed ship to the chances of condemnation before a competent tribunal. The Alexandra was subjected to this ordeal. Chief Baron POLLOCK decided that the evidence upon which the Custom-house authorities had proceeded in the case of the Alexandra was not sufficient, according to law, for her condemnation. This decision has been appealed against, and until this appeal shall be decided in the next term, it would be a serious matter to proceed against any other vessel or vessels without some more legal and conclusive evidence than that produced in the case that is pending for adjudication. But the mere detention of a vessel -- to await further inquiry -- is quite another question. Without waiting for complete evidence, or without any official intimation whether such evidence has or has not been obtained, there seems to be enough of mystery about the two suspected steamers at Birkenhead to call for the suspension of any permission for them to put to sea previous to any doubts being cleared up. It is to be observed that the builders have not been anxious to give any very precise information as to the future of the steamers in question. In the absence of such information, and in the presence of the fact that other vessels have left the same ship-building yard to prey upon the commerce of the Untied States, it is not too much stress of authority on the part of the Government to delay the departure from the Mersey of those suspected vessels until such time as a full and fair inquiry shall be made as to their purpose and destination.

abstract: It has already been mentioned that ROSECRANS' army is being reinforced from Gen. GRANT's department. It is a long distance to transport troops, and the undertaking is accompanied necessarily with much expense and tedious movement. With Vicksburgh as the starting point, there are, first, 347 miles of steam-boating to Memphis, and next the soldiers must embark on the Memphis and Charleston Railroad. The distance from Memphis to Chattanooga is 309 miles, but the road is not in operation throughout the whole length. Trains run regularly to Corinth and Julia, the latter 115 miles out, but it is not unlikely that a large force may have opened the road as far as Decatur, some seventy miles further east. There should, too, by this time, be railroad communication between Stevenson and Chattanooga, by means of the Nashville and Central Road, the distance between these two places being thirty-seven miles. But we can hardly reckon on more than say two hundred miles, if so much, of railroad transportation between Memphis and Chattanooga. Our readers may form an idea from this of the length of time required to transfer soldiers from the Army of the Tennessee to the Army of the Cumberland. It is proper to remark that the movement began several days ago, even before there had been any battle between ROSECRANS and BRAGG.

abstract: Encouraging reports continue to reach us from Gen ROSECEANS. A dispatch from the Army of the Camberland, dated yesterday, states that the present and future prospect of success for the army is not only brightening, but really good, and that if BRAGG attacks, he will most likely be de-...
lead_paragraph: Encouraging reports continue to reach us from Gen ROSECEANS. A dispatch from the Army of the Camberland, dated yesterday, states that the present and future prospect of success for the army is not only brightening, but really good, and that if BRAGG attacks, he will most likely be defeated. Every day's delay adds to the strength of our position, and increases the efficiency of our troops, who are now abundantly supplied with provisions and ammunition, and are full of confidence. Additional information makes it no longer a matter of surprise that the shattered battalions of the enemy do not again offer battle. Their losses were far more severe than was at first believed, and the success of the brave Gen. THOMAS on the left was much greater than has been published. He routed LONGSTREET's corps and would have pursued and destroyed it had it not been for the partial demoralization of our own right wing. Our losses are stated by the latest official estimate to have been in killed 1,800, wounded 9,500, and prisoners 2,500. Many of our wounded have recently been recovered under flag of truce.

abstract: -- Capt. J. MACDUFF, Aid-de-Camp to Maj.-Gen. SICKLES, has resigned his commission in the army on account of ill-health contracted in the army. His resignation has been accepted, and he has an honorable discharge from the service. Capt. MACDUFF has been with the Army of the Potomac through all its campaigns. Before attaching himself to the Staff of Gen. SICKLES, he was one of our correspondents on the Peninsula with Gen. MCCLELLAN, and from his pen came some of the best descriptions of the great battles and marches that intervened between the siege of Yorktown and the retreat to Harrison's Landing. Capt. MACDUFF is an able writer and a brave soldier, and the service and the Press both lose by his detachment from the army.

abstract: The Political Feelings in America
snippet: The Political Feelings in America
lead_paragraph: Allow me to bring to your memory the following facts of similarity and dissimilarity of political confederation between the United States of America and the Confederate States of Germany. The socalled Germanic Confederation includes about forty States, counting four free cities, all under the control of a Germanic Diet or Congress, the Emperor of Austria being its President, and meeting at Frankforton-the-Main. Each State has its own King or Grand Duke, who reigns over it in almost absolute monarchy, with all the paraphernalia of the throne and sceptre, supported by taxing the common people, who have no influence in making the laws. Even in the democratic free cities, no one can vote until he has a certain fixed amount of property. These German States vary in size and population from 18,912 to only 53 square miles in area, with population from about 12,000,000 down to 6,000. Many of these States, in extent and revenue, are inferior to the estate of even a second-class English nobleman. Yet the petty Prince by which it is ruled maintains all the forms of empty pomp and state of Imperial Sovereigns. They have Ministers, an exchequer, a public debt, an array, all in miniature, each petty Prince thinking only of promoting his own separate interests. The nobles retain much of the old feudal habits, and the masses of the Germans are rigidly excluded from Court or titled intercourse, and are taxed to support the Royal Court, and when the State is a very little one, with a diminutive population, it is particularly oppressive to the poor. A liberally educated German relates, that in cherry season, a certain weight of cherries only was allowed him every morning for his breakfast before going to school; at the same time, the garden vegetables and dried sausages, &c., &c., were packed off to go to support Court pomp, as they had no money to pay the tax bill. All must work for that. Their States consist of, as it were, little military monarchies, aiming to suppress popular influences and limiting certain liberties of the Press, &c. In some of the States, the peasants are in a condition approaching personal bondage.

abstract: -- The Writers to be Sent Beyond the Federal Lines. -- Yesterday morning Lieut. BACKUS, of the Provost Guard, was detailed to arrest Mrs. ELIZABETH KANE and her daughter, Miss CLARA KANE, residing at No. 225 Franklin-street, on the charge of corresponding with her son, who is in the Confederate army. It appears that several days since letters from both Mrs. K. and her daughter were intercepted and sent to Col. FISH, Military Provost-Marshal, and he ordered the arrest of the ladies. The following are extracts from the letters which were intercepted: "We are delighted with the news from BRAGG's army. I do hope he will entirely destroy ROSECRANS' army. I pray we may have success everywhere." * * * "I am glad you did not give way to your inclination to visit home. If you could only realize the cruelty of our eniemies you would not expose yourself to capture; and I could not enjoy your visit much at such a hazard. We hope when you and our friends do come it will be in triumph. I never cease praying for you and your companions. We kept President DAVIS' fast day, &c. JOHNNY has gone to London to join the Confederate fleet, as Midshipman. Your uncle is in Canada, and I do not think he will return until the war is over. We are all anxiously awaiting that glorious day when the C.S.A. will march through our streets as conquerors, and in triumph. I feel sure that the Yankees will never take Charleston. They, with their usual braggadocia, say it is only a question of time -- that it is as good as taken, and such like stuff; but we all know how veracious Yankees are. How grieved you must be at losing your old commander, FITZ LEE. His parting address is perfectly beautiful -- short, but affectionate, and to the point. What an honor and pleasure to be under such men. You must write as soon as you get this, and tell me any little anecdote you may think of. With much love, and three cheers for the C.S.A., I am yours, affectionately, &c."

We hope when you and our friends do come it will be in triumph. I never cease praying for you and your companions. We kept President DAVIS' fast day, &c. JOHNNY has gone to London to join the Confederate fleet, as Midshipman. Your uncle is in Canada, and I do not think he will return until the war is over. We are all anxiously awaiting that glorious day when the C.S.A. will march through our streets as conquerors, and in triumph. I feel sure that the Yankees will never take Charleston. They, with their usual braggadocia, say it is only a question of time -- that it is as good as taken, and such like stuff; but we all know how veracious Yankees are. How grieved you must be at losing your old commander, FITZ LEE. His parting address is perfectly beautiful -- short, but affectionate, and to the point. What an honor and pleasure to be under such men. You must write as soon as you get this, and tell me any little anecdote you may think of. With much love, and three cheers for the C.S.A., I am yours, affectionately, &c."

abstract: If there be truth in the statement of Gen. LEE, published by the Richmond papers, to the effect that two army corps have been transferred from the Army of the Potomac to reinforce ROSECRANS, the fact presents a striking illustration of the prodigious areas over which the theatre of war is now extended.
lead_paragraph: If there be truth in the statement of Gen. LEE, published by the Richmond papers, to the effect that two army corps have been transferred from the Army of the Potomac to reinforce ROSECRANS, the fact presents a striking illustration of the prodigious areas over which the theatre of war is now extended. The distance to be traveled over by troops passing from the Army of the Potomac to the Army of the Cumberland is not less than a thousand miles. The rebels, by the advantage of interior lines, have between their army in Virginia and that in Northern Georgia an interval of but half that distance. The severing of the Virginia and East Tennessee Railroad, however, obliges them, in reinforcing from LEE to BRAGG, to make a great detour by way of Branchville, or by Charleston and Atlanta, which brings the distance to hardly less than eight hundred miles.

abstract: The radicals of on slavery and the war
snippet: The radicals of on slavery and the war
lead_paragraph: The "radical" preachers from Missouri belong to that class of men who prefer the immediate destruction of Slavery to the salvation of the Union. They are not opposed to the Union; on the contrary, their proclaimed purpose is to secure and uphold it. But they will not have it with Slavery, or any shred or sign of Slavery anywhere within its limits. Universal abolition is their condition precedent to the stoppage of the war, precedent to reconstruction. They claim for themselves and their party the exclusive title of loyalists, and the exclusive characteristic of loyalty. They denounce all who differ from them and their creed as traitors, Copperheads, sympathizers with the rebellion. They accuse the President of favoring "Pro-Slaveryism, which is but a modified form of secession." They accuse the Government of "throwing its influence in favor of slaveholders, guerrillas and bushwhackers." They accuse Gov. GAMBLE of appointing Pro-Slavery Provost-Marshals. They accuse Gen. SCHOFIELD of appointing slaveholders as officers in the enrolled soldiery of the State. They accuse the Provost-Marshals of sustaining the "policy of GAMBLE."

abstract: The regular Fall season of Italian Opera commences to-night, under the able direction of Mr. MAX MARETZEK. A comparatively unknown opera will be revived for the occasion "Roberto Devereux" receiving from the management the full honors of new scenery and costumes and a distribution which we are certain cannot be greatly exceeded in any opera house of the world.
lead_paragraph: The regular Fall season of Italian Opera commences to-night, under the able direction of Mr. MAX MARETZEK. A comparatively unknown opera will be revived for the occasion -- "Roberto Devereux" -- receiving from the management the full honors of new scenery and costumes and a distribution which we are certain cannot be greatly exceeded in any opera house of the world. It would be difficult to find two roles that are more admirably adapted to the great powers of Mme. MEDORI and Signor MAZZOLENI than those of Elizabeth and Roberto Devereux. Not only does the music suit their voices, but the dramatic opportunities are very great, and will afford ample scope for good acting. The mezzo-soprano and baritone parts are also admirable. Indeed, there are not many operas in the Italian repertoire where the vocal quartette is better provided for. As the argument of the opera may not be remembered by our readers, we condense it for their use. The scene is laid in England during the reign of Queen ELIZABETH, and the story is based on a love episode of the Virgin Queen. Roberto Devereux, Earl of Essex, is her favorite. She has bestowed on him many marks of favor, and given him a ring which is to rescue him from peril, should he ever be overtaken by his enemies. The Earl unhappily does not reciprocate the Queen's tender emotions; he having in early life been fondly attached to the Lady Sara, who afterward, to avoid the royal displeasure, became the wife of Devereux's friend, the Duke of Nottingham. A cabal has attempted the destruction of the Queen's favorite. He is accused of high treason, and summoned from Ireland to be tried by his peers. In an interview with his sovereign, he is charged with coldness and inconstancy, but at the same time is assured of protection. The ring will be his safeguard. Instead of resting satisfied with this state of affairs, the Earl has a scene with his old sweetheart, the Duchess of Nottingham, who advises him to seek safety in flight. This the Earl consents to do, and as a pledge of affection, gives her the ring, confiding to her at the same time the promise attached to it. He receives from the Duchess a scarf, embroidered with her own hands. The Earl does not make good his escape. He is tried, found guilty and sentenced to death. This is not the worst. The fatal scarf has been found in his possession, and conveyed to the Queen, who at once recognizes it as a gage d'amour. The Duke, too, remembers the scarf, and becomes horribly jealous, so that when Elizabeth, in a fit of rage, has signed the Earl's death-warrant, he hurries off revengefully to put it into immediate execution. In this emergency, the Duchess resolves to see the Queen. She produces the ring for the purpose of imploring the royal clemency, and the Queen is overwhelmed with remorse at having signed the fatal warrant. She is eager to remit the sentence, but it is too late. The Duke has hurried up the arrangements for disposing of his rival, and the signal gun from Tower Hill announces that the Earl is no more. The Queen is frantic with despair, declares that the Duke and the Duchess shall lose their heads, and that she will abdicate the throne. Here the opera ends.

abstract: The year that is drawing toward its close has been filled with the blessings of fruitful fields and healthful skies. To these bounties, which are so constantly enjoyed that we are prone to forget the Source from which they come, others have been added, ...
lead_paragraph: The year that is drawing toward its close has been filled with the blessings of fruitful fields and healthful skies. To these bounties, which are so constantly enjoyed that we are prone to forget the Source from which they come, others have been added, which are of so extraordinary a nature that they cannot fail to penetrate and soften even the heart which is habitually insensible to the ever-watchful providence of Almighty God. In the midst of a civil war of unequaled magnitude and severity, which has sometimes seemed to invite and provoke the aggressions of foreign States, peace has been preserved with all nations, order has been maintained, the laws have been respected and obeyed, and harmony has prevailed everywhere, except in the theatre of military conflict, while that theatre has been greatly contracted by the advancing armies and navies of the Union. The needful diversion of wealth and strength from the fields of peaceful industry to the national defence have not arrested the plow, the shuttle or the ship. The ax has enlarged the borders of our settlements, and the mines, as well of iron and coal as of the precious metals, have yielded even more abundantly than heretofore. Population has steadily increased, notwithstanding the waste that has been made in the camp, the siege and the battle-field; and the country, rejoicing in the consciousness of augmented strength and vigor, is permitted to expect a continuance of years with large increase of freedom.

At no time since the beginning of the war has there been a fiercer determination displayed in the rebel counsels to make no terms with the North than now.

abstract: ARREST OF AN ESCAPED CONVICT. -- On Saturday afternoon Detective FARLEY arrested a man named CHAS. ROGERS, a convicted felon, who recently made his escape from a penitentiary at Louisville, Ky. ROGERS is represented as a desperate fellow, and had a term of several years to serve when he broke jail. Gov. ROBINSON, of Kentucky, and the jailor of the penitentiary where ROGERS had been confined, each offered a reward of $100 for his apprehension. The Governor's proclamation, together with the carte de visite of the felon and a full description of his person, were forwarded to this City, and after much effort his arrest was effected. At first he denied that he was the person alluded to in the proclamation, but after being confined a short time at Police Headquarters he confessed his guilt. He was sent back to Louisville on a requisition from the Governor of Kentucky.

abstract: Tammany and the war
snippet: Tammany and the war
lead_paragraph: Two broadly defined parties exist in the Democracy of this City. The one, led by FERNANDO WOOD, clamors for "peace" with the rebel States. "Peace at any price" is practically their motto. To this end, they would proclaim an armistice -- not knowing whether the rebels would regard it or not -- recall our armies from their advanced positions in the Southern States -- yield all territory we have conquered -- send back all slaves that have left their masters, and then ask the rebels to meet us in "National Convention," and name what modifications of the Constitution of the United States they would accept, as the condition of living again in the Union! It is in vain that we point to the fact that the rebel Government scorn and spit upon all this talk of peace and reunion, and declare that no terms of peace except such as recognize the final and absolute independence of the South will ever be entertained. Our Peace Democrats reply that war has not restored and cannot restore the Union -- and that if negotiations fail to do it, the work must be given up as impossible. Inasmuch, then, as the rebels will have no negotiation, unless preceded by dissolution, this party, of necessity, become disunionists -- for disunion is the only condition of "peace" as they demand it.

abstract: Strategy and the War
snippet: Strategy and the War
lead_paragraph: The result of the military operations during the last three months proves in a very pointed way the theory which we have long maintained, that the main, though not the sole obstacle, we admit to the suppression of the rebellion, lies in the existence of rebel armies in the field, rather than in their possession of certain strategical points. We were, we believe, the first, a year ago, to call attention to this fact, at a time when the public mind was so intent upon the capture of Richmond that there was a very general impression afloat that the fall of that place would terminate the war. The exaggerated importance which was ascribed, at the begining of the struggle, to the possession of certain places, was due to a very natural tendency to apply to our operations rules deduced from European military history, in which the capture of a city or fall of a fortress very frequently has determined the fate of a whole province or kingdom. To occupy Paris, or Vienna and Berlin, is, in European warfare, to obtain complete mastery of France, or Austria and Prussia, and we hence not unreasonably concluded that in this, as in other things, "haute strategie" in America resembled "haute strategie" in the Old World.

abstract: In the Board of Aldermen yesterday, the resolution vetoed by the Mayor, directing the Comptroller to sell at public auction for a period of five years, the slips at Piers Nos. 32 and 33, E.R., for ferry purposes, was called up and read.
lead_paragraph: In the Board of Aldermen yesterday, the resolution vetoed by the Mayor, directing the Comptroller to sell at public auction for a period of five years, the slips at Piers Nos. 32 and 33, E.R., for ferry purposes, was called up and read. The resolution was adopted notwithstanding the Mayor's objections. A resolution was adopted, giving permission to the Hudson River Railroad Company to use a dummy on their road from the Chambers-street depot to Thirty-second-street, the Company to pay the sum of $50 as license on each engine or dummy so used. The Corporation Counsel sent in a communication in response to a resolution of inquiry adopted by this Board, asking if he had taken any steps to have the injunction dissolved, served upon this Board, prohibiting them from taking action upon the $3,000,000 ordinance Relief fund. He states that he has received no papers upon which he could take any action. The Committee on Finances reported in favor of donating $1,000 to the widow of the late GEO. W. BADGER, Ex-Foreman of Engine Company No. 19, who was killed at the fire in Cherry-street, which was adopted.

lead_paragraph: The Union men throughout the State are selecting very excellent candidates for members of the Legislature. In the Clinton and Essex District (Fourteenth) they have nominated P.E. HAVENS, Esq., a young lawyer of marked ability, unspotted character and considerable legislative experience. He has served two terms in the Assembly with great credit to himself and his constituents. He has a clear logical mind, speaks with force, fluency and effect, and is never diverted from substantial and practical good sense in his treatment of public questions, by vague speculation or a desire for temporary applause. We trust there is not the slightest doubt of his election by a large majority.

abstract: The New-Or  leans Times is the name of a new Union journal just started in the Crescent City. It comes to us elegantly printed, on fine paper, with full and clear reports of local matters, and sharp, sensible editorials on all the topics of the day.
lead_paragraph: -- The New-Orleans Times is the name of a new Union journal just started in the Crescent City. It comes to us elegantly printed, on fine paper, with full and clear reports of local matters, and sharp, sensible editorials on all the topics of the day. It is thoroughly and heartily loyal, is written in good English, and does not mistake coarse vulgarity and rhetorical clap-trap for strength of argument or earnestness of purpose. It understands apparently how to discuss questions of grave public concern with dignity and candor, and can also differ from an opponent without branding him as a felon, or denouncing him as an idiot. So far as we can judge from the few numbers thus far issued, its editor seems capable of being firm in principle without being violent in temper, and he does not deem it necessary to go into paroxysms of wrath in order to convince the public of his own sincerity, or of his opponent's errors. Perhaps, if we had thought of it in season, we might have saved ourselves the trouble of this analysis by copying the statement of the New-Orleans correspondent of the Tribune, that in style and tone, as well as in its typographical appearance, the New-Orleans Times is a very accurate reproduction of its New-York namesake. That, we presume, tells the whole story: but it may not be amiss to add that it is edited by J.R. HAMILTON, Esq., a gentleman of ability, an accomplished scholar, a man of conscience and character, and, to crown this catalogue of his virtues, the special correspondent of the NEW-YORK TIMES.

abstract: Mr. MARETZEK'S opening night was as brilliant as the most sanguine of mangagers could have expected or desired. The house was completely crowded, and the opera of "Roberto Devereux " passed off with ectat.
lead_paragraph: Mr. MARETZEK's opening night was as brilliant as the most sanguine of mangagers could have expected or desired. The house was completely crowded, and the opera of "Roberto Devereux " passed off with ectat. The manager is to be congratulated on these results. He has endeavored -- and we hope with permanent success -- to reform the old method of conducting matters. Instead of deluging the City with puffs of indifferent singers, he has engaged a first-class company, and left to the public the task of deciding upon their respective merits. The experiment, so far, bas been singularly successful. All Mr. MARETZEK's artists have been received with tumultuous favor, and although there was no preliminary flourish of trumpets anent the opening night, and not even a ghost to arrest the public attention, the house was, as we have previously stated, completely filled.

abstract: We have long blamed England, because compelled. The unfairness of her Government and of her ruling classes, toward our country in its day of adversity, has made it impossible for any true American to speak well of her.
lead_paragraph: We have long blamed England, because compelled. The unfairness of her Government and of her ruling classes, toward our country in its day of adversity, has made it impossible for any true American to speak well of her. The injury was too flagrant, the motive too palpable. Yet our indignation has always been mingled with sorrow. There has been no getting rid of the feeling that England ought to have stood by our people closer than ever in their resistance of this monstrous attempt of Slavery against their national life. England was bound to this by every moral obligation, every sentiment of honor, every line of her Anti-Slavery record. Had she thus kept true, it would have cemented a moral alliance between the two nations, such as the world has never yet seen. Their affinity in blood, in language, in religion,would have been deepened into an infinitely warmer and worthier brotherhood. They would thenceforth have stood forth as the paired pioneers of the world's march, twin champions of all that is free and grand, the very Castor and Pollux of the nations. It is a calamity to the race that England has so greatly failed in the part so plainly imposed upon her by Providence. The material embarrassments and mischiefs occasioned by her neutral policy, falsely so called, are of small consequence compared with the moral rupture that has resulted. The material harm is but limited. It has hindered us, but it has not thwarted us. Inspite of it, we are now close upon final and glorious success. But though the physical effects of what England has done, and has failed to do, are passing away, the moral effects remain. The waters of the Atlantic have closed over the Harvey Birch and the Jacob Bell; and so might we wish that the waters of oblivion could close over the British faithlessness that caused it. But it is vain to wish. It is not in human nature that this thing should be.
