abstract: By the arrival at this port yesterday of the steamers City of London, Glasgow and Sidon, we have files of foreign journals to the 24th ult. The news is one day later than that brought by the Saxonia, and telegraphed from Cape Race.
lead_paragraph: By the arrival at this port yesterday of the steamers City of London, Glasgow and Sidon, we have files of foreign journals to the 24th ult. The news is one day later than that brought by the Saxonia, and telegraphed from Cape Race. It is now positively asserted that MAXIMILIAN has accepted the Mexican Crown at all risks and perils, renouncing his rights and prerogatives as the nearest collateral Prince to the throne of Austria. The Times assumes that Great Britain will acknowledge and favor the new regime in Mexico. The reply of Prince GORTSCHAKOFF to the French and Austrian notes on the Polish question has been published, together with accompanying memoranda. These replies manifest the same firm tone as that addressed to England. Relative to the allusion made M. DROUYN DE LHUYS to the Western Provinces of Russia, as participating in the international stipulations which settled in 1815 the destiny of Warsaw. Prince GORTSCHAKOFF maintains that the Imperial Cabinet cannot admit that point of view, even in the most restricted manner. Russia will not admit the right of Europe to interfere in her internal affairs. It is said that Count RECHBERG, the Austrian minister, has advised that no response be made to Prince GORTSCHAKOFF's dispatch, but that the three great Powers now await further action on the part of the Russian Government toward the Poles. The Paris Moniteur has reproduced the letter from Warsaw of Aug. 15, addressed by the Polish National Government to Prince CZARTOVISKY, claiming belligerent rights, and its publication in the French official organ is considered by English and continental journals as equivalent to an unofficial recognition by NAPOLEON of the Polish National Government. Russia was actively engaged in warlike preparations. American topics were still greatly discussed in England, but there was a general admission, even by those journals which have been most strongly pro-Southern, that the rebel cause showed signs of utter ruin. The Confederate loan had again declined to 30@28 per cent. discount. The pirate Alabama, according to St. Helena advices of Aug. 6, had boarded the ship Havelock, off the Cape of Good Hope, and reported that she had captured a bark to the eastward of the Cape and fitted her out as a privateer, also that the Georgia was with her. The steamer Great Eastern had been withdrawn from the American trade for the present. The Liverpool Cotton market closed easier and at weak prices. The Breadstuffs and Provision markets were steady and few transactions taking place. Consols closed at 93 1/4@93 5/8 for money.

abstract: The London Times is greatly  shocked at sundry inconsistencies which it professes to have discovered in President LINCOLN's declarations of opinion and of policy during the past two years.
lead_paragraph: -- The London Times is greatly shocked at sundry inconsistencies which it professes to have discovered in President LINCOLN's declarations of opinion and of policy during the past two years. The Times was always very sensitive on the subject of consistency. As it never changes its own opinions, never in the slightest degree adapts its policy to the emergencies or interests of the moment, and always clings tenaciously to whatever opinion it once utters, it is quite natural that any one who pursues a different course should incur its distrust and censure. Upon one point, however, Mr. LINCOLN has certainly been consistent; he has never earned the praise or escaped the denunciation of the Times. He may have wavered and possibly changed in other matters -- but in this he has been firm. And it is only fair to add that in this, and in nothing else, the Times has been consistent also.

LEE of his campaign in Maryland and Pennsylvania, in June and July, was published in the Richmond papers of Saturday last, and it is, says the Richmond Examiner, "the first official report of Gen. LEE's many military operations which the public has been permitted to see." It clears up several points which have heretofore been but little understood, but leaves untouched many of the most interesting problems connected with the Northern invasion. As the rebel commander's view of that campaign, it is deeply interesting, especially as this is the first official report of it we have had, Gen. MEADE's not yet having been published:

abstract: The October Term of this Court opened at 10 o'clock yesterday morning, before Judge BARNARD. The roll of Grand Jurors was called, but not enough answering the summons to form a quorum, those present were discharged until Wednesday morning. The list of Petit Jurors was called through and a large number were sworn. At the suggestion of District-Attorney HALL, the Court ordered an additional pannel of 75 Petit Jurors to be summoned, in contemplation of the right of challenge being fully exercised, as there was a large number of capital cases on the calendar. None of the cases on the day calendar being ready for trial, the Court adjourned to 10 o'clock this morning. Many of the riot cases that were transferred to this Court from the Court of Sessions will doubtless be sent back to the latter Court for trial during the Term.

abstract: Report of Pennsylvania and Maryland Invasion
snippet: Report of Pennsylvania and Maryland Invasion
lead_paragraph: The specific object of LEE's Summer invasion of Pennsylvania was a matter of profound mystery and endless speculation at the time; and the mystery is not perfectly cleared up by his official report of that campaign, which has just seen the light at Richmond, and which we give in full this morning. It was thought by some that the gigantic army of the rebels, whose numbers were accurately stated by a reliable City cotemporary at 190,375, meant nothing less than the capture of Washington and Baltimore, the capture of Philadelphia and Pittsburgh, the capture of New-York and Boston, and, for that matter, the capture of Cincinnati and Rouse's Point. With Panic preceding them, Death accompanying them, and Desolation following in their wake, there seemed no reason why they should not work their will and wreak their vengeance upon the North; and those who remember the history of that time will recall how the Tribune proposed to placate them in advance, and to "bow to destiny," as impersonated in JEFF. DAVIS, in event of their "watering their horses in the Delaware."

abstract: AN EXTENSIVE THEFT A COUNTRYMAN ROBBED By a WOMAN. At an early hour yesterday morning Mr. HIRAM S. TERRELL, of Danbury, Conn., made his appearance at Police Headquarters, where he stated that on Sunday he was robbed of about the sum of $15,000 in money and drafts by two women, whose ...
lead_paragraph: AN EXTENSIVE THEFT -- A COUNTRYMAN ROBBED By a WOMAN. -- At an early hour yesterday morning Mr. HIRAM S. TERRELL, of Danbury, Conn., made his appearance at Police Headquarters, where he stated that on Sunday he was robbed of about the sum of $15,000 in money and drafts by two women, whose names he gave as Mrs. LAURA and ROSA WELSH, both of whom, he said, reside at No. 12 Greene-street. Detective SLOWEY was at once dispatched in search of the guilty parties, and after much effort he succeeded in taking into custody Mrs. LAURA, (who gave her name as CAROLINE BUCKMAN,) ROSA WELSH and the housekeeper of the establishment, whose name is LEWIS SEYMOUR. They were all taken to Police Headquarters, and subsequently ROSA WELSH was arraigned before Justice STEERS at the Essex Market Police Court. Mr. TERRELL there made an affidavit in which he claimed that he had lost only $5,450. The money consisted, he said, of a $1,000 Treasury note, one $50 Treasury note, two United States notes of $20 each; also, bank bills on various State banks for $200, four drafts of $1,000 each on the Pahquoe Bank, of Danbury, Conn., and one diamond ring, worth $160. Mr. TERRELL swears that on Sunday last he took a carriage at the Northern Hotel, in this City, where he was temporarily stopping, went up to Greene-street, where he secured a companion -- ROSA WELSH -- and with her he rode to Luff's Hotel, in Harlem-lane. Soon after reaching the latter place he discovered that all his money and drafts were gone. Mrs. LAURA, as the complainant alleges, came up in her carriage and took ROSA away. None of the money has been recovered. The accused were held for examination, wa[???][???][???] will take place on Wednesday morning, at the Essex Count.

abstract: The October term of this Court opened yesterday morning with the trial of Dr. EDWARD M. BROWN, indicted for murder in the second degree, in causing the death of CLEMENTINA ANDERSON, on the 19th of November last by means of an abortion. The circumstances of this case were very fully developed on the Coroner's inquest, and are doubtless still familiar to most readers of the newspapers. The case was brought on for trial in April last before Judge BARNARD, when, after half the jury were sworn, they were discharged, and the case postponed by order of the Court. A point of law was thereupon raised by defendant's counsel, H.L. CLINTON, Esq., that Dr. BROWN had been once placed in jeopardy, and could not be tried again. This point was decided against the prisoner after a very full argument before Recorder HOFFMAN. The Doctor has been confined in the Tombs since his first arrest, all applications for bail having been refused. Considerable difficulty was found yesterday in obtaining an unbiased jury, and the Court was obliged to adjourn without obtaining the full number. The Court ordered a new panel to be summoned for 10 1/2 o'clock this morning, when the trial will doubtless proceed, as only four more jurors are required. Dr. BROWN is defended by H.L. CLINTON, Esq., and Ex-Judge STUART, and District-Attorney HALL conducts the case for the people.

abstract: At the opening of the Court yesterday morning WM. STRATTON was placed at the bar, charged with being engaged in the riots in July last. The prisoner pleaded guilty, and his counsel asked for a suspension of sentence on the ground that the prisoner ...
lead_paragraph: At the opening of the Court yesterday morning, WM. STRATTON was placed at the bar, charged with being engaged in the riots in July last. The prisoner pleaded guilty, and his counsel asked for a suspension of sentence on the ground that the prisoner was not one of the original rioters, but was led into joining the mob on the second or third day of the riots -- he having unfortunately indulged too freely in liquor. The particular act charged against him was assisting to tear up the track of the Fourth-avenue Railroad. Judge HARVARD refused to suspend sentence, but in consideration of the fact that the prisoner had pleaded guilty, and thereby saved the Court the trouble of trying him, and also of the fact that he had previously sustained a good character, he would sentence him to only six months in the Penitentiary. The Judge remarked to the prisoner that he had been engaged in the riots of July last, which were the most outrageous and disgraceful that had ever occurred in this country. Had there been any loss of life or great destruction of property attending his offence, he would not have escaped a long term in the State Prison; and he would here take occasion to remark, that all offenders who had been engaged in the commission of those higher crimes, if they were convicted before him, might expect to have meted out to them the full penalty of the law.

abstract: The Tax Receiver began to receive the taxes on personal estate on Monday, when over $79,000 were paid in. Yesterday his office was thronged with people desiring to make payments, and $204,060 were received. The largest item paid by any one man was $30,000 from WM.B. ASTOR; the next largest was from PETER GILLETT - - $8,000. The receipts on the first two days last year amounted, respectively to $50,000 and $180,000. The increase shown this year speaks well of the ability of out citizens to pay their tax bills.

abstract: and Legal-Tenders
snippet: and Legal-Tenders
lead_paragraph: Some Of JUDGE SELDEN AND LEGAL TENDER. Some of our Democratic cotemporaries affect to be in great tribulation on account of Judge SELDEN's opinion against the constitutionality of the act of Congress making "greenbacks" a legal tender. They seem to think that friends of the Administration cannot vote for him. We do not see why not. To our minds, while we do not concur in the soundness of that opinion, the fact that he gave it, under all the circumstances of the case, against all the political temptations the other way, proves his preeminent fitness for the Bench. It is much more important to have Judges who will be independent and honest in the discharge of their duties than to have men whose opinions concur with those of any political party.

abstract: The New-York Typographical Society met on Saturday night, elected a new board of officers, and commenced operations under a constitution containing some new important features. Mr. WM. MCCREA, was elected President, and THEO. L.D. VINNE, of the firm of FRANCIS HART & Co., Vice-President. The other officers were reelected. A Board of Directors, to manage the business affairs of the institution was also chosen. Hereafter the meetings of the Society will partake more of the nature of literary reunions than heretofore. A plan of life membership, by which, publishers and other persons connected with the printers' art may join this time-honored institution, has been devised, and employing printers are already enrolling their names. In this respect the Typographical Society, though having a large membership of influential men, will enter upon a new career. The library and meeting rooms are at No. 3 Chambers-street, and are open to all printers.

No better or more effective document could possibly be circulated by the friends of the Union than this. Mr. LINCOLN has a wonderfully clear and precise way of stating his opinions on public topics: and these opinions are so uniformly and so distinctly marked by sound common sense, and by unselfish devotion to the public welfare, that they never fail to carry conviction wherever they are read. No better answer can possibly be given to the abuse of President LINCOLN than these letters afford.

lead_paragraph: The rebels appear to be making movements designed to give BURNSIDE some trouble. A dispatch from Nashville, dated Monday, states that a force of them on that day had destroyed the large bridge south of Murfreesboro. This pretty piece of enterprise, however, is not likely to be repeated. BURNSIDE's cavalry force is greatly superior in point of numbers and fighting qualities to that of WHEELER and, doubtless, will make its superiority felt. The rebel infantry have as much as they can attend to in watching the Army of the Cumberland.

abstract: Maffitt, Capt., and the Florida, the checkered career of
snippet: Maffitt, Capt., and the Florida, the checkered career of
lead_paragraph: One rarely sees a greater change in the aspect of a case than has been exhibited in the case of the rebel steamer Florida, since her arrival at Brest. When she first made her appearance there, she came flushed with the recent success of burning an American merchantman almost within sight of England; and the tongues and pens of the rebels and their friends in France and England were loud in glorification of her, her commander and her crew, and in congratulations upon her and their success. It was a picture of intense couleur de rose. Excited Englishmen visited her at Brest, and wrote to the London Times marine tales which were narrated to them by her Captain, who was described as "a merry-looking man, with a ready, determined air," "equally ready for a fight or a jollification," and whose corsair career was depicted as very much of a jollification, though without much fighting. Those of her crew who came on shore were reported to have their pockets filled with prize money, and their bags bursting with bonds given by captured merchantmen. The Opinion Nationale stated that every sailor was entitled to 45,000 francs as his share. Then followed the announcement that a part of her crew had been detached from her to join another vessel, thus leaving openings on board her for other jolly tars whose imaginations might have been fired by these golden tales, and who would be only too happy to jump at the chance of making thousands of dollars in this easy, speedy and safe way. And to crown the whole, the vessel was allowed to be repaired in the Government dock.

lead_paragraph: The Ninth regiment N.Y.S.N.G., Col. JOHN W. DAVIS, and the Draft Exemption Committee have come into collision. Some five or six of the regiment have been drafted, and those who have applied for relief under the provision which exempts "the regular members of the active militia," are summarily ruled out by Supervisor BLUNT, Chairman of the Committee, on the ground that the regiment is not uniformed, has not done any duty, and, to all intents and purposes, is not in existence. Those applying for relief, on being sworn, testify to not being uniformed and not having paraded in two years, and on such statements the above conclusion has been arrived at, and they are "bluntly" ruled out.

abstract: The Union of Mozart and Tammany is subject solely to the question of spoils. Mozart comes to its consideration rollicking and careless, Tammany tremulous and anxious.
lead_paragraph: The Union of Mozart and Tammany is subject solely to the question of spoils. Mozart comes to its consideration rollicking and careless, Tammany tremulous and anxious. Mozart is determined to have a full half, nothing short of that, and also to sacrifice in the arrangement not the smallest chip of its Peace platform. Tammany, who sees certain defeat in not conceding the terms demanded, is putting the best face it can upon the matter, and trying to swallow the following, which will probably be the division for County and City offices.

abstract: The New-York Historical Society held a meeting last evening at their rooms, corner of Second-avenue and Eleventh-street, commemorative of the late President of the Society, Hon. LUTHER BRADISH. A large audience was assembled. The meeting was called to order and presided over by Rev. Dr. DEWITT, the first Vice President of the Society, who, after alluding to his early friendship with Mr. BRADISH, and stating the purposes of the present meeting, called upon Hon. GULIAN C. VERPLANCK, who after alluding to the public services of the deceased, his varied accomplishments, his generous impulses and many benevolent characteristics, presented an elaborate series of resolutions, which in substance embodied his previous remarks.

abstract: A very respectable German left his house at Yonkers yesterday at noon, to procure in New-York medical aid for a sick wife. Not understanding English, he did not get information as to the character of the return train which he took, and was surprised to find himself driven through Yonkers at the rate of an express train. He kept his seat until the train passed Irvington, when, wrought up to the necessary rashness by the thought of his wife's anxiety for his return and need of his presence, he leaped from the train, struck on his feet, was dashed forward on his face, and escaped with some slight bruises on the face. Certainly a good Providence saved the poor fellow out of pity for his fearful devotion.
lead_paragraph: A very respectable German left his house at Yonkers yesterday at noon, to procure in New-York medical aid for a sick wife. abstract: The distinguished citizens of New-York whose names will be found appended to the letter given below, have extended an invitation to Gen. CHAS. K. GRAHAM, who has just returned from his captivity in ...
lead_paragraph: The distinguished citizens of New-York whose names will be found appended to the letter given below, have extended an invitation to Gen. CHAS. K. GRAHAM, who has just returned from his captivity in Richmond, to meet with them, and receive such honors as have been merited by his great services in the field; and the occasion will be signalized by a dinner at DELMONICO's (Fifth-avenue) this evening, at which Gen. GRAHAM will be present. No reader of the TIMES needs to be informed of the record made by Gen. GRAHAM from the time he left this City as Major of the first regiment of SICKLES' brigade -- two and a half years ago -- until the bloody but victorious day of Gettysburgh, in which he himself gallantly led and splendidly handled a brigade. Throughout, his career was worthy of an American soldier, and we can say no more than this. And his conduct when taken prisoner, and during his captivity, was no less honorable than his conduct in action. The names of the gentlemen who have tendered him this honor are a sufficient proof of the estimation in which he is held by his own City of New-York. Capt. MUGDUFF, formerly of the New-York Press, and latterly of Gen. SICKLES' Staff, is Chairman of the "Press Committee" on the occasion, and his name is a guarantee for the fit performance of his arduous duties. The invitation and response are as follows:

abstract: -- The young folks of our City are busy as possible at work for the Fair in aid of the "Union Home and School for the Education and Maintenance of the Children of our Volunteers." Each little pair of hands are assisted by kind hearts, and are really going to show us what little folks can do and what they will do for the orphans left by our brave soldiers. The Fair will open Monday, Oct. 26, and continue one week, at the City Assembly Rooms, No. 446 Broadway. The young folks are taking their offerings to the Union Home and School, while Societies and schools now engaged are requested to notify the Committee at the Union Home and School, Fifty-seventh-street, near Eighth-avenue, in order that tables may be assigned them, and rooms reserved for their articles.

abstract: The tele  gram, ("considered entirely reliable,") in reference to Gen. BURNSIDE'S position, will be read with great interest, as setting at rest ...
lead_paragraph: -The telegram, ("considered entirely reliable,") in reference to Gen. BURNSIDE's position, will be read with great interest, as setting at rest the thousand and one rumors which the rebels have favored us with in regard to his precarious position, his disasters, his retreats, &c. We do not say that his position is not precarious: for if he holds, as is asserted, the line of the East Tennessee Railroad from Greenville to Calhoun, a distance of at least 150 miles, his detachments must be widely scattered, and his lines very open to attack.

abstract: ARREST OF THE OFFENDER. -- An inquest was held yesterday on the body of JOHN E. MCKENZIE, who died at the New-York Hospital, from injuries received at the hands of JAMES CROSS. The facts of the case, as they appeared on the inquest, are as follows: On Sunday afternoon last, CROSS and the deceased met in the grocery-store of CONRAD HALSBERG, NO. 685 Water-street, where they had an altercation. After quarreling some time, the parties adjourned to the dock to have a fight. There the deceased struck CROSS a blow on the breast with his fist, whereupon the two clenched, and a severe struggle ensued, during which CROSS was seen to give deceased a heavy push in the side, but no knife was seen in his hand at the time. The deceased then threw up his hands, opened his vest, and exclaimed, "That man has stabbed me," and immediately fell to the ground. He was taken to the New-York Hospital, where he died yesterday morning. The wound inflicted was in the lower part of the abdomen. Immediately after committing the deed, CROSS held up the knife, which was dripping with the blond of his victim, and then suddenly started to run away. Officer BOYD, of the Thirteenth Precinct, started in pursuit, and after much effort, succeeded in arresting him. The knife with which the wound was inflicted was found on the person of the prisoner. When arrested, CROSS said: "I cut the man, but I did it in self-defence." Dr. FOSTER, House Surgeon of the Hospital, made a post-mortem examination of the body. He found two stab wounds in the lower part of the abdomen, either one of which were, in his judgment, sufficient to cause death. The jury rendered a verdict "that the deceased, JOHN E. lead_paragraph: ARREST OF THE OFFENDER. -- An inquest was held yesterday on the body of JOHN E. MCKENZIE, who died at the New-York Hospital, from injuries received at the hands of JAMES CROSS. The facts of the case, as they appeared on the inquest, are as follows: On Sunday afternoon last, CROSS and the deceased met in the grocery-store of CONRAD HALSBERG, NO. 685 Water-street, where they had an altercation. After quarreling some time, the parties adjourned to the dock to have a fight. There the deceased struck CROSS a blow on the breast with his fist, whereupon the two clenched, and a severe struggle ensued, during which CROSS was seen to give deceased a heavy push in the side, but no knife was seen in his hand at the time. The deceased then threw up his hands, opened his vest, and exclaimed, "That man has stabbed me," and immediately fell to the ground. He was taken to the New-York Hospital, where he died yesterday morning. The wound inflicted was in the lower part of the abdomen. Immediately after committing the deed, CROSS held up the knife, which was dripping with the blond of his victim, and then suddenly started to run away. Officer BOYD, of the Thirteenth Precinct, started in pursuit, and after much effort, succeeded in arresting him. The knife with which the wound was inflicted was found on the person of the prisoner. When arrested, CROSS said: "I cut the man, but I did it in self-defence." Dr. FOSTER, House Surgeon of the Hospital, made a post-mortem examination of the body. He found two stab wounds in the lower part of the abdomen, either one of which were, in his judgment, sufficient to cause death. The jury rendered a verdict "that the deceased, JOHN E. MCKENZIE, came to his death from a stab wound at the hands of JAMES CROSS, on the 4th day of October inst." The deceased was 33 years of age, and a native of Connecticut. The prisoner is 34 years of age, a machinist by occupation, and resided at No. 683 Water-street. Coroner NAUMANN committed him to the Tombs to await the action of the Grand Jury.

abstract: The Washington correspondent of the Philadelphia Ledger states that Government has been advised of a startling proceeding now said to be in course of execution; but there are few willing to credit the same. The matter, in a few words, is, that a leading ship-builder at New York is now (unknowingly, of course,) constructing a couple of powerful vessels-of-war, iron clad, which are really intended for the French in the prosecution of their designs upon this continent. The vessels are represented as being ordered by a different Power than France, and, if in reality for that Power, there is nothing against their construction in an American yard; but it is more than whispered that these vessels are ultimately intended for LOUIS NAPOLEON, and proof of it would seem to appear in the not unfrequent suggestions that are made to the builders by French officers purporting to act for the Italian Government.

abstract: The second performance of "Roberto Devereux" last evening was witnessed by an audience that lacked the numbers of the opening night, and was not superior in point of appreciation. The best morceauxwere missed; no one saw their point; no one seemed to know that they were the gems of the opera. Nevertheless there was a slightly warmer appreciation of the leading artists, who, we may here state, were in capital voice. Signor BELLINI fortunately was not in the caste, so there was no disappointment. His role was sustained -- and without rehearsal -- by Signor YPPOLITO. The effort was in every respect creditable to that artist.

lead_paragraph: Three days' later advices from Europe reached us yesterday by the arrival of the steamship Persia from Liverpool on the 26th and Queenstown on the 27th ultimo. The most important item of news relates to the alarming depredations of the rebel steamers Alabama and Georgia and the sailing pirate Conrad in the vicinity of the Cape of Good Hope. The first-named vessel had captured the American ships Sea Bride and Nela, and the second had taken the ship Prince of Wales in the vicinity of the Cape. The rebels were graciously received and feted by the British colonists, and the American Consul having protested against the capture of the Sea Bride, as achieved within British waters, was snubbed by the local Governor. The aggregate number of vessels captured or destroyed by the Alabama is stated to be fifty-six and by the Georgia fifteen. The Vanderbilt, of whose safety great fear has been entertained, is reported to have been at St. Helena on the 20th of August, leaving on that date in pursuit of the pirates. In our French exchanges we find the official report of the decision of the Bordeaux Tribunal of Commerce declaring the Alabama a belligerent vessel proper, and quashing the suit of the French merchants who had endeavored to obtain compensation for their property destroyed in the Olive Jane by the rebel vessel. Viewing the Polish question in its present aspect, the London Times is of opinion that further negotiations between Russia and the three Western Powers are virtually concluded, and if there is to be an appeal from the existing state of the controversy, it must be an appeal to the arbitrament of brute force. In the meantime and for six months to come Poland is handed over without a possibility of relief to the Power against which she is so vainly but bravely struggling. The withdrawal of Mr. MASON from England was still discussed by all the journals, and various reasons for the step are assigned. The London Globe, the official organ, says that the question of courtesy has not at all entered in the treatment of Mr. MASON, but simply policy. There had been little change in the Cotton, Provision and Breadstuffs markets. Consols had declined 1/8 cent., closing at 93 1/4@3/8.

abstract: His Position and Communications
snippet: His Position and Communications
lead_paragraph: The rebel cavalry raid which is reported to have taken place on Gen. ROSECRANS' line of communications at McMinnville, is one of a series of annoyances which may be expected, so long as the two armies face each other without great operations to absorb the attention. The temptation to these expeditions is very great, for the line connecting the Army of the Cumberland with its base -- the line over which supplies for man and beast as well as ammunition and reinforcements have to pass -- has the prodigious extension of three hundred miles, and is, by consequence, exceedingly exposed to this sort of attack. Along this route the rebels can, of course, always expect pickings -- they can cut the railroad line, gobble up wagon trains and attack isolated posts. The rebels are well furnished for making these raids, for they have a large force of cavalry, or rather of mounted infantry -- as large, at least, as fifteen thousand men, under command of WHEELER and FORREST, and in fine condition.

abstract: The difficulties in the Provost-Marshal office of the Sixth District have culminated in a dead lock, so far as the consideration of the claims for exemption on the grounds of alienship are concerned. Marshal FARR claims that the simple oath of alienage is sufficient for exemption, and for the Board to act upon. The majority of the Board, Commissioner LAMONT and Surgeon POWELL, deny that the oath is sufficient, und claim that it should be corroborated by the records in the County Clerk's office. Clerks to search the records have been appointed by the majority of the Board; but Capt. FARR refuses to recognize them, and denies that the majority has power to appoint anybody for any position, claiming all that power for himself. Meanwhile the cases of all those parties claiming to be aliens are laid over, and amount to at least three hundred for the past six weeks. It certainly would appear that while the search would be productive of much good it could in no case be of any harm.

abstract: -- The Boston Advertiser, in referring to our July riots, says that "the City of New-York will never escape the memory of those dreadful days." Never while this generation lasts, certainly. Nor will it ever forget the men who incited those riots, the faction which participated in them, the party which winked at them, or the public officers who tampered with the riots and parleyed with the rioters. It was a warning to all men who love American institutions, who believe in the Republic, who revere law, -- a warning to poor men and to rich men, to those who possess property and to those who expect to own it. It was a warning to this City, to our great State, to the Whole country. It would seem like the madness which precedes destruction, if, after this fearful and ever-memorable warning, the City of New-York were to indorse the men and the party who were responsible for the outbreak of this riot, and responsible for its continuance through four days. If the men and the party on whose shoulders rest the guilt of the dread week of murder, arson and plunder, are indorsed by our City, and if far greater evils than the July riot overtake us in the future, the voters of New-York will know who are to blame. They will not need to go beyond themselves to find the culprits.

abstract: Sept. 30; Grimm, Jacob, the German writer
snippet: Sept. 30; Grimm, Jacob, the German writer
lead_paragraph: This celebrated German writer, who, in conjunction with his late brother William, has been so long well known, not only in Germany, but throughout all Europe, died on Sunday evening last at Berlin, after a short illness. He was born Jan. 4, 1785, and had therefore reached his 79th year. Although he sought comparative retirement after the death of his brother, he was indefatigable up to his last moments in carrying out the objects to which he had devoted his long and useful life; and with patriotic self-devotion his last hours were spent, not in earning new fame by the continuation of those works which were so peculiarly his own, but in the preparation of his great German dictionary. Jacob Grimm, like many others, had difficulties to contend with in the outset of his career. When he commenced the profession of authorship, Augustus William Schlegel looked upon ancient German literature as in some degree his own domain, and did not treat the young beginner with any degree of friendship, regarding him almost us a usurper, and finding terrible fault with his etymology. But a change soon came over the feelings of Schlegel as to his country man, for afterward he never spoke or wrote of him without expressing the highest opinion of his talents; and he once said: "I cannot name him without expressing my admiration of his greatness." His loss will be irreparable in more than one sense, for he was honored and esteemed in Germany not less as a man than as a scholar, and the tranquil spirit by which he was actuated manifested itself in the kindly nature of his writings. In politics he took the Liberal side, and his loss will be felt by many German journals, with the conductors of which he was on terms of valued amity. It is to be regretted that the great national German dictionary on which he was engaged, has not reached beyond the word "Fromm;" but, from the ample materials left by the deceased, there is every hope that the work will be concluded in as satisfactory a manner as that in which it was commenced.

abstract: HIGH PRICES OBTAINED. -- The residue of the Kate Dale's cargo, consisting of bales of Upland cotton, was sold at public sale yesterday. There was an unusually large attendance, owing to the scarcity of cotton in the market, and higher prices were obtained than at any time since the war began. 20 bales brought 92 1/2c. the pound; 10, 92 1/2c.; 20, 92 1/8c.; and 82 bales, 92c; 603 bales were bought by GARDNER & Co., of New-York, extensive manufacturers, for 90 7/8c, the pound. The lowest price obtained for cotton in rather bad order, was 82 1/2c., about the same that the best quality of was cotton has been selling for in New-York and Boston. The sale realized over $320,000, which, with the $49,000 obtained for the vessel, and the portion of the cargo sold a few weeks ago, make a total of $369,000. The Kate Dale was captured by the steamer R.R. Cuyler, after she had been detached from the squadron, and the prize money will consequently be divided solely among her officers and crew. -- Philadelphia Ledger, Oct. 8.

abstract: President; The and Popular Factions
snippet: President; The and Popular Factions
lead_paragraph: When the result of some of the elections last Fall seemed to indicate dissatisfaction on the part of a portion of the public with the policy of the Administration, or at least with its manner of conducting the war, and when the President resolutely refused to sacrifice his own notions of right to the clamors of discontent and timidity, mutterings of regret were heard from various quarters that the Executive in the United States was not in as immediate subjection to the popular will as the Executive in England, and that an adverse vote did not entail a change of cabinet as well as a change of measures. The fact that in England the Government is so completely in the hands of a class, that the waves of popular feeling only reach it after roaring a very long time in vain on the shore; and that an adverse vote, either in the House of Commons or at the polls, generally expresses a sentiment which it has taken years to form, was by our would-be reformers entirely overlooked. Our Executive was made independent of the people for the time it holds office, by the founders of Government, intentionally, and not through inadvertence; and for the very strong reason, that ours being a pure democracy, and not, as in England, a democracy with a strong aristocracy to act as a buffer between it and the Administration, it was felt that an Executive which was forced to reflect not only the calm and mature judgment, but every fleeting passion of a community as excitable and as restive and nervous as ours, would be the worst Executive that was ever seen, and would, in fact, be little better than a Government carried on by Committees appointed by mass-meetings.

abstract: Between 1 and 2 o'clock yesterday morning, Capt. CAMERON, of the Eighteenth Precinct, with a platoon of men, made a descent on a gambling-house situated at No. 818 Broadway. The proprietor, R. HAMILTON DIEDERICH, the cue-keeper, and nine ...
lead_paragraph: Between 1 and 2 o'clock yesterday morning, Capt. CAMERON, of the Eighteenth Precinct, with a platoon of men, made a descent on a gambling-house situated at No. 818 Broadway. The proprietor, R. HAMILTON DIEDERICH, the cue-keeper, and nine others who were found engaged in gambling, were arrested. This house has for a long time been well known to the Police, and the officers have been on the watch to detect the proprietor. Many persons were in the habit of spending their time and money at this establishment. Among the victims was Mr. EMIL SICK, of No. 70 Ludlow-street, who appeared before Justice DOWLING at the Tombs yesterday afternoon, and made an affidavit to the effect that, between the 1st day of January last and the 15th of May ensuing he had lost the sum of $20,000 at the gambling-house above-named. He further testified that the money which he had lost did not belong to him, but to some merchants doing business in Broad-street. He also stated that at the times he lost the money a man named MARCUS C. LITTELL was the proprietor of the gambling saloon at the place above-named. Upon this statement Justice DOWLING issued a warrant for the arrest of Mr. LITTELL. Superintendent KENNEDY is entitled to great credit for the part he has taken in trying to break up this gambling-house. It has been well known to the Police for many months past; but until recently the authorities could get hold of no evidence which would warrant them in taking any action. Two citizens who had suffered in the establishment were at length found, and they made affidavits of their losses, which were submitted to Superintendent KENNEDY. Capt. CAMERON selected Officers O'DONNELL and DAVIS, who, dressed in plain clothes, at about 2 o'clock A.M., entered the saloon, where they found gambling of all descriptions going on. The duty of these officers was merely to survey the premises. They retired, and reported what they had discovered. Capt. CAMERON then selected ten of his most efficient and trustworthy men, all dressed in full uniform, and with them he marched to the gamblers' den, and surrounded it. When everything was in readiness for the capture, Capt. CAMERON passed through the front door, seized the colored servant in attendance, and with two or three of his most trusty men, entered the saloon and took prisoners all whom he found engaged in gambling. The arrested persons were taken before Justice DOWLING, where they gave their names as follows. R. Hamilton Diederich, proprietor; Owen Johnson, cue keeper; Chester Roberts, Thomas Yeiden, C.P. Williams, L.W. Wesley, R.S. Thomas, R. Alexander, J.B. Schenck, James Diament and another who refused to give his name. Two colored waiters, named James and John Cooper, were also arrested and held as witnesses.

abstract: There is, it is said, an impression among the soldiers of the Army of the Potomac that they have fought their last great battle in Virginia. And this impression, which probably rather comes through a kind of instinct ...
lead_paragraph: There is, it is said, an impression among the soldiers of the Army of the Potomac that they have fought their last great battle in Virginia. And this impression, which probably rather comes through a kind of instinct to men gossipping around the camp-fires than as the result of any very recondite process of reasoning, has in it a great intrinsic probability. The weightiest consideration conducting to this conclusion is the fact of the fundamental change in the military programme that has grown out of events in Tennessee.

abstract: Mozart and Tammany Mutual Conference Committees
snippet: Mozart and Tammany Mutual Conference Committees
lead_paragraph: The Sub-Conference Committees of Mozart and Tammany met on Wednesday, and they close-locked their doors and kept out all but the faithful; even reporters could not ascertain what they were about, and what they had concluded upon. But it is ascertained that the following Lion and Lamb were the presiding officers of the Committees: FERNANDO WOOD, Mozart; CHAS. G. CORNELL, Tammany. The question first considered was that of a platform. Tammany argued that it was necessary, as a matter of policy, to lay down a war platform. Mozart replied with the argument that it had never been customary for a Democratic County Convention to pass any platform resolutions. Tammany responded with the assertion that just now it was a necessity to have a platform, and finally it was left to one of each Committee to fix up a series of planks for the Democracy to stand upon. The probabilities are that the platform of the State Convention at Albany, will be re-presented and adopted. Hon. FERNANDO WOOD was one of the principal mechanics in constructing that, and all the "jours" acknowledged his exceeding skill in arranging it on the "little joker," principle of "now you see it, and now you don't; five to one, gentlemen, that you can't tell which cup it's under." The Albany Platform should be readopted. It can be construed both ways -- for and against the war -- and so much for the Sub-Conference Committees, who report to the larger bodies next Monday.

abstract: A Paris correspondent of the London Army Gazette mentions the coming of Mr. MASON to France, to aid his colleague SLIDELL in operating upon the French Government; and says that "perhaps another gentleman, who lately represented California, will also lend ...
lead_paragraph: A Paris correspondent of the London Army Gazette mentions the coming of Mr. MASON to France, to aid his colleague SLIDELL in operating upon the French Government; and says that "perhaps another gentleman, who lately represented California, will also lend the influence of his tongue and great knowledge of affairs." There can be no doubt who this California representative is. It is undoubtedly Mr. GWIN, lately United States Senator from California. The movements of this individual have been rather erratic during the past two years; and it was not until our Paris correspondent announced through our columns on Monday last that the Ex-Senator had arrived at the French capital, that we could definitely settle his whereabouts. He remained for a twelve-month in the loyal States after the outbreak of the rebellion; and it was in the Spring of last year that he was arrested by a naval officer on the Isthmus of Panama, as he was on his way, it was supposed, to this City. After being conveyed here, and remaining under surveillance for some time, he went to Washington, but from there, after a short residence, suddenly disappeared, and about a year ago turned up in Richmond. There or thereabouts he remained until August last, when he went to Wilmington, from which he sailed for Europe in a blockade-running steamer, and made the passage from Wilmington to Paris in the remarkably short space of twenty days. From the beginning, GWIN was an arrant rebel in fact, but while in the North his treason assumed the somewhat modified garb of the Copperhead. His purpose was to be on both sides, or rather to be on the winning side, whichever it might be. He stayed a long while in the North after the rebellion broke out, to see what might be the upshot of affairs; and when the Southern arms were widely successful last year, he went over to the Confederacy. Now, again, when the Southern cause is declining, and its only hope is from Europe, he wends his way there, to secure his own safety, and to aid the Confederacy after his own style. He will doubtless prove an efficient coadjutor of the great Louisiana intriguer, Mr. SLIDELL.

abstract: We have some very exciting and conflicting reports from Chattanooga. The rebels send news that BRAGG had opened an artillery fire on ROSECRANS, and that their shells reached Chattanooga, but ROSECRANS quickly responded to their fire. From our own side we have accounts ...
lead_paragraph: We have some very exciting and conflicting reports from Chattanooga. The rebels send news that BRAGG had opened an artillery fire on ROSECRANS, and that their shells reached Chattanooga, but ROSECRANS quickly responded to their fire. From our own side we have accounts to Wednesday night, at which time no general battle had come off, but desultory firing was continually kept up. The rebels seem to be operating with their cavalry in our rear, and we should judge that our communications were in peril. The general tenor of our dispatches would indicate a quick renewal of battle near Chattanooga.

lead_paragraph: THE NORTH AMERICAN TELEGRAPH ASSOCIATION. -- The North American Telegraph Association is now in session, at the office of the American Telegraph Company, in this City. The following Companies, composing the Association, are represented: The American Telegraph Company, the Western Union Telegraph Company, the New-York and Buffalo Telegraph Company, the Atlantic and Ohio Telegraph Company, the Illinois and Mississippi Telegraph Company, the Southwestern Telegraph Company and the Montreal Telegraph Company. At the meeting, yesterday, resolutions were passed highly complimentary to CYRUS W. FIELD, Esq., for his indefatigable labors in connection with the Atlantic Cable Company, and to PERRY D. MCCOLLINS. Esq., for his persistent endeavors to unite the two hemispheres, via Behring's Straits and the Russian Possessions. Both of these great projects are now likely to be fairly tested, as the combined capital and ability of this powerful Association will be at the service of these magnificent enterprises.

abstract: meanderings of a madman
snippet: meanderings of a madman
lead_paragraph: Mr. JOHN MITCHELL, the "fat negro" man, has written an article in the Richmond Enquirer, which he is so fearful will not be noticed in the North, and will not consequently come under the eve of Louis NAPOLEON, that he utters a sort of defiance to Northern journals to copy it. Notwithstanding the "fat negro's" impudence, we transfer to our columns all that part of the article that has any meaning to it at all. He wishes the Emperor of the French to be "duly informed of the general and extreme gratification with which the Confederates have looked upon the establishment of so good a neighbor upon their southern border; and that, instead of being anxious to join LINCOLN and his Generals in a war upon His Majesty, nothing would please them so well as a league with His Majesty, to make war upon LINCOLN, and thus make a speedy end of the braggadocio Yankee nation forever." This is really all MITCHELL wishes to say, except to further inform his French Majesty "that we (MITCHELL) take no interest at all in the 'Anglo-Saxon race,' and rather incline to believe that we belong to the 'Latin races' ourselves," which must be decidedly rich to those who know MITCHELL'S pedigree -- which we do not. We give him the benefit of our aid to bring his ideas to the notice of NAPOLEON; but yet we would be very far from advising the latter personage to believe that the people of the South -- rebels though they be -- will ever carry out the programme of this "fat negro" of the Latin race.

lead_paragraph: Capt. SEMMES has made his appearance in a new role. Weary of the glory of his numerous triumphs over unarmed merchantmen, he seeks for new worlds to conquer, and of all the honors which he could aspire to, what in the name of wonder should he choose but the honors of the Bench! He has donned the ermine, or rather turned up the cuffs of his pea jacket with that spotless fur. It is as Judge SEMMES that he is to be known to posterity, not alone as Captain of a corsair.

abstract: We notice that recent propositions have been made in several of our State Legislatures for negotiations with the enemy and suits for armistice. These deserve an unqualified condemnation. They are generally made in artful language; they are very innocent ...
lead_paragraph: We notice that recent propositions have been made in several of our State Legislatures for negotiations with the enemy and suits for armistice. These deserve an unqualified condemnation. They are generally made in artful language; they are very innocent on their race; they are always accompanied by certain protestations that the interest of the South is not to be sacrificed; that the object is an "honorable" peace, and that the negotiation is to be an essay on Christian charity. There is no possible truth in such protestations. They are the convenient covers of traitorous designs, or of cowardly acquiescence in the failure of our struggle.

abstract: Commendable Action on New-York Riot Trials; as Affected by the War
snippet: Commendable Action on New-York Riot Trials; as Affected by the War
lead_paragraph: As we most heartily commended the charge of Recorder HOFFMAN to the Grand Jury, at the time of the opening of the trial of the rioters in August last, so with equal heartiness do we now commend the charge of Justice BARNARD, delivered to the Grand Jury on Wednesday, on occasion of the reopening of a term of Court which will, in good part, be devoted to the trial of the same class of culprits. We published Justice BARNARD's charge yesterday; and though no one had previously doubted his purpose to pursue an honorable course, uphold the authority of law and vindicate its action against its violators, yet the appearance of the charge gave a feeling of satisfaction and security to all good citizens. Justice BARNARD, like Recorder HOFFMAN, administered a severe condemnation upon all who violate the laws, to whatever party they may belong, or under whatever pretext they may act. "Evil disposed men of all political parties, "he say, "have within the last few, years called in question the constitutionality of every law which in any way affected them or their interests;" and the terrible fruits of this teaching are at last apparent. He further argues that "if a large number of men claiming that a law is unconstitutional can disregard it and resist by violence its enforecement, so can a smaller number on the same ground resist another law, and so can each individual resist a law which does not happen to suit him; and thus all government would end. It will thus be perceived that the fact that the acts of violence committed in this City were so committed under the plea of resisting an unconstitutional law, not only affords no excuse, but enhances the criminality of the act. If this be so, in case of resistance to any law claimed to be unconstitutional, is not such resistance the more reprehensible when made to a law such as the one in question?"

abstract: There has been no result of the war so extraordinary, and so unlooked for, as its effect on the cities of the North. Those of us who remember and who does not? the pathetic earnestness with which, previous to the secession movement, our Pro-Southern Democrats warned us all that if the South left us, our towns would go to decay, the grass grow in our streets, and our ships rot at the ...
lead_paragraph: There has been no result of the war so extraordinary, and so unlooked for, as its effect on the cities of the North. Those of us who remember -- and who does not? -- the pathetic earnestness with which, previous to the secession movement, our Pro-Southern Democrats warned us all that if the South left us, our towns would go to decay, the grass grow in our streets, and our ships rot at the wharves, must witness the actual condition of things with a good deal of amusement. One superstition, in particular, which was deeply rooted in the minds of the denizens of Tammany and Mozart Halls -- that the hotels at the North were all kept up by Southern planters and "merchants" -- must, by this time, have received a tolerably severe blow. There has probably been hardly a Southern planter seen in the North for the last two years, or a Southern merchant, unless HAMBLETON, of black-mail fame, be entitled to that designation; and yet we believe the hotels are at present fairly patronized. There are few of them which do not turn away every day nearly as many guests as they receive. Even the New-York Hotel, the very headquarters of plantocracy, and which ought to be ashamed to survive the outbreak of the war, manages to flourish as bravely upon the greenbacks of Northern customers as ever it did upon the gold and silver of the South. The demand for houses, too, is unprecedented. There are none to rent, and few for sale, and the tide of population, nevertheless, continues to pour into every one of our great towns with undiminished impetuosity.

abstract: By the arrival of the steamship Columbia at St. Johns, N.F., on Wednesday evening, we have three days' later news from Europe. Earl RUSSELL had made an important speech on American topics, in which he had thoroughly discussed the policy of England defending her course in all ...
lead_paragraph: By the arrival of the steamship Columbia at St. Johns, N.F., on Wednesday evening, we have three days' later news from Europe. Earl RUSSELL had made an important speech on American topics, in which he had thoroughly discussed the policy of England -- defending her course in all respects. On the whole, his expressions were conciliatory and friendly to the North. In alluding to this speech, the London Times says that what Earl RUSSELL stated relative to the iron-clads in the Mersey, is interpreted as meaning that the vessels will be detained, even if the existing law is in their favor; so that Parliament may be called on to pass measures for the purpose. There was little change in commercial affairs. The Liverpool Provision market was steady and Produce market quiet. Consols for money closed at 93 1/8@ 33 1/2.

abstract: The Board of Aldermen met yesterday, and upon the recommendation of the Comptroller, adopted an ordinance making the following transfers of moneys to exhausted funds: From accost of Charities and Correction to account of Advertising, $15,000; to City Contingencies, $15,000; ...
lead_paragraph: The Board of Aldermen met yesterday, and upon the recommendation of the Comptroller, adopted an ordinance making the following transfers of moneys to exhausted funds: From accost of Charities and Correction to account of Advertising, $15,000; to City Contingencies, $15,000; to Street Cleaning, $60,000; and the following sums to account of Roads and Avenues, viz.: From Diamond Reef, (blasting of.) $4,438; from Seventh Precinct Station-house, $1,257 15; from Street Improvements, 4,304 85 -- total, $10,000. Of the amount transferred to "City Contingencies," $10,000 is for the reception and entertainment of the Russian officers. The Comptroller reported an expenditure of $52,280 from the Relief Fund for the fortnight, ending on last Saturday, to 13,362 families, comprising 13,311 adults and 18,000 children. The Board adopted an ordinance making a further appropriation of $500,000 to the Fund, alter amending it, by increasing the salaries of the Assistant Treasurer from $75 to $100 per month. The Seventy-ninth regiment (Highlanders) were voted a handsome or gimerta standard, inscribed with the names of the thirteen pitched battles in which they have participated. By resolution of Mr. OTTIWELL, the Board concurred to direct the Street Commissioner to contract for a new patent self-regulating gas-burner that has been tested with great success. Adjourned to Monday.

abstract: We have consulted BUFFON and CUVIER, as also Peter Parley, and discover that in calling Mozart and Tammany the "lions and the lambs," a mistake was made. A critical comparison of the nature of the animals, with the facts and information afforded by the authors named, satisfies us of an error, and that "Rams" and the "Nanny-goats" are the proper designations; Mozart the "Rams," Tammany the "Nanny-goats," and any one at all ...
lead_paragraph: We have consulted BUFFON and CUVIER, as also Peter Parley, and discover that in calling Mozart and Tammany the "lions and the lambs," a mistake was made. A critical comparison of the nature of the animals, with the facts and information afforded by the authors named, satisfies us of an error, and that "Rams" and the "Nanny-goats" are the proper designations; Mozart the "Rams," Tammany the "Nanny-goats," and any one at all acquainted with the organizations will at once appreciate and approve the application. This, however, is merely explanatory and apologetic to "lions and lambs" for what they might justly consider an aspersion, and has nothing to do with the meeting of the State Democratic Committee on Thursday at the St. Nicholas Hotel, to which we now proceed.

abstract: Speech at New-York Union Meeting--"Who is Responsible for the War?"
snippet: Speech at New-York Union Meeting--"Who is Responsible for the War?"
lead_paragraph: A large and highly appreciative audience was called together at Cooper Institute, last evening, by the announcement that Hon. HENRY WINTER DAVIS, of Maryland, would speak on the interesting and vital topics of the day. They were well repaid by an address of unusual power, eloquence and logic, exposing the shifts to which opponents of the Government and sympathizers with the rebellion have resorted since the outbreak of the war, and impressing the duty of every man who loved the country to support the Administration in its efforts to subdue traitors abroad and at home.

abstract: The Locust Point arrived last evening from New Orleans with dates to the 1st. The papers make no allusion to the report published on Thursday, of the repulse of Gen. FRANKLIN'S ...
lead_paragraph: The Locust Point arrived last evening from New Orleans with dates to the 1st. The papers make no allusion to the report published on Thursday, of the repulse of Gen. FRANKLIN's command at Brashear City, end the subsequent victory over the rebels by Gen. ORD, nor do they state anything regarding the health of the city. We are informed by our correspondence that FRANKLIN's corps, at latest advices, was encamped with WASHBURN's command at New-Bisland, 50 miles from Brashear City, and that the comparative slowness of his advance was attributable to the obstruction of the Bayou Teche by the enemy. These obstacles had been removed, and the stream was open to New-Iberia. A guerrilla party had captured several of our men near Donaldsonville, and an expedition to clear the country of these depredators had been successful. Several important orders issued by Gen. BANKS have been made public. One announces that there will be a conscription in the First and Second Congressional Districts of the State; that the organization of one or more volunteer regiments for the protection and defence of New-Orleans is authorized; that men of color, from 20 to 30 years of age, employed upon Government or on private plantations, will be detailed for military service in the Corps d'Afrique, upon order of the Commission of Enrollment, and that arrangements will made to secure the crops, and laborers will be furnished as far as practicable to supply the vacancies occasioned by the execution of the order.

abstract: His Prospects in Tennessee
snippet: His Prospects in Tennessee
lead_paragraph: The telegraphic dispatches concerning affairs at Chattanooga, which we spread before our readers yesterday and to-day, indicate that the military situation in that quarter is eminently critical. We do not say it is perilous to Gen. ROSECRANS, for we imagine that that officer now holds his position so stoutly, and has such a largely augmented army, that, in the event of another battle, the chances are greatly in favor of his achieving a decisive victory over the army of BRAGG and LONGSTREET. But appearances certainly indicate that the quiet which has prevailed on the Tennessee since the 20th of September is likely soon to be broken, and that the thunders of war which crashed and rolled along the mountain ranges of Upper Georgia three weeks ago, will burst forth again before many days.

abstract: Baltimore Committee's Invitation to Russian Officers at New-York
snippet: Baltimore Committee's Invitation to Russian Officers at New-York
lead_paragraph: The Harbor was especially enlivened, yesterday, by the formal visit of the Committees from Baltimore to Admiral LISOVSKY for the purpose of tendering to him and the officers of his squadron the hospitalities of the commercial metropolis of Maryland. On the 5th inst. the Common Councils of Baltimore, in both branches, passed resolutions and appointed delegations of their members to convey to the Russian commanding officer of the fleet now at anchor in the Hudson, a formal and special invitation to visit the Monumental City and receive the attentions of its authorities and people. The deputation, which arrived here on Friday night, consisted of the Committees of both branches of the Councils, and another composed of six citizens appointed by the Mayor of that place. It comprised Hon. JOHN L. CHAPMAN, Mayor; JAMES YOUNG, Esq., President of the first branch; S.F. STREETER, Chairman, and Messrs. JOHN F. TOWNER and E.S. LAMBDIN, of the Committee; Messrs. SAMUEL DUER, President of the second branch, and JOHN G. WILMOT, Chairman, with WM. MOODY and JOHN BARRON, Esqs., members of the Committee. The Citizens' Committee was as follows: Ex-Mayor THOMAS SWANN, Hon. HENRY W. HOFFMANN, Collector of the Port; JOHN H.B. LATROBE, Col. WM. CHESNUT, and Capt. JACOB W. HUGG. In addition to these were several Baltimoreans of note, who accompanied the Committees and joined in the demonstration, viz.: Messrs. VALENTINE FURMAN, WM. MCCLYMONT, JOHN DUKEHEART, JOHN SLACK, and others. During the day the Hon. HENRY WINTER DAVIS, who chanced to be in New-York, also joined the party, and the whole-souled greeting extended to the Muscovite strangers.

abstract: The Diet and M. Bismarck
snippet: The Diet and M. Bismarck
lead_paragraph: The Prussian atmosphere is full of political rumors. It is said that the dissolution of the Diet was not the work of VON BISMARK, but the tale is that it was brought about in this way. One of the artifices employed by him to maintain his position consists in isolating the King, and preventing all intercourse between him and those who would be likely to enlighten his ignorance. Now, though WILLIAM may be conscious of the surveillance exercised over him, he does not wish others to be cognizant of it. It happened, while he was at Gastein, that he unexpectedly met Baron AUERSWALD, one of his oldest friends, on the promenade. "What," exclaimed the King, "you here, and don't come to see me!" "I called twice, your Majesty, but was twice refused admission." WILLIAM made no reply, yet hardly was he back to Carlsbad when he ordered the decree dissolving the Chambers to be drawn up, without consultation with his Premier. His Majesty seems in fact to be growing somewhat weary of the ministerial fetters. Putting aside altogether the necessity which inclines him to conciliate his people, he has recently experienced certain slights at their hands that have annoyed him considerably. During his homeward journey to Berlin, the Corporations of several of the towns through which he passed refused him a public reception, and even had the boldness to adopt resolutions to that effect. This evidence of his waning popularity not all the vigilance of VON BISMARK could conceal from the King, who doubtless was not mistaken as to the real cause of it.

abstract: The grand banquet to be given by the City Government to the officers of the Russian fleet, will take place the latter end of next week, or the week after. The action taken by the Common Council on Thursday, and approved by the Mayor on Friday, disposes of all financial obstacles in the way of the proposed banquet, and the Committee will now perfect the arrangements as speedily as possible. It is not yet decided where to hold the banquet, but it will probably come off at the Fifth-Avenue Hotel or at the Astor House. The President of the United States and Cabinet officers will be invited, as well as the Governor of this State. It is also in contemplation to invite the officers of the English and French vessels now in our harbor.

abstract: -- A series of robberies have been committed on the Hudson River Railroad within the past few days, of the most daring nature. One of the victims is a Mr. LANDON, who resides in Mendon, Monroe County, this State. He testifies that on Wednesday night last, he left this City on an Express train of the Hudson River Railroad, bound for Montreal. Mr. LANDON was sitting in the rear part of the last car. While the train, was approaching Yonkers, two ruffians entered the car, dragged LANDON therefrom and threw him into Spuyten Duyvil Creek. The injuries he received, together with the cold bath, rendered him insensible for a time. When he recovered he he found that his pocket-book, containing over $800 in money, besides valuable papers, was missing. No clue has yet been obtained as to the persons who committed the theft. Mr. S.B. CRANSON, of No. 64 Beaver-street, was beaten and afterward robbed of $1,000, while passing over this road a few nights since. We have also heard of two other men who recently had their pockets picked of large sums of money while riding in these cars. The Detective Police have been notified, and two of the shrewdest in the City have been detailed to work up the case, and, if possible, to secure the members of the gang of thieves and pickpockets, who, of late, have so much infested the cars on the Hudson River Road.

abstract: National Force and Mode of Raising It
snippet: National Force and Mode of Raising It
lead_paragraph: -- We publish in the TIMES of this morning a very able and erudite article, from the pen of an eminent lawyer of this City -- which article has been too long crowded out of our columns by the pressure of domestic and foreign news. It is entitled, "The National Force," and discusses the power of a nation to raise armies, the mode of obtaining troops adopted in various European countries, but particularly in England, together with other collateral questions, in their historical and legal aspects. It disperses much of the fog which has been thrown around the draft, and disposes of many objections to it, so far as those objections are founded on English authorities and precedents. It is astonishing how many errors have beem spread abroad on this subject by speakers and newspapers, and how many misconceptions concerning it pervade the public mind. It is all-important, in a practical point of view, that these errors and misconceptions be removed; and this can only be done by bringing before the people such searching investigations as that referred to.

abstract: YELLOW FEVER. Yellow fever is a subject on which New-Orleans papers have always been rather reticent, until such time as its ravages ...
lead_paragraph: -- We have New-Orleans advices to the 4th instant, but there is no confirmation of the existence of yellow fever, which was lately reported from Washington to be prevailing on the Lower Mississippi, and of which a number of our naval officers were said to have died. Yellow fever is a subject on which New-Orleans papers have always been rather reticent, until such time as its ravages assumed an extent in which silence was impossible; but it could not easily exist without our having indications of the fact from the mortality returns or the local columns of the journals. Beside, it would be a very extraordinary thing for the yellow fever to break out at the close of September. If that month comes in with the absence of the disease, the city and vicinity is usually considered safe for the year. We suspect that our special dispatch, which characterized the fever of which our officers died at New-Orleans, as "pernicious" fever, or malignant intermittent, is the correct statement of the case. This view is confirmed by a letter which we have just received from our special correspondent at New-Orleans, who says that there have been whisperings of "Yellow Jack" being in that city, but that they are all positively false." The Crescent City, and our troops stationed there, may well be grateful for the good fortune, or good Providence which has saved them during two successive seasons from the plague of the Southern coast.

abstract: -- The World of yesterday has another of its ridiculous articles on political economy. It says: "Obligations like those of Mr. CHASE we suppose, not being of a character that must be paid, it would be worse for us to be out of debt three or four thousand millions than to be in debt to that amount" -- which is an inference about as honest from a statement about as true as the usual inferences and statements of the World. It further says: "This doctrine being the basis, we should like to see a calculation of the probable eventual price of gold, when purchased with 'obligations' of a character that 'need not be paid.'" The "probable eventual price of gold" is a theme upon which the World has been harping for two years; but as experience and analysis have proved all its past efforts to be out of tune, its present or future attempts are utterly unworthy of notice. We cannot lumber our columns with farther specimens of the maunderings and dishonest speculations of the World on this question; but really if such gospels of political economy can find toleration, we shall next expect to see our publishers competing for a "treatise on thorough bass, written by a chimpanzee, with the tip of his tail dipped in treacle."

abstract: One of the most curious and novel rural festivals ever witnessed in America, closed last Saturday at Egg Harbor City, N.J. It is a genuine German October Festival an old-fashioned Weihlese, or Wine Harvest, so called as practiced in Vaterland, and, in various forms, in all the wine-growing countries of the world since the palmy days of ancient Judea.
lead_paragraph: One of the most curious and novel rural festivals ever witnessed in America, closed last Saturday at Egg Harbor City, N.J. It is a genuine German October Festival -- an old-fashioned Weihlese, or Wine Harvest, so called -- as practiced in Vaterland, and, in various forms, in all the wine-growing countries of the world since the palmy days of ancient Judea. In the earliest times in the far East, and now throughout the vine-producing districts of Germany the gathering of the grapes and their consignment to the wine press, ever was among the most striking and popular of the rustic festivals. The joyous season of the ripeness and fulness of the year teems with incentives to hearty jollity, and the whole-souled Teutonic race have always made it a period of unbounded wassail. The russet hues of the landscape; the hazy atmosphere; the smell of the fallen leaves; the lingering, half-languid warmth tempered still by bracing breezes; the clustering fruit upon the laden trees and vines, and all the evidence of the fulfillment of the season's labor and its rich reward, endow Autumn with indescribable charms as peculiar to it as to Spring its fresh verdue and bloom, and to Summer its golden glow of garden and field. The brilliant, pleasant outside life, indeed, is ceasing, but the prospect of the cosy ingle-side at home, the solid good cheer and the purply, brimming wine-cup by the ruddy hearth are thoughts agreeable alike to youth or age, and all join in for wholesale pleasure. It is just such a grand frolic as this that the Germans are celebrating at Egg Harbor for the benefit of their great model farm belonging to the Central Association of Husbandry in North America, as the head Society is called, The festival in held in the City Park of the above-named place, and being combined with the regular Fair of Atlantic County, is a most interesting event, especially as it is the very first of the kind ever celebrated on this Continent.

abstract: The steamship City of Baltimore, from Liverpool Sept. 30, via Queenstown Oct. 1, passed Cape Race on Friday morning. The news is two days later. From the brief summary telegraphed we learn that a report was current to the effect that the mission of ALEXANDER H. STEPHENS to France was to settle upon terms with the Emperor for the recognition of the South on an emancipation basis. The London Times publishes an absurd rumor, probably based upon the representations of Ex-Senator GWIN, formerly of California, but recently of Richmond, Va., that the Golden State was desirous of seceding and joining the Mexican Empire. The delegation from Mexico were to have had an interview with MAXIMILIAN on the 3d. for the purpose of tendering him the crown. The proposition is said to have been made to the other Western Powers by England to ignore Russia's title to Poland. The latest commercial advices via Queenstown report the Liverpool Cotton market firmer, but prices unchanged. Provisions were also firm, but Breadstuff's remained quiet. Consols closed at 93 3/8 for money.

lead_paragraph: There are two styles of perpetual "Britishers" whom we have always admired, and always shall admire. abstract: REPUBLICAN ASSEMBLY CONVENTIONS. The Kings County Republican Conventions were held on Friday evening to nominate candidates for the Assembly. The First District Convention met and adjourned until the 19th inst., without making a nomination.
lead_paragraph: REPUBLICAN ASSEMBLY CONVENTIONS. -- The Kings County Republican Conventions were held on Friday evening to nominate candidates for the Assembly. The First District Convention met and adjourned until the 19th inst., without making a nomination. The Second District Convention met at the corner of Union and Court streets, and also adjourned without making a nomination. The Third District Convention met at No. 9 Court-street, and after one formal ballot, on which H.B. BRADSHAW received five votes, and ALEX. CAMPBELL the same number, the Convention adjourned till next Wednesday evening. In the Seventh District, JACOB WORTH was nominated.

abstract: And English Constitutional Law; Militia and English Constitutional Law
snippet: And English Constitutional Law; Militia and English Constitutional Law
lead_paragraph: Military law is distinguished from municipal law in having personal extent, or in being a personal law. Laws govern persons and territory. By governing persons, law is said to have personal extent. By governing in certain territory it is said to have territorial extent. We speak of personal law and territorial law. The municipal, or civil law, extends to persons generally, within a certain territory. It has territorial extent, or is territorial law. It is therefore called "the law of the land." Military law extends to persons discriminated without reference to territory. It has personal extent, or is personal law. Territorial law governs persons while they continue within certain territory. A personal law may govern for the life of those to whom it extends, or for a less term.

abstract: The Committee appointed on the fith inst., by the Common Council of Baltimore, visited Admiral FARRAGUT yesterday morning, at the Astor House, in compliance with resolutions passed by the Baltimore municipal body, and invited the distinguished officer to visit that city. A richly engrossed copy of the resolutions was presented to the Admiral by Mr. F.S. STREETER, Chairman of the Committee of the First Branch, who accompanied it with some well-timed compliments, and formally urged, on behalf of his fellow citizens an acceptance of their invitation. Admiral FARRAGUT signified that it would delight him to comply, should the exigencies of the service not demand his presence elsewhere. He was compelled to forego the pleasure of accompanying the deputation on board the Russian fleet, owing to an engagement of the service, which required him to visit a Government vessel just going to sea.
