abstract: Russia's Final Reply to the European Powers; Ultimatum of on the Polish Insurrection
snippet: Russia's Final Reply to the European Powers; Ultimatum of on the Polish Insurrection
lead_paragraph: The Government of the Czar has at length condescended to reply to the "identical notes" of the intervening Powers. The tone of these Gortschakoff replies is most courteous; they accept, without qualification or reservation, every one of Earl RUSSELL'S six points, and promise that the Czar "will do all in his power to solve the question which is a source of misunderstanding between the Cabinets." But what does all this amount to when it is also asserted that none of these points can be carried out, that the solution of the said question is impracticable, until the insurgents are crushed and Poland is pacified? The fact is, let the Allies attempt to disguise it an they may, that the importunate remonstrances of their diplomatists, have not caused Russia to recede a single hair's breadth from her original position. So far in truth have the interventionists been from effecting any good for the Poles, that they have rendered their case rather worse than otherwise. That intelligence which La France recently published about it being the intention of the Czar to grant a constitution to Poland in common with the rest of his empire, was certainly not without foundation. The benevolence of ALEXANDER undoubtedly contemplated some such philanthropic scheme; and the correctness of this view is rendered more than plausible by the late remarkable speech of the Czar to the Diet of the Grand Duchy of Finland; but the tone of the Anglo-Gallic dispatches had roused the pride of the war party in the Cabinet, who would not hear of any concession being made to the insurgents at the dictation of the Western Powers, and so the Czar had to shelve his Constitution project for the present. If Russia, then, will concede no terms to the Poles, but requires unconditional submission, it is to the indiscretion of their French and English friends that they must ascribe the severity of their fate. The interventionists thrust themselves into this Slavonic imbroglio most inconsiderately, and while in utter ignorance of the real nature of the question. They spoke and acted as if the entire Polish nation was in arms against Russia. They consigned to oblivion this important fact, that it was an insurrection of the aristocracy and of the democracy of the towns, and that the mass of the peasantry, who constitute in Poland the vast majority of the population, were not only quiescent, but even devoted to Russia -- devoted to her because she had raised them from the degradation of serfs to the dignity of freemen, and had secured to them possession of the soil, as well as personal liberty.

abstract: Charge on Trial of Rioters, Usefulness of
snippet: Charge on Trial of Rioters, Usefulness of
lead_paragraph: The charge of Judge BARNARD to the Grand Jury, at the Court of Oyer and Terminer on Wednesday, will gratify and relieve everybody who feared that the good work begun by Recorder HOFFMAN would not be continued in his absence. The rioters are evidently assure of justice at the hands of one as those of the other, and justice is all that those who most abhor them could desire for them. Judge BARNARD's emphatic condemnation of the atrocities of last July is all the more valuable from the fact that he cannot be accused of sympathy with the Administration or its policy. It relieves the decenter portion of the community from the doubt -- and it was a very horrible one -- which many of us had begun to feel, whether political partisanship was not getting a little too tigerish for endurance. Every respectable citizen who recalls the sensations with which he read or heard of the expressions of sympathy uttered in the World and Herald, of the 14th of July, for the bands of cutthroats who had been following their devilish trade on the previous day, will readily understand that if these two journals had expressed the feelings of any considerable portion even of the Democratic party, there would have been in six months a general and overwhelming demand for protection by a strong hand, whatever sacrifices of public franchises or public liberties such protection might exact. The main end of government is, after all, the protection of life and property, and there are no men of any race who would not hold liberty in detestation, if its possession made this object unattainable. The ruin of every free Government that has ever been ruined, has been due in the main to the anxiety of the mass of the citizens about the safety of their throats and purses.

abstract: War Resolutions of and the Daily News
snippet: War Resolutions of and the Daily News
lead_paragraph: The New-York News has come to the conclusion that there are some things which the Peace party of New-York City will not bear. They did not have as prominent a place at the Albany Convention as they wanted, and that Convention adopted one resolution which so far squinted toward prosecuting the war that the News had to reject it entirely, as "unmeaning." But now it learns that, when the Conference Committee which has been formed between Tammany and Mozart meets to agree upon a division of the spoils, "a few mischievous partisans of Tammany, unless controlled by the more discreet majority, will attempt to force War resolutions upon it;" and thereupon it announces that "such a course will under no circumstances be acquiesced in by Mozart Hall" -- that "there will be no affiliation under any War resolution," for "there is not a man of the Mozart Democracy that would consent to that surrender of the vital principle of his organization."

abstract: Affairs with the Army of the Potomac again commence to be exciting. For some days past the apparent concentration of a strong rebel force in the vicinity of Madison Court House has been looked on with suspicion, and on Saturday morning one of Gen. KILPATRICK's cavalry brigades
lead_paragraph: Affairs with the Army of the Potomac again commence to be exciting. For some days past the apparent concentration of a strong rebel force in the vicinity of Madison Court House has been looked on with suspicion, and on Saturday morning one of Gen. KILPATRICK's cavalry brigades was dispatched to reconnoitre in that direction. When near Robertson's River our troopers met a large body of STUART's cavalry, and a fight was the result. The battle raged an hour, when KILPATRICK was compelled to fall back upon his infantry supports. Another severe contest ensued, and, after a considerable number had been captured, the infantry also gave way. This illfortune, however, was quickly retrieved by a detachment of cavalry, who retook nearly all the prisoners, when our whole force, stubbornly contesting every foot of the way, fell back toward Culpepper. It is generally believed that the rebel movements signify an intention on the part of A.P. HILL's corps to change from our left front to the rear of our right, in order to cut our railroad communication, and measures are in progress to frustrate the scheme. Guerrilla parties are becoming more and more audacious. On Friday night, they were as close to our lines as Bailey's Cross Roads, Fall's Church and Munson's Hill, at each of which places they committed depredations. Washington was excited with rumors on Saturday and yesterday respecting retrogade movements on the part of LEE and the advance of MEADE, but nothing definite on either point has reached us.

abstract: ONE HUNDRED YEARS OLD.--The friends of Messrs. JOHN TRIMBLE and JACOB VALENTINE, on Friday evening, were guests at the residence of the latter, No. 115 East Twelfth-street. The occasion was a most interesting one, being the one hundredth birthday of Mrs. HULDAH WOOD, the grandmother of
lead_paragraph: ONE HUNDRED YEARS OLD. -- The friends of Messrs. JOHN TRIMBLE and JACOB VALENTINE, on Friday evening, were guests at the residence of the latter, No. 115 East Twelfth-street. The occasion was a most interesting one, being the one hundredth birthday of Mrs. HULDAH WOOD, the grandmother of Mrs. VALENTINE and Mr. TRIMBLE. The venerable lady is in the possession of her faculties, has never worn glasses in her life, enjoys good health and persists in devoting herself to a portion of household duties. She has lived to see six generations of her family, and has a remarkable remembrance of the early as also of the later scenes and incidents of her life. Surrounded by care and tenderly watched, the pleasant probabilities are that a number of years yet remain to her.

abstract: Denial of Communication with the South
snippet: Denial of Communication with the South
lead_paragraph: -- FERNANDO WOOD, in a letter from Washington dated the 9th, denies that he has "had any interest in or connection with any business transaction, direct or indirect, with the South for the last ten years." This denial is made in consequence of the publication of Mr. G.B. LAMAR's letter to him proposing a partnership in a project for running the blockade -- LAMAR agreeing to furnish the ship and cargo, to take charge of the whole business, to share expenses equally, and then to divide the profits, WOOD's share in the transaction being simply to "negotiate" for "permission, tacit or written," to run the blockade -- in plain English, to bribe the officers of the blockading squadron. As the letter was intercepted on its way, it of course never reached Mr. WOOD's hands; if it had, we have no reason to doubt that he would have been quite as indignant that any gentleman with whom he "dined in 1861" should make him such a proposition, as he now is that the letter should have been "intercepted, opened and given to the newspapers." We beg to assure him, however, notwithstanding the very natural doubt which he expresses, that the letter is genuine. If it could do him or the public any particular good, and we were at liberty to do so, we should gladly satisfy his curiosity as to the manner in which the document missed its destination, and reached our hands instead of his. As it is, however, he must excuse us for not doing so.

abstract: KINGS COUNTY POLITICS.--The Democratic primary meetings are to be held this evening, at which time Ward officers will also be nominated wherever they can be agreed upon. The City Convention will meet on Tuesday afternoon, for the purpose of
lead_paragraph: KINGS COUNTY POLITICS. -- The Democratic primary meetings are to be held this evening, at which time Ward officers will also be nominated wherever they can be agreed upon. The City Convention will meet on Tuesday afternoon, for the purpose of nominating candidates for Mayor, Street Commissioner and Justice for the Fifth District. BENJAMIN PRINCE and MARTIN KALBFLEISCH, the present incumbent, are the only contestants for the Mayoralty nomination and the chances thus far appear about even. It is barely possible that both will be thrown overboard, and a new man taken up. Should Mr. PRINCE be nominated, it appears to be Mr. KALBFLEISCH's determination to run in opposition. In that event he will receive the support of the War Democrats and the Republicans, who are indisposed to make a nomination should such a result ensue. The CountyConvention will meet on Wednesday. The contest will be on the County Judgship. Hon. SAMUEL GARRISON, JAMES TROY and Supervisor BLOOM are the candidates. The Assembly Conventions will meet the day following. The Republican Union Assembly Conventions have nominated CORNELIUS MCARDLE for the Fourth District, JOSEPH R. THOMPSON for the 81th District, and JACOB WORTH for the Seventh District. The remaining nominations will be made during the week.

abstract: Failure of Volunteering in
snippet: Failure of Volunteering in
lead_paragraph: The argument which the Copperheads chiefly plied in their opposition to the Government draft, was its absolute uselessness. They protested with all their vehemence that the wants of the army could he easily supplied try volunteering, stimulated by reasonable bounties. It was, as they represented, simply a love of oppression and tyranny that impelled the Government to impose compulsory army service upon the free citizen. They used this pretence, as a lash of scorpions, to drive the people into phrenzy. This was the thing, as used by the demagogues of this City in the Press, on the platform, and at the street corners, which produced the terrible July riots.

abstract: The steamship of Baltimore from Liverpool Sept. 30, via Queenstown Oct. 1, passed Cape Race on Friday morning. The news is two days later. From the brief summary telegraphed we learn that a report was current to the effect that the mission of ALEXANDER H. STEPHENS to France was to settle upon terms with the Emperor for the recognition of the South on an emancipation basis. The London Times publishes an absurd rumor, probably based upon the representations of Ex-Senator GWIN, formerly of California, but recently of Richmond, Va., that the Golden State was desirous of seceding and joining the Mexican Empire. The delegation from Mexico were to have had an interview with MAXIMILIAN on the 3d. for the purpose of tendering him the crown which he would formally accept. The proposition is said to have been made to the other Western Powers by England to ignore Russia's title to Poland, on the ground that she had violated the treaties of 1815. The late speech of Senator SUMNER, on our Foreign Relations, had been very generally commented on by the English Press. Mr. MASON had at last left London for Paris. The latest commercial advices via Queenstown report the Liverpool Cotton market firmer, but prices unchanged. Provisions were also firm, but Breadstuffs remained quiet. Consols closed at 93 3/8 for money.

abstract: Cor. of Sec. Cameron, >amp;c., on Maryland Election and Seizure of Disloyal Legislators; Maryland Legislature and Election--Correspondence on Seizure of Disloyal Members in 1861
snippet: Cor. of Sec. Cameron, >amp;c., on Maryland Election and Seizure of Disloyal Legislators; Maryland Legislature and Election--Correspondence on Seizure of Disloyal Members in 1861
lead_paragraph: It is well known that in several of the Southern States acts of secession were passed in defiance of the will of the people. The Virginia Convention contained a decided majority of members elected expressly as Union men, and yet by bribery, intimidation, cheating and every political trick which desperate and unscrupulous traitors could possibly devise, a majority of the Convention was induced to pass a secession ordinance, and the people of the State were thus betrayed into the rebel Confederacy. Similar devices were used in other Southern States. It is notorious that in the Fall of 1861 the rebels intended to get possession of Maryland in the same manner -- the secession members of the Legislature that was to meet in September being relied on to take the necessary preliminary steps. Fortunately for the people of Maryland, as well as for the country at large, the Government became aware of these treasonable schemes, and took prompt and effectual measures to defeat them. How it was done may be seen in part from the following letters and orders issued at the time by the Secretary of War, by Gen. MCCLELLAN, by Gen. BANKS and other officers of the Government. It is not too much to say that if the Government could have acted with equal vigor and promotness in the case of Virginia and some other States, they would have been spared the ruin and desolation which the double treachery of their own leaders has brought upon them.

abstract: Rebel Strategy
snippet: Rebel Strategy
lead_paragraph: The present aspect of military affairs is one which may well absorb the most earnest attention of the official managers of the war. The very fact that the rebels are really hard pressed engages them the more to make good by strategem what they have already lost by force. In the mere hard pounding of actual battle we are not afraid to put any of our armies against an equal force of theirs; but it must be acknowledged that in the ruses and wiles of war, in combinations prepared with an admirable secrecy and executed with marvelous celerity, they have always excelled. This is a moment peculiarly favorable for a new and unexpected military coup, and we have very little doubt that they are now laying a mine whose explosion will startle the country, and may do much to restore the rebel military status to the height at which it stood before our Summer successes.

lead_paragraph: State elections take place to-morrow in Pennsylvania and Ohio. Both will be of the utmost interest and importance, as embodying the verdict of two of the largest and most powerful States in the Union upon the question of prosecuting the war until the military power of the rebel Confederacy is completely broken. The canvas in both States has been conducted with vigor and energy, and it is scarcely possible that the issue should not be distinctly and generally understood. No intelligent man can doubt that if the rebellion is to be quelled at all, it must be by force of arms. No peace can possibly be had except by giving up the Union or by beating the rebel armies. The country must take its choice between these two methods. Either of these ways will give us peace. If we concede independence to the rebels, they will stop fighting, -- because they will then have gained what they are fighting for. If we destroy their armies and occupy their strong military positions, they will stop because they can't help themselves.

lead_paragraph: The rentree of Miss KELLOGG on Friday night in VERDI's charming Opera of "Rigoletto," was certainly the leading event of Mr. MARETZEK'S opening week at the Academy of Music. "Roberto Devereux" was not a success, and the second performance was received as tamely as the first. This result is attributable mainly to Signor BELLINI, who has the misfortune to be always sick when any special effort is expected at his hands. The role which he had to abandon on Wednesday night is one of the strong features of the opera, and would have displayed his grand voice to the greatest perfection. As it was the public yawned, felt disappointed, and went home grumbling about DONIZETTI, forgetting hat it was the singer, and not the composer, who was at fault. On Wednesday the "house" was neither so full nor so brilliant as on the opening night. Both occasions were eclipsed on Friday, when Miss KELLOGG returned to our stage, and achieved what she is always entitled to, a genuine artistic success. Her performance of the difficult role of the heroine was characterized by the most graceful perception of its dramatic opportunities, and by a complete and thorough interpretation of the music. We were glad to remark that the lady's voice was stronger and more manageable than we ever remember to have heard it. The protracted bronchial trouble which prevented her singing last season has happily terminated without ill consequences, and the long rest which it has necessitated seems indeed to have been of positive benefit to her. The opera was excellently rendered by the company. Signor MAZZOLENT sang superbly, and brought down a torrent of applause in an introduced romanza from "I Lomdardi," (La mia Letizia.) Signor BARILI sustained the part of the Jester with a great deal of dramatic ability, and Mile. SULZER, although her voice lacks color, sang the contralto part very well. The orchestra and chorus were thoroughly good; indeed the performance was all that could be desired or expected of the forces now at the Academy, and will, we hope, be repeated. To-night VERDI's "Ernami" will be produced. This opera was given, it will be remembered, with immense effect last season.

abstract: The specific issue of the approaching election in this State is the merit or demerit of Gov. SEYMOUR'S official conduct. All personal considerations respecting the candidates vanish before this one supreme concern.
lead_paragraph: The specific issue of the approaching election in this State is the merit or demerit of Gov. SEYMOUR'S official conduct. All personal considerations respecting the candidates vanish before this one supreme concern. The national questions have no force independently of this, for Gov. SEYMOUR'S record is made up of practical applications of all the opposing principles and policies. He has been almost the only opponent of the Administration in high place, and our people thereby have had the peculiar advantage of seeing with their own eyes how such opposition works. They have viewed it for the last ten months, and are now to pronounce upon it.

lead_paragraph: By the arrival at this port last evening of the steamship City of Baltimore, from Liverpool on the 30th inst., we have full files of European journals, from which we make up an interesting budget additional to that received by telegraph and published yesterday. The speech of Lord JOHN RUSSELL on American topics we present in extenso, and it will be found well worthy of attentive perusal. The London Times of the 30th contains a memorial from the Manchester Southern C[???], addressed to Earl RUSSELL, asking him to make representations at Washington against the unrelenting and exterminating character of the war. To this document the Secretary of Foreign Affairs had replied that he feared no representation of the British Government would do good, but that he would instruct Lord LYONS to report on the statements made in the memorial.

abstract: Gen. MCCLELLAN, having been accused of being favorable to the reflection of Gov. CURTIN in the election in Pennsylvania, which occurs to-day, has written a letter, which we give this morning, saying that this is incorrect, and that he favors the election of Judge WOODWARD, the Democratic candidate. He says he understands Judge W. to be in favor of the decisive and energetic prosecution of the war, until the military power of the rebellion is destroyed; but also that the war should be directed in accordance with the principles of humanity and civilization, and that its sole object is the restoration of the Union, the Constitution and the laws.

abstract: A SAD FAMILY BEREAVEMENT A BROTHER AND SISTER DIE ON THE SAME DAY. Last week a sadly thrilling event took place in the family of one who was, while living, a citizen of the highest respectability and worth, Mr. PETER McLOUGHLIN.
lead_paragraph: A SAD FAMILY BEREAVEMENT -- A BROTHER AND SISTER DIE ON THE SAME DAY. -- Last week a sadly thrilling event took place in the family of one who was, while living, a citizen of the highest respectability and worth, Mr. PETER MCLOUGHLIN. On the decease of this gentleman, which took place some few years since, he left two children, MARY ANN and THOMAS. The former, last November, married Mr. JOHN BAGLEY, of this City, and has since resided in Madison-street. The brother THOMAS was sent nearly the same date to St. Joseph's College, in Pennsylvania, in order to pursue his studies, and prepare himself by diligent application for any duties which might devolve upon him in after life. On Friday morning last both died, one at college and the other in New-York, after being sick for some three weeks previous. The douple funeral took place yesterday. High Mass was celebrated at St. Teresa's Roman Catholic Church, corner of Rutger and Henry streets, at 10 o'clock in the morning. Rev. Father BOYCE, pastor of the church. Rev. Father INMAGHAU, of Pennsylvania, and Rev. Father MCLAUGHLIN, of New-Rochelle, officiated at the mass. The latter gentleman delivered an excellent and impressive funeral sermon. The church was crowded, and the occasion was a peculiarly solemn one. It was indeed a rare scene to witness that of the obsequies of two young persons allied so closely by the ties of relationship.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The opera of "Ernani" was not performed last evening, in consequence of the continued indisposition of Signor MAZZOLENI -- who was suddenly seized with almost absolute extinction of voice on Saturday night. In its stead RELLINI's "Norma" was given -- a work in which the ladies of the company are always heard to the greatest advantage. Mme. MEDORI sings and acts superbly as the Druidess, and Mlle. SULZER is thoroughly admirable as Adalgisa. The grand duet in the second act received the best of treatment from these artists, and was rapturously applauded. Signor BIACHI, as Oroveso, sang with much spirit, and liberally revealed the wealth of his voice. The tenor part was intrusted hastily to Signor TAMARO, who sang it with taste and discretion. For such a role he is more than sufficient. The choruses and orchestra were good.
lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The opera of "Ernani" was not performed last evening, in consequence of the continued indisposition of Signor MAZZOLENI -- who was suddenly seized with almost absolute extinction of voice on Saturday night. In its stead RELLINI's "Norma" was given -- a work in which the ladies of the company are always heard to the greatest advantage. Mme. MEDORI sings and acts superbly as the Druidess, and Mlle. SULZER is thoroughly admirable as Adalgisa. The grand duet in the second act received the best of treatment from these artists, and was rapturously applauded. Signor BIACHI, as Oroveso, sang with much spirit, and liberally revealed the wealth of his voice. The tenor part was intrusted hastily to Signor TAMARO, who sang it with taste and discretion. For such a role he is more than sufficient. The choruses and orchestra were good.

abstract: The startling report receives us from Washington that the whole rebel army has crossed the Rapidan, and that Gen. MEADE has fallen back to the north bank of the Rappahannock.
lead_paragraph: The startling report receives us from Washington that the whole rebel army has crossed the Rapidan, and that Gen. MEADE has fallen back to the north bank of the Rappahannock. When our forces retired from Culpepper they burned such stores as could not be conveniently carried away, in order to prevent them falling into the hands of the enemy. The rebels are said to have commenced the passage of the Rapidan on Thursday last, moving in the direction of Madison Courthouse, as stated yesterday, with the evident intention of turning Gen. MEADE's right wing. Heavy cavalry forces have been sent to our front to dislodge the rebels, who are said to be holding all the gaps in the Bull Run Mountains.

abstract: THE LATE ATTEMPT TO BREAK JAIL. -- The attempt to break jail on Monday night, as has since transpired, was a regular plot laid by some of the worst characters now imprisoned and awaiting trial for various offences. A man named SPENCER, who is charged with counterfeiting, is supposed to be the leader. Preparations had long since been made to overpower the keeper on the first opportunity that presented itself, break off the lock, or take the key and open the gate leading to the corridor, and when once in the yard to scale the fence and escape. Some fifty prisoners are confined on the corridor where the outbreak occurred, many of them desperate characters. All were in the secret, having communicated with such other through the sewer pipes which run from one cell to the other. POWERS, MCGARVY and SPENCER made the assault on the keeper as soon as he opened the cell door to admit another prisoner. It was their intention to disable, if not to kill him. One of the party struck him with a bar of iron, and another attempted to choke him, by drawing a handkerchief across his neck. The handkerchief not being strong enough for the purpose, broke, and the keeper, although nearly senseless, managed to seek safety in the cell his assailants had just vacated. MAY had taken the key of the outer gate from him, and also the keys of the cells. MAY then locked him in, and proceeded to release the other prisoners. A few colored men and boys refused to come out of their cells or to take any part in the master IGNAUZ RYTZKY, condemned for the murder of SIGISMUND FELLNER, the diamond merchant, also remained in his quarters, declining to aid the mutineers, but instead, succeeded in saving the keeper's life, and preventing the prisoners from escaping, by informing them that the jail was surrounded by policemen -- that every passage outside was guarded, -- and that it would be useless for them to get beyond the walls. One policeman having accidentally made his appearance at the gate, rendered RATZKY's statement plausible, and the prisoners at once desisted. Had they known that there was no person there except that solitary policeman, they might have easily accomplished their purpose. After some delay several officers arrived, and the door being opened with a duplicate key, the imprisoned jailor was released, and the prisoners were continued in closer and more secure quarters. Mr. ISAAC MESSERGIE, the keeper, was found to be seriously injured. Dr. VAN ZANDT was called to his aid, and bound up his wounds. He will doubtless recover, although he will necessarily be continued to his house for some time. The District Attorney intends to draw up new indictments against the ringleader of the revolt.

abstract: The visit to the Institutions, by invitation of the Commissioners of Public Charities and Corrections, came off yesterday, and was enjoyed by a large number of guests. The parties for whom it was specially intended were the officers of the different foreign war-vessels in the harbor, the foreign Ministers, Consuls and other dignitaries in the City. Portions of the company, about 10 o'clock A.M., left Pier No. 1, East River, in the steamer John Romer, and another portion joined them at Bellevue. Among those who availed themselves of the invitation were the British Admiral MILER, the French Admiral REYNAUD, and the officers of their fleets; Count DE SANDOVAC, Commander of Moro Castle, Cuba; Count DE GEORGI [???]SR[???]N, Minister, and Vice-Consul H. KENAN, Capt. DEL SANTO, Royal Italian Navy; M. DE COURPOIS, Deputy French Consul at Boston; Chevalier B[???]TMAL[???], Hay[???]en Minister, and a number of other foreigners. Admiral FARRAGUT was present, as were a host of other prominent citizens.

snippet: Mozart and Tammany, Insurrection in
lead_paragraph: There is insurrection in Mozart Hall -- insurrection in Tammany. The Faubourg St. Antoine of the Democratic party is arming itself against the Faubourg St. Germain, and of the issue there can be no doubt. The snobs of the St. Germain will go to the wall. The working, voting, victory-winning masses of the party have never yet been defeated. Already the tocsins are pealing from every political steeple, and barricades are being made of City railroad cars across all the main avenues leading to power and place.

abstract: The United States vs. The steamer Kate. -- This vessel was captured on Aug. 1, 1863, off New-Inlet, N.C., by the steamers Iroquois, Mount Vernon and Niphon. The proofs showed that the vessel was chased by the blockading squadron off Wilmington, and was driven ashore on July 12, where she was stripped of her lading, rigging and machinery by the rebels, and, being afterward found afloat, was captured by the squadron.

abstract: Is PHELAN yet able to vanquish SEEREITER, is a mooted question, which can be answered by the result of the contest between them, at the Ti[???]g testimonial, at Irving Hall, this afternoon. Of course, SEEREITER is in his best play, as he has been weeks training for his trial with KAVANAGH for the championship, while PHELAN has only played an occasional game; yet good judges are of the opinion that the Father of Billiards will come out first best. Several other first-class players are in the programme for the afternoon, when it is expected the ladies will be present in force. In the evening the champion. KAVANAGH, contends with TIEMAN, and among the other novelties is a trial at the French game by Mons. ISIDORE and ESTEPHE. Nearly all the players were in town last evening, and from appearances the testimonial will be a great success.

abstract: The sacrifice of Judges HILTON and BOSWORTH is complete, so far as Tammany can make it. The Judgship of the Common Pleas has been handed over to the Mozart faction, in which, amongst the leaders, Judge HILTON has no friends. Judge BOSWORTH's place on the bench is now in debate between City Judge MCCUNN and a Mr. CARDOZA, who is pressed by one section of the Mozart leaders, aided and abetted by Mr. Alderman FARLEY, of the Tammany wing. Surrogate TUCKER is in more danger than his friends seem aware of. By uniting with Brother BEN WOOD against FERNANDO, on the nomination of JOHN MCCOOL for Register, he has incurred the enmity of Sheriff LYNCH, Mr. MAT. GOODERSON, Mr. BEN. RAY and others of that ilk, who were in favor of Mr. TOM. HEN. FERRIS for the office. Mr. JOHN DECKER, Chief Engineer of the Fire Department, is thus thrown out of the two regularly accredited organizations; and must run for Register as the candidate of the "New-York," "Jeffersonian," and all the allied sore-heads of the Democratic party. He is a a strong man; and with ten thousand firemen and exempts behind him, or Mr. JOHN S. GILES, (also a possible sore-head candidate for this office,) his competition may become formidable, and will certainly give strength to whatever ticket he may run upon. The revolt of Sheriff LYNCH and Mr. MAT. GOODERSON is believed to indicate the hostility of Judge BARNARD and Comptroller BRENNAN to Mr. TUCKER's reelection as Surrogate -- Sheriff LYNCH and GOODERSON both being in favor of Mr. SAM. JONES, Judge BARNARD's brother-in-law, for the office. Under the coalition as made, City Inspector BOOLE has a clear track for Mayor, so far as the united action of Mozart and Tammany can secure it. This is the chief point in which the City Railroad men of Tammany have been heavily defeated -- the non-success of Mr. S.B. GARVIN for Judge WHITE's place being another sore discouragement. There may yet be some slip between BOOLE's cup and his lip. His enemies are active, and his agency in securing a yearly revenue of $300,000 to the City in the Harlem-Broadway Railroad will not lightly be forgiven, and can never be forgotten. The Tammany self-elect had everything "arranged" at Albany to secure this grant to themselves, without one cent of compensation to the City for the injury to be thus inflicted upon our most beautiful thoroughfare. Mr. BOOLE suddenly put in his oar and settled, that, if any rail-track was to be laid in Broadway, the City should receive a yearly revenue equal to many millions bonus, for the privilege, -- the probabilities being that the rival claims thus created will keep Broadway out of the clutches of any City railroad managers, either "Harlem" or "Peter Guese," for many long years to come.

abstract: A short time since it was stated in the TIMES that a reenrollment in those districts where only half the claimed quotas was drawn, would soon be ordered, and that the preliminary steps had been taken at Washington. This was denied in some of the papers, and in one on the authority of Col. NUGENT. Yesterday, this gentleman issued orders, in pursuance of instructions from Washington, to the Boards of Enrollment of the Second, Third, Fourth, Fifth and Sixth Districts to prepare forthwith to proceed with a reenrollment of those Districts. These are the ones to the enrollment and quotas of which Gov. SEYMOUR made objections. On such objection the President assented to a reenrollment and directed only fifty per cent. of the quotas claimed to be drawn. The President also gave to Gov. SEYMOUR the permission to select some one to see that the reenrollment was fairly and correctly made.

The English Press comments freely on the recent great battles in Georgia, those which are ever willing to hail disaster to the Union arms regarding them as great victories for the rebels.
lead_paragraph: The arrival of the steamship Africa at St. Johns, N.F., from Liverpool on the 3d inst., puts as in possession of two days later news from Europe. The English Press comments freely on the recent great battles in Georgia, those which are ever willing to hail disaster to the Union arms regarding them as great victories for the rebels. The London Daily News, one of the staunchest friends of the North, while commending BRAGG's policy of concentration, by which alone he has been enabled to check ROSECRANS, still insists that he must effect much more ere he can be said to have achieved any solid and lasting advantage. From France, the news is still unfavorable for Southern recognition. The Paris Siecle, an influential leading journal, intimates that if the rebel Commissioner STEPHENS comes to Paris expecting to procure the recognition of the South, he will meet with great disappointment, since the period for that event, if it ever existed, has passed by. The Confederates, in aiming their negroes, acknowledge that their means of resistance are exhausted. The Archduke MAXIMILIAN has replied to the Mexican deputation, who have waited upon him with a formal offer of the throne, that he is willing to accept it, if tendered by a free, spontaneous and genuine expression of the people of Mexico, coupled with some guarantee for the integrity and independence of that country. In the Liverpool market, Cotton was buoyant, Breadstuffs steady, and Provisions quiet. Consuls 93 [???]@93 1/2. The Confederate loan had advanced 1 [???] cent.

abstract: There was further skirmishing on Monday on the north bank of the Rappahannock, from which it is evident that the rebel advance is up to the line of the river. MEADE'S army, as announced by us yesterday, is now north of the Rappahan-...
lead_paragraph: There was further skirmishing on Monday on the north bank of the Rappahannock, from which it is evident that the rebel advance is up to the line of the river. MEADE'S army, as announced by us yesterday, is now north of the Rappahannock, but this movement was decided upon some time ago in event of threatening demonstrations on the part of LEE. It is represented that the fighting thus far has been purely on our side at least by cavalry, and by artillery supports, the main army not having been engaged. The loss in GREGG's cavalry division is said to be severe, the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Pennsylvania and Tenth New-York suffering most.

abstract: His indorsement of Judge Woodward
snippet: His indorsement of Judge Woodward
lead_paragraph: Gen. MCCLELLAN, who was so slow in the military field, is rather faster in the political. We have at last a dash from him -- a regular slap-dash. At his retreat in New Jersey, he learns from "a reliable gentlemen" that there is danger that the Copperhead line will not come up to the scratch; and he no sooner hears of it than he speeds, as he never sped before, to the rescue. The lightning could not outstrip him; or, if it did, it was only to carry the message that Gen. MCCLELLAN was only a little behind, and that "he regards the election of Judge WOODWARD, as Governor of Pennsylvania, to be called for by the interests of the nation." The tidings reached Philadelphia just as the sun was descending beyond the Schuylkill -- thirteen hours and three quarters, by the best watches, before the opening of the fight. The shades of night, we understand, were used, to the best purpose, in working the dirt. The engagement commenced with sunrise, and lasted through the day, with terrible effect, we hear, upon the followers of Judge WOODWARD. They are routed, it is said, horse, foot and dragoons. Gen. MCCLELLAN, it is expected, will reach the field in person to-morrow.

abstract: CHESS MATTERS. -- The chess-playing season opens this month, and, from present appearances, there is going to be lively times in chess circles in this City this Winter. On Wednesday last the annual meeting of the Paulsen Club, of this City, took place, on which occasion the following officers were elected to preside over its affairs for the ensuing season: President, EUGENE BREUZINGER; Vice-President, D. WATERMAN; Secretary,. F. HALLERBACH; Treasurer, Mr. WALLACH. On Wednesday evening next, Mr. BORCH, the noted German blindfold player, will attempt the difficult mental feat of playing ten games simultaneously, without seeing the men or boards. The games will be played at the [???] of the Paulsen Club, No. 186 Bowery, near, Stanton-street, and on this occasion all chess players are invited to visit the rooms of the Club. The contestants against Mr. BORCH will be selected at the rooms at 8 P.M., from among those present. On Saturday last, the following officers were elected at the annual meeting of the Brooklyn Club; President, F. PERRIN, Vice-President, E. MATHEWS; Secretary, Capt. RAYMOND; Treasurer, G. BAXTER; Tournament Committee, Messrs. THOMPSON, RAYMOND and HORNER. The Club tournament will commence next month, at their new rooms. Matches are to take place this season between the New-York, Brooklyn and Paulsen Clubs, which bid fair to be very interesting chess events.

abstract: This vessel, which was commenced some weeks ago at Mr. ROWLAND's yard at Greenpoint, is progressing rapidly. She was designed by Chief Engineer STIMERS, U.S.N., and is intended for river and harbor navigation. She is 225 feet long, 45 feet wide, and 9 feet depth of hold. The Cohoes is of peculiar construction. There is an immense hull, outside of which there is another hull, the space between them forming water-tight compartments; outside of the outer hull is the wooden bulwarks and iron armor. The compartments are capable of being flooded and pumped out if necessary, so as to lighten her. The inner vessel is able to float without the aid of the outer hull, if it should be damaged by a ram or projectile. The internal sides are square with the bottom, which is perfectly flat the whole length and width of the vessel. The sides will be 6 1/2 feet thick, including the compartments, timber and 3 inches of iron plating. The frame and inner hall are already completed. The revolving turret will be 20 feet in diameter and 8 inches thick of solid iron. The accomodations for the officers are forward, and those for the sailors are placed in juxtaposition. She will be driven by two propellers. Her armament will consist of two 150-pounders. Her speed is expected to be 6 knots; it is probable that she may make 8 knots, which is very good speed for this class of vessels. The decks will be bomb proof -- 15 inches of solid timber with a coating of iron one inch in thickness.

abstract: its advantages and dangers
snippet: its advantages and dangers
lead_paragraph: DE TOCQUEVILLE was the first to call attention to the enormous gain to humanity that would result from the success of the political experiment which we were making on this continent, from the single fact that it would accustom great and powerful communities to submit their differences to judicial arbitrament, and would make it a point of honor with them to abide by legal precedents, instead of resorting to the sword. To know what this Federal system of ours, if it can only be perpetuated, will save the inhabitants of this continent in money and bloodshed, we have only to study the history of Europe during the last six centuries. We do not mean to say that it is probable that, without the Union, we should have here a faithful repetition of all the horrors through which Europe has passed since the Crusades, because the advance of civilization and the stronger hold of the precepts of Christianity on men of all classes, would give our wars a tinge of gentleness and humanity by which those of the Old World were not marked until our day. But we should have among us in full activity the very cause which has led to all European wars since the close of the Fourteenth century -- the fears of the smaller States of the predominance of the larger ones, expressed in the struggles on behalf of what is so well known as "the balance of power." Once cut the States loose from each other, or cut the Union up into several Confederacies, and you call into play the very passions to which the world owed the Thirty Years' War, the wars between LOUIS XIV, and WILLIAM III., the war of MARLBOROUGH, the war of 1756, and the wars of the French Empire. You rouse between each political community the spirit of hostile rivalry; the love of domination among the strong, and the fear of conquest and oppression among the weak. The larger States would find in their strength and resources a justification for seeking to extend their territory; the smaller ones would find in their weakness a fair excuse for entering into combinations for self-defence, and even in seeking safety in foreign alliances. There would be incessant intrigue, jealousy, and recrimination, and, as a general consequence, incessant hostilities, or -- what is almost as fatal to prosperity -- incessant fears of hostilities. Any arrangement which saves all this, let its imperfections be what they may, is certainly worth all the sacrifices which any one generation can make for it.

abstract: BROOKLYN DEMOCRATIC CITY CONVENTION -- NOMINATIONS OF MAYOR AND STREET COMMISSIONER. -- The Brooklyn Democratic City Convention met at the "Senate," in Fulton-street, yesterday afternoon at 3 o'clock, and effected a temporary organization by selecting Mr. WM.B. PARKS as Chairman. The list of delegates was then called, and it was found that 14 out of the 20 Wards were contested. The entire time until 8 o'clock P.M. was occupied in deciding between the contestants. At length, all those entitled being admitted, Mr. WM.S. LEECH was elected permanent Chairman. An informal ballot was taken for Mayor with the following result:

abstract: It was difficult to tell the precise import of the heavy cavalry skirmishing which has been going on since Saturday last in the space between the Rapidan and Rappahannock rivers. The fact, however, that Gen. MEADE thought fit to march the whole of his army to this side of the Rappahannock on Sunday, indicated that he considered himself menaced by something of far greater magnitude than STUART'S cavalry.
lead_paragraph: It was difficult to tell the precise import of the heavy cavalry skirmishing which has been going on since Saturday last in the space between the Rapidan and Rappahannock rivers. The fact, however, that Gen. MEADE thought fit to march the whole of his army to this side of the Rappahannock on Sunday, indicated that he considered himself menaced by something of far greater magnitude than STUART's cavalry. Indeed we know definitely that a corps of the rebel army attempted at the close of last week, by a rapid northern march along a line near the eastern base of the Blue Ridge, to get on the right flank of our army, which was then stationed at Culpepper Court-House; and we know that this movement was only prevented by a skillful manoeuvre on the part of Gen. MEADE, who quickly flung two corps forward from Culpepper to the Rapidan, and threatened, in turn, to get in the rebel rear, cut their communications, and otherwise embarrass them. It may be taken for granted, we judge, that LEE would never have attempted anything so daring as this flanking movement, unless he were prepared for battle, and considered himself able to cope with the army under Gen. MEADE.

abstract: The vote in Pennsylvania on Tuesday will probably dishearten a good many of Gen. MCCLELLAN's friends, by driving them to the conclusion that the General's dicta on political affairs do not possess as much influence, even in the home of his youth, as they ought to possess. He said his say on the Pennsylvania election in the very nick of time, and yet the electors do not seem to have paid the least attention to it. His supporters will now probably conclude that this afflicted country is on the verge of its ruin, because it has rejected his advice in one of the most critical periods of its history. But we feel bound to warn both him and them against taking the matter too much to heart. He is not the first great military chief who has found himself out of place in the arena of politics. JULIUS CAESAR, BELISARIUS, the Great CONDE, DUMONT, WELLINGTON and CAVAIGNAC, are all conspicuous proofs that no amount of ability in war will secure a man success in the turmoil and strife of the forum. The art of managing men in the field has hardly anything in common with the art of managing them at the stump and the polls, and, considering how rarely the world is blessed with the presence of an universal genius, it is no disgrace to any man to possess the one without the other.

The Committees consisted of one of each party from each Ward. Upon an organization being effected, a sub-committee of five from each of the general conference committees present were appointed to report a basis of agreement, who, after a a short deliberation, reported the following programme: T[???]mmany to take the Fourth and Seventh Senatorial Districts, and the First, Second, Tenth, Eleventh, Twelfth, Thirteenth, and Fourteenth Assembly Districts; Mozart to take the remaining Districts.

abstract: There is no longer room for doubting, notwithstanding the incompleteness of the returns, that the elections held in Pennsylvania and Ohio last Tuesday have resulted in the success of the Union ticket by immense majorities. The probability is that Gov. CURTIN in Pennsylvania has beaten WOODWARD by from 20,000 to 25,000 votes, as the returns thus far exhibit a steady gain over the vote of 1860.
lead_paragraph: There is no longer room for doubting, notwithstanding the incompleteness of the returns, that the elections held in Pennsylvania and Ohio last Tuesday have resulted in the success of the Union ticket by immense majorities. The probability is that Gov. CURTIN in Pennsylvania has beaten WOODWARD by from 20,000 to 25,000 votes, as the returns thus far exhibit a steady gain over the vote of 1860. In Ohio, VALLANDIGHAM, as every sensible person believed, has been overwhelmingly beaten. Cincinnati, which usually gives a handsome Democratic majority, now gives 5,000 majority for BROUGH. and the returns from nearly every part of the State are all in the same direction.The home vote alone gives BROUGH a majority of about 50,000, which will probably be swelled by the vote of the soldiers to 100,000.

lead_paragraph: A NEW DODGE. -- Last week a man entered the cigar-store of Mr. COOK, on Broadway, while that gentleman had gone to dinner. He made inquiry of the lad in charge for Mr. COOK, and especially whether that was his usual hour for dinner, having, as he with apparent impatience said, called the day before, and not found him in. He was answered and left. A few days since he called at the store at the same hour, and when Mr. COOK was again at dinner, exclaiming when he came in, as though addressing Mr. COOK, that he (Mr. COOK) "had not sent those cigars home." On finding the gentleman not in, he appeared annoyed, and told the boy that he had bought and paid for six boxes of cigars, which his employer had promised to send to No. 38 Lispenard-st. before 11 A.M. Looking around, he recognized a pile of six boxes as the ones he had bought, said he would take them home himself, and called for twine. The lad, off his guard by this matter of fact air, gave it. The man coolly tied the boxes together, put them under his arm and marched of, and that was the last seen of him or of the $60 worth.

abstract: speech at Cincinnati
snippet: speech at Cincinnati
lead_paragraph: Hon. SALMON P. CHASE, Secretary of the Treasury, arrived at Cincinatti on Monday last, on a brief vacation visit, and was welcomed most enthusiastically by an immense crowd of citizens, who greeted him at the railroad depot with salvos of artillery and a grand military and civic procession. The distinguished visitor was then escorted to the Burnet House, where, notwithstanding the drawback of a heavy rain, the crowd was considerably augmented and bent on having a speech. In a few moments Mr. CHASE appeared on the balcony, and was greeted with lively cheering.

abstract: As the mountain  would not come to MOHAMMED, the Prophet had to go to the mountain; and, in like manner as Admiral DAHLGREN seems disinclined
lead_paragraph: -As the mountain would not come to MOHAMMED, the Prophet had to go to the mountain; and, in like manner as Admiral DAHLGREN seems disinclined to enter Charleston harbor and try the quality of the rebel torpedoes, the torpedoes themselves have been sailing out to test the power of the iron-clads. The expedition of the infernal machine against the Ironsides, whereof we give full accounts from our special correspondent, was certainly a very bold affair, and a little of the spirit that brought that daring party out in their little cigar-shaped craft would have carried our iron fleet into Charleston long ago. It is difficult to estimate the precise bearing which this single experiment has on the general question of the capacity of the iron-clads to withstand the explosion of torpedoes. We are told that the torpedo in question held a charge of sixty pounds of powder, and being exploded directly amidships of the Ironsides, left her wholly uninjured. This is a test whose exact value the professional men will best appreciate; but we suppose it will hardly be claimed that sixty pounds of powder might not be exploded in contact with an iron vessel, which would produce a very different effect. Besides, the condition of floating torpedoes, such as this, and fixed torpedoes, such as those with which Charleston harbor is said to be sown, (and which would explode directly under the vessel,) are widely different. In the meantime, we cannot but hope that the naval chief of the expedition will quickly get ready to experiment, as well as to be experimented upon.

abstract: Not victories in the field, but better yet -- at the ballot-box. It is strictly true that the most glorious triumphs over the rebels -- Donelson, Antietam, Gettysburgh, Vicksburgh -- were of less moment than the victories over the Copperheads gained at the polls, in Pennsylvania and Ohio, last Tuesday. The battle won in the field of blood to-day might be lost on the next week or the next day; but that won at the ballot-box stands. Tuesday's work secured loyal Governors for the great States of Ohio and Pennsylvania for two and three years to come. No vicissitudes of fortune can lake away the fruits of these great successes. Combined with similar results in the other leading States, they in fact put the triumph of the national cause beyond all contingency. From the beginning it has been certain that the North had a strength sufficient to subdue the rebellion, and sure to do it if kept true to the Government. The only real danger has been that this strength would be divided and made of no effect, by the arts of seditious and factious men. The most untiring efforts have been made to accomplish this. Every machination known to political craft has been applied. The Confederate Generals who have fought against the Government have not displayed one whit more skill or perseverance than the Copperhead leaders who have intrigued against the Government. It is the grandest event of the times that these intrigues have been baffled by the intelligence and patriotism of the people. It is now substantially settled that the North, in all its official agencies, will stand firmly by the Government to the end of the war, and that its factious minority will remain powerless for mischief. The settlement of this fact was all that was wanted to settle the issue of the war itself.

abstract: ANOTHER DRAFT-ENROLLMENT ORDERED IN THE SECOND CONGRESSIONAL DISTRICT. -- On Tuesday noon Provost-Marshal MADDOX received orders from Washington to prepare for making a new enrollment in his district, which comprises the Sixth, Eighth, Ninth, Tenth, Twelfth, Fourteenth, Sixteenth, Seventeenth and Eighteenth Wards of Brooklyn, and the five country towns of Kings County. The original number called for was about 4,000, but the number was decreased on the representation of Gov. SEYMOUR, who thought the proportion excessive. As a result, this second enrollment is ordered to be made under the superintendence of State agents, appointed by the Governor, so that all may be known to be correct. And if the former enrollment is found to be right, another draft will be necessary to make up the deficiency now existing in the district.

abstract: We have news from Viginia this morning which is startling, if true. It is reported that Gen. MEADE'S Army after crossing the Rappahannock, has fallen back as far as Manassas Plains  that the Army of LEE has also crossed the Rappahannock that our army was stripping for the fight that a battle was imminent, and Washington rumor even adds that the struggle opened at daylight yesterday on the old Bull Run battle-ground.
lead_paragraph: We have news from Viginia this morning which is startling, if true. It is reported that Gen. MEADE's Army after crossing the Rappahannock, has fallen back as far as Manassas Plains -- that the Army of LEE has also crossed the Rappahannock -- that our army was stripping for the fight -- that a battle was imminent, and Washington rumor even adds that the struggle opened at daylight yesterday on the old Bull Run battle-ground. During last evening the telegraph was exceedingly reticent concerning the condition of affairs in Virginia, and little or nothing was allowed to pass over the wires. Our army trains on Tuesday night were all at Centreville. Another Washington story is that Gen. MEADE is to be displaced, but it is incredible that this should take place at present.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. The fine attendance yesterday evening, when PETRELLA'S Opera of "Ione" was given, recalled the best triumphs of last season. The house was fashionable and brilliant beyond the ordinary experience of the past week, and the quaint rhythms and vigorous instrumentation of the composer brought down, as of old, plenty of applause.
lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The fine attendance yesterday evening, when PETRELLA's Opera of "Ione" was given, recalled the best triumphs of last season. The house was fashionable and brilliant beyond the ordinary experience of the past week, and the quaint rhythms and vigorous instrumentation of the composer brought down, as of old, plenty of applause. Signor MAZZOLENI, whose loss of voice on Saturday last occasioned a panic in Fourteenth-street, was once more at his post. No indications of the contretemps were noticeable. The gentleman was in excellent voice, and went through the very laborious tenor role without visible fatigue. Signor BELLINI, too, happened to be in fine voice, so that with the cooperation of the prima donna, Mme. MEDORI, the performance was rendered thoroughly delightful. Mr. MARETZEK had to surrender his place in the orchestra to Senor NUNO, in consequence of a severe attack of indisposition. The auxiliary forces were well handled by this gentleman.

abstract: -- The Union men in the City are rapidly completing their list of nominations for the State Legislature and for county offices. In most instances all merely personal and party considerations yield readily to the paramount purpose of uniting all loyal votes in support of the Government. In one or two cases, we regret to see independent nominations made and accepted without due deference to the general sentiment and wish of those who have a right to be consulted. We trust that all who have the welfare of the country at heart will make all reasonable sacrifices of personal feeling to insure success.

abstract: The full height, breadth and depth of the delusions under which the South commenced this war will probably only be fully revealed alter most of the actors in it have been gathered to their fathers.
lead_paragraph: The full height, breadth and depth of the delusions under which the South commenced this war will probably only be fully revealed alter most of the actors in it have been gathered to their fathers. But we know enough of it already to be greatly puzzled by the extraordinary want of foresight and judgment displayed by the leaders in their calculation of the course likely to be pursued by Europe and the North. Their knowledge of the capacity and resources of their own people has been proved by events to have been exceedingly accurate and profound, but their ignorance of every other people seems to have been, for men of as much ability and shrewdness as they have undoubtedly shown themselves to possess, and for men who have, to an extent unknown amongst us, made politics and political history a lifelong study, curious in the last degree. Their principal errors, too, are of a kind that we should expect from what are commonly called "practical men" -- men of little education, to whom self-interest in its lowest sense is the key to all political problems, and by no means from persons who have studied politics in books. The notion, for instance, that the North, being a commercial community, devoted to the pursuit of gain, was for that reason sure not to fight, is rather the conclusion of a backwoodsman than of a student. The lesson of history is that commercial communities are amongst the most pugnacious and ambitious, and most obstinate of belligerents: -- witness Carthage, Venice, Genoa, Holland and England.

abstract: Proclamation on disloyal combinations
snippet: Proclamation on disloyal combinations
lead_paragraph: Many evil disposed persons are now engaged in endeavoring to produce disaffection toward the State Government, with the avowed purpose of overthrowing it by violence, if they shall be unable to accomplish their end by other means. They endeavor to attract other citizens to their support by the circulation of most unfounded statements and misrepresentations. Among this class of persons are to be found men who bear about with them commissions from the State Government, and many who have obtained notoriety only by the favor of that Government, while others of them have been removed from office, and still others have been refused office by that Government.

lead_paragraph: Yesterday morning, Admiral LISOVSKY, with a portion of the officers of his fleet, visited the public institutions, in pursuance of an invitation from the Commissioners of Public Charities and Corrections. The party was not large, most of the officers of the fleet being debarred by other engagements. The tour of inspection was pretty much the same as that made with the French and English officers on Tuesday, and afforded to the guests much interest. At Randall's Island, the distinguished guests were welcomed by the boys, one of whom made a very neat address, and which was cordially received by them. At Blackwell's Island the party were entertained at the house of the Warden. Over good cheer there was an interchange of kindly words and sentiments, and when the party broke up for return there was a general acknowledgment that the day had been one of great interest and enjoyment.

abstract: WINTER GARDEN. -- The play of "Ruy Blas" produced at this establishment Wednesday night, belongs to a period of VICTOR HUGO's career, when flushed with his victories over the formalists of the schools he had determined to carry the romantic drama to its greatest extent. Sentimentalism can hardly go further than in the character of the hero, unless we except the love-lorn flunkey of the more recent yellow-covered literature -- the Jeames who married his young mistress -- as a type of a high emotional nature. There are points of resemblance, indeed, between Ruy Blas and the last named character. When we become acquainted with him, he is in the guise of a serving-man. A noble by association he becomes a menial in order that he may be near the lady whom he is not at liberty to approach in any other way. This is none other than the Princess, shortly to become Queen of Spain by marriage with the monarch. One of Ruy's old associates. Don Caesar, recognizes him, and the recognition is witnessed by the evil genius of the play. Don Salluste, who also overhears the domestic's declaration of love. Don Salluste has recently been degraded, mainly through the Princess' means. He determines to be revenged, and uses Ruy Blas to effect his object. Assuming the title of Don Caesar, who in the meantime has been sent out of the way, he (Ruy) makes love to the Princess, and in the last scene has an interview with her which is sufficient to compromise her with her future husband. Don Salluste is, of course, a witness, but he is not permitted to enjoy his triumph. The despised menial turns upon him; a struggle ensues, and both are killed. The Princess, it is presumed, returns to the palace, and no one hears of her indiscretion.

abstract: Rev. H.W. BEECHER, who has returned from his tour of the Continent, accompanied by Rev. Dr. RAYMOND, spent Saturday evening in the Tabernacle House, Finsbury, to which Dr. CAMPBELL had invited a number of the leading ministers of the metropolis to meet him. The conversation mainly turned on the civil war now raging, on which Mr. BEECHER expressed himself with great frankness and confidence. Rev. JOHN GRAHAM and Rev. JOHN KENNEDY made pointed reference to some expressions ascribed to Mr. BEECHER about the time of the Trent discussion, when he was reported as having said, "They would bide their time till they had settled matters with the South, and then!" The report which reached England stopped there, but not so the speaker, who finished the sentence nearly as follows: "Then we will show England how we can forgive an injury, and heap coals of fire on the heads of those from whom it comes."

abstract: The semi-occasional sessions of the Court of Oyer and Terminer in this City, is an annoyance which ought to be abated. They not only do not facilitate but they actually obstruct the dispatch of criminal business. Take the present term for example.
lead_paragraph: The semi-occasional sessions of the Court of Oyer and Terminer in this City, is an annoyance which ought to be abated. They not only do not facilitate but they actually obstruct the dispatch of criminal business. Take the present term for example. On Monday last the October Term of the Oyer and Terminer commenced simultaneously with the October Term of the General Sessions. Thus far three cases have been disposed of by both courts. If the Sessions had been sitting alone, twice that number would have been tried, and the useless attendance of a score o jurors and witnesses, would have been avoided. It is a well known fact -- a fact not at all creditable to the legal profession -- that nine-tenths of the criminal practice of this City is confined to some half dozen lawyers. If two Courts are in session, it almost invariably happens that when a criminal is placed at the bar in one Court, the lawyer retained in the case is engaged, or expects to be engaged, in the other, and vice versa. The result is a hindrance to the prosecution of business in both Courts. The Court of General Sessions is the criminal Court of the City, and, with its two Judges, is abundantly capable of transacting all the criminal business of the county. The Supreme Court has more civil business than it can attend to without holding sessions of the Oyer and Terminer, and it rarely happens that a case is transferred to this Court from the General Sessions for any reason that would not be equally operative for a change of venue to some other county. There is, therefore, no occasion for sittings of the Oyer and Terminer in this county, and experience has shown that they can be dispensed with.

abstract: The condition of the Confederate finances and Confederate currency is causing the rebels an immense amount of trouble. Everything else in the South is at the control of the rebel leaders but this. JEFF. DAVIS writes about it, MEMMINGER ponders over it, WIGFALL spouts about it, the Confederate Congress enacts laws about it, and so does the Legislature of Virginia, while all the newspapers are in a condition of "confusion worse confounded" about it; but all of them together cannot force up or keep up the value of a Confederate dollar, or alter the relative price of provisions and their paper money. JEFF. DAVIS has a charming plan to "form societies of citizens to unite in an effort to restore and maintain the par value of the currency with gold, and to engage to sell and buy only at reduced prices." WIGFALL's plan or remedy will, he says, certainly reach the evil, if acted on. It is that "every man at once resolve to invest every surplus dollar in Government bonds, and every dollar that is so invested will to that extent contract the currency, and reduce prices." The plan of the Confederate Congress is to fix absolutely the prices of things, and seize supplies by impressment, while the Virginia Legislature fixes the prices of the necessary staples in ordinary traffic. But all these schemes, and all this legislation, do not better matters. They go on from bad to worse, till now, says WIGFALL, "the $11 a month which the soldier receives is scarcely worth $1, and he cannot be relieved by an increase of pay, for it would hut still further inflate the currency and increase prices, and if his pay were double, the $22 would probably buy less than the $11 which he now receives." This is surely a hopeless state of affairs; but it has another effect which WIGFALL expatiates upon. "The higher the prices," he says, "the larger the issues, and the larger the issues the higher the prices. The cost of the war the first year was one or two hundred millions of dollars, three or four hundred millions the next, and it will be eight or ten the third, if prices are not reduced."

abstract: Wednesday morning, at 9  o'clock the ironclad Manhattan was launched at the yard of Mr. SECOR, in Jersey City. Over 6,000 persons were present, amougst whom we noticed Rear Admiral FARRAGUT. Admiral GREGORY, Chief Engineer STIMERS.
lead_paragraph: Wednesday morning, at 9 1/2 o'clock, the ironclad Manhattan was launched at the yard of Mr. SECOR, in Jersey City. Over 6,000 persons were present, amougst whom we noticed Rear Admiral FARRAGUT. Admiral GREGORY, Chief Engineer STIMERS, Admiral DUPONT, and several others. The workmen commenced to strike away the blocks at 9 o'clock, and in about twenty minutes the vessel began to slide; a hitch occurred, however, which detained her on the stocks till quarter to ten, at which time she slid gracefully into the stream, and the cheers of the surrounding multitude, Miss GREGORY, daughter of the Admiral, christened the vessel.

The Seventeenth will leave today for the seat of war, under command of Col. GROWER: Col. JARDINE, of the Ninth, is Lieut.-Colonel, and J.O. MARTIN, Major. The regiment is eight hundred strong, and is the first veteran one which leaven New-York. It would be but right if the City would present it with a stand of colors in place of the old ones which are battle-worn. So short is the notice of departure that the anticipated parade through the City cannot be made. The following are the orders:

abstract: The report which we published yesterday concerning the falling back of the Army of the Potomac from Rappahannock Station to Manassas plains, is fully confirmed by our dispatches received last night. The movement is described as having been splendidly executed, without the slightest confusion. The battle of Wednesday, of which our dispatches yesterday gave the first intimation, turns out to have been a series of brisk engagements between A.P. HILL's corps and the Second and Fifth corps of the Army of the Potomac, in which the cavalry on either side took part. In each of these encounters the fighting was stubborn, but our men succeeded in beating back the enemy, who lost heavily. A large number of prisoners fell into our hands, and also a battery of six guns. Later in the day, LEE made an attempt to flank Gen. MEADE by way of Chantilly, but was unsuccessful in consequence of a rapid counter move. A small party of rebels made a dash upon one of our supply trains, and, after destroying two of the wagons, were driven off by the teamsters, who rallied to defend the property. Yesterday there was no fighting of importance. Gen. SICKLES is announced to have gone to the front to take command of his old corps in case of a general engagement.

abstract: "Profound indignation" is the sentiment entertained among all classes in Chile, at the action of the French Government in forcing a monarchy upon Mexico. A discussion on the subject had taken place in Congress, and the Minister for Foreign Affairs was requested to exprees himself as to whether Chile ought to recognize such a Government.
lead_paragraph: "Profound indignation" is the sentiment entertained among all classes in Chile, at the action of the French Government in forcing a monarchy upon Mexico. A discussion on the subject had taken place in Congress, and the Minister for Foreign Affairs was requested to exprees himself as to whether Chile ought to recognize such a Government. The Minister did not answer. Several notes had been exchanged between Mr. NELSON, United States Minister to Santiago, and the Minister of Foreign Affairs, on Mexican matters, "and it is a consolation to learn from them that both Governments are possessed of like sentiments of aversion to crowned heads on American soil," &c. The Argentine Republic has sent an agent to Chile to confer on Mexican affairs, it is said.

abstract: It is a question not of positions, but of sides. Is the man on the side of the Government, or is he not? That is the point. To say that he occupies this position or that position, that he is a War Democrat or a Conservative Republican, or a Radical Republican -- that he is a "let-them-go" peace man, or an "olive-branch" compromise man, or a war man, with "ifs and buts" -- is to say nothing of practical consequence. There never yet was a cause in which all who engaged in it were exactly of the same mind. In respect to minor matters there is always a wide difference of opinion. The rebels themselves are agreed about nothing, save the one purpose, not to come back into the Union. The very devils in the pit, according to MILTON, had their fierce debates whether to proceed by open war or by covert guile, and even whether not to proceed at all, but simply lie and bear it. The accord comes from agreement of spirit, not judgment -- the spirit which fixes what side shall be taken, not the judgment, which determines the particular position occupied on that side.

abstract: The complimentary match in honor of "CUYP," the celebrated bowler and cricketer, came to a conclusion rather prematurely, by the action of an American belonging to the New-York Club, who, after advising the Americans to avail themselves of all the time they could to delay the game until sundown, called time before it was time, and caused the stumps to be drawn and the men to commence leaving the field; the result being that the stumps had to be pitched again and the game resumed, but not in time for the last man to be sent to the wickets, when time was called by the Umpires and a drawn game declared. The result is a practical victory for the English not withstanding the action of the young American pupil of the New-York Club. The result has been very satisfactory, as well as complimentary, to "CUYP."

abstract: ALLEGED EXTORTION. -- DAVID JOHNSON and CAMIEL R. JONES were arrested yesterday, on the charge of extortion. The complainant is Mr. SAM. KROMER, of No. 39 Carmine-street, who testified that on the 12th inst. the defendants called at his place of business and made threats that unless certain sums of money were paid by him to them they would have him arrested and would break up his business. Complainant fearing that they would put their threats into execution unless he complied with their demand, gave them $25 under protest. KROMER afterward made complaint against them and caused their arrest. They were taken before Justice QUACKENDUSH who held them for examination.
lead_paragraph: ALLEGED EXTORTION. -- DAVID JOHNSON and CAMIEL R. JONES were arrested yesterday, on the charge of extortion. The complainant is Mr. SAM. KROMER, of No. 39 Carmine-street, who testified that on the 12th inst. the defendants called at his place of business and made threats that unless certain sums of money were paid by him to them they would have him arrested and would break up his business. Complainant fearing that they would put their threats into execution unless he complied with their demand, gave them $25 under protest. KROMER afterward made complaint against them and caused their arrest. They were taken before Justice QUACKENDUSH who held them for examination.

abstract: The Enquirer says: "The city was exhilarated to a generous glow of enthusiasm early in the morning by a lurid picture of Chattanooga in flames, and the shells of two hundred and fifty mortars, howitzers, siege guns and columbiads bursting in magnificent confusion over the heads of the Yankee army, clustered in consternation all around it. This initial rumor was succeeded by the certain knocking of the Ironsides, at Charleston, into a cocked-hat, and the towing off of the spoiled remnants of that peculiarly objectionable monster into quarters outside of the bar. The smoke of this splendid achievement growing a little cool, rumor made a flank movement upon Tennessee, and brought up Gen. JOHNSTON at Murfreesboro in a blaze of glory, brim full of triumph, and with his heel on the head of the terrible anaconda. The next breeze 'that swept from the northeast' brought to our ears the stirring though familiar get-along sound of 'LEE in motion!' -- to Washington, of course; and on the heels of this cheering and portentous zephyr, (supposing a zephyr to have heels,) the modest but earnest report of the evacuation of the City of Norfolk.

abstract: The most superb specimens of brook trout that we have ever seen have just been brought to this City by Mr. G.S. PAGE, of the firm of GEO. S. PAGE & BROTHER, Maiden-lane. They were caught by Mr. PAGE, in the early part of this week, somewhere north of New-York City, about 150 miles off -- though concerning the exact locality the angler is discreetly reticent. The heaviest of the fish, a huge, fat, plump, glorious fellow, of firm flesh and unequaled complexion, weighed 8[???] pounds; the next largest weighed 8 1/4 pounds; the next, 7 1/4, and several of them were 5 and 6 pounds apiece. Altogether fifty-one large trout, weighing 273 pounds, were taken from a small brook in eight days fishing, by two gentlemen -- Mr. PAGE, and Mr. HENRY O. STANLEY. The simple sublimity of these facts needs no comment further than to say that they threw GENIO C. SCOTT into such an ecstacy that he immediately sat down, and wrote a note to a City paper, declaring that he was not a "monomaniac" -- which statement may be taken with a barrel of salt. We may add that these fifty-one trout were kept alive for a day or two after being caught, in a small yard or pen of swift water.

abstract: Mobile continues remarkably healthy, notwithstanding the efforts of certain individuals to make it appear otherwise. Evil reports have been circulated in the country by interested parties, that the yellow fever was raging here. There is no spot in the South healthier than Mobile at present, and the indications are that it will remain so. It may be that the "yellow fever" has broken out among the wheat and corn speculators -- in fact, we believe it to be epidemic among them -- but the consumers are so strictly dieted that it is impossible for any disease to develop among them.
