abstract: Capt. CAFFREY, of the Fifteenth Precinct, at a late hour on Thursday night, made a descent on two disorderly houses, situated at Nos. 61 and 63 West Thirteenth-street, kept respectively by JOSEPHINE DUMONT, alias JANE SMITH, and NELLIE CAMERON. The proprietors were arrested, also all the inmates of both sexes, and taken to the Station-house. Yesterday they were arraigned before Justice QUACKENBUSH, at  the Jefferson Market Police Court, where, after a hearing, the principals were committed for examination. Some of the other prisoners were held to bail, and others discharged. The complaints in these cases were made by Messrs. WM.M. GILES and JOHN TAYLOR, who reside at Nos. 59 and 66 West Thirteenth-street, nearly opposite the disorderly places in question. These gentlemen allege that the houses above named have for a long time past been the resort of very vile characters of both sexes, and that they are great nuisances to all the good citizens in that neighborhood.

abstract: It is very disagreeable to have to dash pleasant fancies; but we must, so far as possible, deal with facts. If Gen. S.D. LEE is at Murfreesboro, a fact of which there is as yet no official or other authentic information, he has not with him, we regret to say, the number of men given him by rumor. But he has a respectable force, and with it is operating on ROSECRANS' line of communication. He may, indeed, be at Murfreesboro, for full time has elapsed since he set out on his expedition for him to have reached that point, or he may be on the Nashville Railroad, much nearer to Chattanooga. In any event, there is little doubt but that his operations will be a source of serious annoyance to ROSECRANS. He will certainly much embarrass his communications by burning bridges and trestles, and intercepting trains, both on the railroad to Nashville and the one to Memphis. We shall hear more of his operations in a day or two.

abstract: Free Labor in the South
snippet: Free Labor in the South
lead_paragraph: We have now within our army lines, or within control of our military posts, a million of the slaves of the so-called Confederate States. We do not refer to the negroes of Missouri, Kentucky and Maryland, but mainly to those of the four great Slave States bordering on the Lower Mississippi -- Louisiana, Arkansas, Mississippi and Tennessee. The events and incidents of the war have broken up the long-established social and industrial systems of these States; and we find this vast mass of negro humanity unloosed, unfixed, helpless unless helped, and demanding supervision, guidance, attention and care in its transition from a state of absolute Slavery to the improved condition that we hope fortune has in store for it. We cannot help taking cognizance of its existence, for it is forced upon us; we cannot avoid directing it unless we would have it ruin the country. As yet but too little attention has been paid to the subject, either practically or speculatively; and the authorities, seeing and feeling the gigantic embarrassments and difficulties of the subject -- knowing that it is a problem so stupendous and profound, so far-reaching in its bearings, and demanding so imperatively an intelligent solution, have rather held back their hands and permitted matters to drift, in hope that time and clearer skies would somehow or other come to our relief. This, if not the best thing that could be done, is, we believe, really the only thing that could wisely be done, under the circumstances. But the consequence is that masses of negroes and great tracts of country are now "at loose ends," and it is only at one or two points that the subject has been grappled with at all. The principal of these are Louisiana (some of its parishes) and the South Carlina sea-islands. As a matter of the deepest interest, we present to the readers of the TIMES this morning some of the observations on the new free-labor system made by intelligent persons in each of these localities. After studying them, we think our readers will agree with us that the experiment is an essential success, though it would appear that in Louisiana at least it is not carried on in all respects as might be desired.

abstract: It has been observed that not many Federal Generals have been killed in this war. The military expediency of keeping out of danger is fully appreciated by those heroes, so self-denying of glory, so generous in their distribution of the posts of honor and peril to the humble privates in their ranks. BURNSIDE, butting the heads of his rank and file against the ramparts of Fredericksburgh, and ensconcing himself in a snug covert three miles from the roar of battle, is a fair specimen of the military discretion of the Commander-in-Chief of the Federal forces. It is a rare thing to hear of one of them who is unmindful of the great law of self-preservation. Such slaughter as has been among the common soldiers of the Yankee army has not often been witnessed, nor such exemption from peril as their leaders have enjoyed. SCOTT, MCCLELLAN, MCDOWELL, BUEL, POPE, BURNSIDE, HOOKER, all five, and not even a scar to testify that they have ever been engaged in a battle of this war.

abstract: on The Monroe Doctrine, its Origin and Nature
snippet: on The Monroe Doctrine, its Origin and Nature
lead_paragraph: The reader may recollect that in my last number I quoted a passage from the London Quarterly Review for January, 1862, in which among the facts that proved the United States to have pursued for fifty years an offensive course toward Great Britain, showing herself "not a loyal friend, but a grasping and bullying enemy, it was mentioned that President PIERCE, on occasion of the negotiation between the two countries relative to Central America, had "avowed his adherence to what is called the Monroe doctrine." At the close of the article I observed that, as far as the so-called Monroe doctrine "bore upon the affairs of Spanish America, it had the concurrence and warm approval of the British Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs; Mr. GEORGE CANNING."

abstract: The Aldermen did not meet last week. This was unfortunate, as there are two important measures to be acted on by them. The first in importance is the procuring of wood for the "people" of this city. It was not the intention of the mover of this project to make a free gift of the wood purchased by the public money to the people, but it was to throw the weight of the City Treasury against the extortioners who are now demanding $40 per cord.

abstract: THE QUAKER CITY. -- Philadelphia has said a good many very hard things about New-York during the past year -- referring particularly to its Copperheadism, its riots, its growth, wealth and grandeur, its frivolity, its tendency to absorb the commerce, trade and talent of the Continent, and so forth. We have had to acknowledge the justice of a good deal of the censure of our censor, though we could not approve the acrimonious and jealous spirit in which it was dealt. In return for it all we have taken occasion, now and then, to commend the innumerable virtues of Philadelphia. We are glad to be able now to say another good word for it, and we are sorry that we cannot indulge the hope that the Metropolis is likely soon to deserve eulogium upon the same ground. Philadelphia on Tuesday sustained her character and honor by giving a handsome majority for the Union Republican candidates. She could not have spoken a better word for herself; she could not have set a nobler example to us; she could not have done greater service to the Union and all its interests. Grander than all else is intelligent patriotism, and in this Philadelphia stands the first of cities. We own up to it, not in a spirit of jealousy, but of unqualified admiration. She is constant in it, too, not wavering or spasmodic. Last year, says the North American,

abstract: The rapid advance in all necessaries of clothing and subsistence threatens us with great distress. We cannot see how unemployed persons, and how those who live on incomes and salaries, are to get along, especially at the inclement season of the year now approaching. How are they to buy shoes and clothing at the present rates? Nay, how long are these rates to prevail? A great auction may in a day or two run them all up fifty per cent.! An auction thus has become to be regarded by the people with as much dread as a battle! A defeat on the battle-field could hardly bring more suffering upon them.

abstract: In the case of MILLER and MIMS, examined before Justice STARR yesterday, for whipping a negro to death, the defendants were sent to jail without bail. There appears to have been the greatest brutality used toward the unfortunate negro. We saw some of the sticks used on him, and we wonder how any man could so far forget his humanity as to beat anything with them. We leave the matter in the hands of the jury, hoping that our laws will be fully vindicated.

abstract: A report has been made to the Board of Commissioners of Health by WILLIAM H. ARMSTRONG, Esq., the Clerk of such Board, which sets forth concisely and clearly the powers of the Board as to nuisances and the authorities therefor. It is a compilation which has long been needed, and bears the evidence of a latorious, thorough and intelligent examination. Heretofore the Board of Health and the Commissioners have been groping in the dark.
lead_paragraph: A report has been made to the Board of Commissioners of Health by WILLIAM H. ARMSTRONG, Esq., the Clerk of such Board, which sets forth concisely and clearly the powers of the Board as to nuisances and the authorities therefor. It is a compilation which has long been needed, and bears the evidence of a latorious, thorough and intelligent examination. Heretofore the Board of Health and the Commissioners have been groping in the dark. Until this valuable compilation by Mr. ARMSTRONG they have had to roam over the wide fields of State laws and municipal ordinance, and made tiresome search for anything definite or satisfactory as to their powerr to abate nuisances. The report was based on a complaint against a "fat boiling" establishment in the City limits, and shows that no power does exist in this Board to cause the removal from the City of any business which may be deemed detrimental to the public health, that power being conferred expressly on the "Board of Health." But the Common Council can meet this difficulty by passing an ordinance under the statute giving the Mayor, Aldermen and Commonalty power to pass all such by-laws and ordinances as may be needed for preservation of the public health, removal and abatement of nuisances. This would be preferable to anything the Board of Health may do, as they can act only on special cases after notice to parties against whom action is to be taken. An ordinance of the Common Council would be general, and would cure all cases of nuisances without the trouble and delay caused by the present mode of procedure. The ordinance in regard to boiling offal, bones, &c., does this so far as these businesses are concerned, but does not include what was the source of complaint on which the report was made, "fat boiling;" an amendment to the ordinance embracing this would protect the City from an abomination. It is claimed, however, that in the absence of an ordinance by the Common Council, that almost absolute power is vested in the Board in connection with the City inspector, by the section of the Statute which directed the Inspector to do, or cause to be done, everything in relation to cleansing and purifying of building lots, &c., which, in the opinion of the Mayor and the Commissioners of Health, shall be deemed necessary. This power, however, is not sufficiently defined, and could be fairly contested. A memorial and draft of an ordinance, embodying the views in the report, have been submitted to the Common Council, and laid over for consideration.

abstract: the Copperhead Charges of
snippet: the Copperhead Charges of
lead_paragraph: The Copperheads have made "Tyranny" and the "Rights of the People" their special watchwords. They have set themselves up as the particular expounders and champions of constitutional law. They have proved by the book that ABRAHAM LINCOLN is fast riveting their chains, and that American freemen must rouse and rally or be slaves forever. In positiveness of assertion, or in passionateness of appeal, no revolutionary language ever exceeded theirs. The usurpations and oppressions of GEORGE the Third were never set forth in more unqualified or more direful terms. The newspapers argued, and the orators shrieked. From Maine to California, all that could be done was done to rack the popular mind and heart into a frenzy. The Constitution was being torn to rags, Personal Rights were under the sword, Liberty was dangling over a precipice, and LINCOLN, the despot, was preparing to reign.

abstract: The net result of the draft in this City cannot be ascertained fully as yet, but judging form the returns already, in it will be far more satisfactory than is generally supposed and infinitely better than the Copperheads have prophesied or desired. The total number drafted, including the fifty per cent, allowed for exemptions, was 27,000.
lead_paragraph: The net result of the draft in this City cannot be ascertained fully as yet, but judging form the returns already, in it will be far more satisfactory than is generally supposed and infinitely better than the Copperheads have prophesied or desired. The total number drafted, including the fifty per cent, allowed for exemptions, was 27,000. According to present prospects the Government will get about thirty-three per cent. of this number in men, and ten per cent. in commutation money. It has often been asserted by those opposed to the draft that the cost of obtaining recruits by this method would be far greater than by offering bounties for volunteers. So far from this being the case, we are informed by the Assistant Provost-Marshal-General NUGENT, that the average cost to the Government of each, man procured by the draft, will be less than $73. In the Fourth District, which has been the most expensive in proportion to the number of men furnished, the average cost will be about $100 per man, while in several of the other districts it will not reach $40 per man.

abstract: The steam sloop-of-war Brooklyn, flagship of Commodore FARRAGUT during the attack on and capture of New-Orleans, in which engagement she received serious injuries, is now upon the great Sectional Dock, at the foot of Rutgers-street, East River, undergoing repairs under the supervision of Messrs. JACOB A. WESTERVELT & SONS. The Brooklyn is over 2,000 tons burden, yet was raised from the water in one hour and five minutes -- the occasion attracting a large concourse of people. During Thursday afternoon the old Commodore visited the vessel, and, being recognized by the workmen on the several drydocks in the vicinity, was loudly cheered. Under the guidance of Capts. MCCORMAC and BETTS, of the mercantile service, the "Old Salamander" was conducted about the locality, and was everywhere greeted with marked evidences of respect and esteem. The Brooklyn will remain on the dock for several days, and so ample opportunity will be afforded our citizens to witness her magnificent proportions.

abstract: If a foreigner could have observed the bearing of the Southern people during the momentous events of the last few weeks, he must have thought them the most impassible and phlematic of nations. The news of a great victory was received, not merely with imperturbable calmness, but with something akin to frigid mistrust. The preconceived ideal of the people of the Southern States so familiar to the world must have appeared very much at variance with the reality. There is greater rejoicing over a single dubious and meagre victory in the land of granite, and codfish, and wooden nutmegs, than is accorded to a Chickamauga or a Manassas in the sunny region of cotton and tobacco.

abstract: Surgeons Captured, the Case of
snippet: Surgeons Captured, the Case of
lead_paragraph: We give this morning some official documents of interest, which have lately been published in Richmond, concerning the exchange of the Surgeons who have been captured on the field of battle, and are how held as prisoners both in the North and in the South. The large number of these professional gentlemen who are in durance makes the matter one requiring immediate attention. The whole difficulty lies in the case of Dr. RUCKER, who is a prisoner in Richmond, and against whom the rebels allege a deed, committed in Virginia, in violation of law. They are willing to exchange the other Surgeons, but refuse to give him up, insisting that he shall first be tried in Virginia for his alleged offence. This, as a principle, cannot be conceded by us, for by the local laws of every Southern State, every one of our soldiers has incurred the penalty of death, for stirring up insurrection among the slaves, for circulating incendiary documents, (such as the TIMES,) and for numerous similar things; and we have, of course, steadily refused to give them the privilege of general execution of our prisoners. The correspondence upon the subject between the exchange officers was dropped as long ago as two months, and in the meantime these surgeons (who should not be regarded as prisoners of war at all) are incarcerated, without prospect of release. We hope that negotiations will at once be renewed, and the rebels brought to terms; and, as we hold in our hands three times the number of surgeons held by the enemy, we should think it were possible to do this. Some interesting and valuable notes on the subject have been furnished us by a distinguished general officer of our army, who has lately been released from imprisonment in Richmond, and we cannot better elucidate the case than by appending these notes:

abstract: The price of gold fell this forenoon below 155 cent. Exchange on London is 170@171 cent. Some of the damaging war rumors of yesterday, used to put the price up to 156 1/2@157 cent, are dissipated by the facts in the morning papers from the army of the Potomac. A rumor in the opposite direction in one of the opposition morning papers that Mr. CHASE is about to put $3,000,000 of gold in the market is equally at fault. Mr. CHASE is in the West, and as far as we are advised has no idea of interfering with the market for gold. That he holds a large surplus over his wants for the November interest which might be legitimately employed and to advantage for the sinking fund, at 50 cent. premium is no doubt true, and this fact may have given color to the rumor referred to. Nevertheless we have reason to believe it to be at least premature.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- VERDI's opera of "La Traviata" was played here last evening for the first time this season, and, considering the very inclement weather, attracted a good audience. The casts was in all respects the same as last season, the leading roles being sustained by Mlle. ORTALANI, BRIGNOLI, Signor MAZZOLENI and Signor BELLINI. We have rarely heard the lady to greater advantage; the Summer's repose has evidently benefited her. Signor MAZZOLENI sang and acted with much spirit, but Signor BELLINI was, as usual, out of voice. The orchestra and chorus were excellent.

abstract: An exciting rumor that a corps of the rebel army, (supposed to be A.P. HILL'S) had moved from our front in the direction of Leesburgh, was circulated in Wahington Thursday night. An advance in that direction might mean another invasion of Pennsylvania, and a heavy force was immediately dispatched to check the enemy's  design.
lead_paragraph: An exciting rumor that a corps of the rebel army, (supposed to be A.P. HILL's) had moved from our front in the direction of Leesburgh, was circulated in Wahington Thursday night. An advance in that direction might mean another invasion of Pennsylvania, and a heavy force was immediately dispatched to check the enemy's design. There was more or less skirmishing all Thursday along our whole line, apparently for position, and Gen. MEADE is said to have gained the advantage. A body of the enemy also on Thursday night were seen moving southward in the direction of Blackburn's Ford, and our batteries opened upon them. They replied for half an hour and disappeared. It was also reported on Thursday that one rebel corps were advancing upon Fairfax by the Chantilly road, and our heavy batteries were sent in that direction. They returned with information that all was quiet. There were no movements of any kind reported yesterday. Our army is said now to be well in hand, in line of battle, prepared for any attack, and with its baggage and transportation trains secure.

abstract: Among all the honors that have been heaped upon Admiral FARRAGUT since return from the scene of his Western exploits, we venture to say that none have been more acceptable or gratifying to the gallant here than the reception given him yesterday by the scholars of Public School No. 11. Having accepted an invitation to visit the above school, the Admiral yesterday drove in his carriage to the...
lead_paragraph: Among all the honors that have been heaped upon Admiral FARRAGUT since return from the scene of his Western exploits, we venture to say that none have been more acceptable or gratifying to the gallant here than the reception given him yesterday by the scholars of Public School No. 11. Having accepted an invitation to visit the above school, the Admiral yesterday drove in his carriage to the school-house, located in Seventeenth-street, near Eighth-avenue, arriving at the door a little past 11 A.M. He was accompanied by Mrs. FARRAGUT, Rev. Dr. OSGOOD, of the Church of the Messiah, PETER COOPER, Mr. RANDALL, Superintendent of Public Schools, and a number of other gentlemen. The party were escorted first to the Male Department on the upper floor, where all the male scholars were congregated, and where a large number of invited guests, mostly ladies, had also assembled to participate in the reception. The school-room was handsomely decorated with the American colors, and from the ceiling opposite the entrance the word "WELCOME," wrought in evergreen, shone forth amid the festoons of the old flag. The Admiral, with his lady and the other members of the party, were seated upon the platform and the exercises commenced with the singing of a song by the pupils entitled -- "The dearest spot of earth to me is home, sweet home."

abstract: Hamilton Gail; Gala Days; Clark, N. G.; Elements of the E glish Language; Youmans, Dr. E. L.; Class Book of Chemistry
snippet: Hamilton Gail; Gala Days; Clark, N. G.; Elements of the E glish Language; Youmans, Dr. E. L.; Class Book of Chemistry
lead_paragraph: Dr. YOUMAN's work on Chemistry has for many years held its own as, perhaps, the very best classbook on the Subject, and in the present edition he brings it up abreast of the latest discoveries in this expansive and expanding branch of science. New views of the nature and connection of the forces have been accepted in the scientific world, which compel a new treatment of this branch of the subject. The old notion that the forces are separate and peculiar forms of imponderable matter, has given way to the idea that they are closely allied and mutually convertible forms of activity or motion in ordinary matter. The older views are held to be self-contradictory, and as they do not explain and cannot represent the present facts of science, they are abandoned by the body of advanced scientific thinkers of the present time. The newer doctrines may be still incomplete, and are not without their difficulties, but they are more simple and rational -- they harmonize with the later facts of discovery, and open many new paths of investigation of the highest interest and promise. Among the latest chemical and physicochemical discoveries embodied by Dr. YOUMANS, in the new edition of the Text Book, are the Spectrum Analysis and the elements discovered by it; Prof. GRAHAM's interesting views of Dialysis and the colloidal condition of matter, and BERTHELOT's remarkable researches in organic synthesis, or the artificial production of organic substances.

abstract: Question, the
snippet: Question, the
lead_paragraph: The opposition which was made at first to the employment of negroes in our armies, has all but passed away, as indeed it could not fail to do, for it was founded in great part upon erroneous views as to their capacity, which have been entirely dissipated by a little experience. But that there should have been such opposition at all, will always be one of the singular features of the history of the rebellion. One would have thought the employment of negroes in the army during the Revolution and the war of 1812, and their constant employment in the navy, would have prevented the rise of any such feeling.

abstract: -- Among the many varieties of talent which our civil war is developing, in the different branches of literary and artistic endeavor, it is with satisfaction that we recognize the very rapid progress toward the highest reputation and excellence of young Mr. THOMAS NAST, whose inimitable political caricatures are so widely and deservedly popular. The events of the great struggle have furnished his prolific crayon with abundant subjects, and the pages of Harper's Weekly and other illustrated papers are, now, continually enriched with the productions of his taste and skill. Mr. NAST is but in the commencement of his career, yet already ranks among the most successful of our artistic aspirants.

abstract: ANOTHER ACCIDENT FROM FURIOUS DRIVING. -- In rainy weather, when nights are most obscure, a certain class of our omnibus and hack-drivers hold [???] carnival on Broadway in their utter disregard of the [???]s and lives of the population. It is high time that this outrageous abuse should be stopped by summary and decisive measures. Broadway is hard to cross at any time for the aged, feeble or infirm. Women and children may regard the attempt to do so as well nigh hopeless, even in the broad glare of the noonday sun, unless assisted by some determined policeman. But at times when the slippery pavements are greased with oozy mud and glistening with the uncertain light of the corner lamps, the stoutest man has good reason to hesitate before he ventures upon so perilous an undertaking. These are precisely the periods when our City Jehus seem to convert Broadway into a grand municipal race-course, and hence at such seasons the papers are called upon to register fresh casualties. Friday evening, about 10 o'clock, a man was run over by a stage driven at top-speed, on Broadway, in the vicinity of Barnum's Museum. He was dashed to the ground, badly cut and bruised, and covered from head to foot with mire, his clothing being completely destroyed of course. The stage drove right on, in spite of shouts and cries directed at the driver. The unfortunate stranger was picked up by Officer SNYDER and taken to the Second Ward Station-house, too much bewildered to give his name and address. Only last week, upon a dark and rainy evening, a similar result of brutal recklessness occurred at the corner of Broadway and Fulton-street, the guilty party there likewise making his escape. Pedestrians have clear paramount rights on the public thoroughfares, and an example must be made of those who recklessly override them. When some of our omnibus Companies have swinging damages to pay, they will probably issue proper orders to their employes.

abstract: English Interference With
snippet: English Interference With
lead_paragraph: There is a little spot on the west coast of Africa, the geographical extent of which does not exceed two hundred miles in length, and one hundred and fifty in breadth, and the population of which comes within two hundred thousand, and yet this morsel of territory should possess more interest in the eyes of Americans than all the crest of that great continent together. It is the kingdom of Dahomey, the dominion of the great BAD-JA-HUNG, the "King of Kings," as he is styled by his loving lieges, and the seat of the slave trade. The kingdom of Dahomey boasts but one principal city, that of Abomey, a place of fifty thousand inhabitants, and the residence of the King. To this city but few white men have ever penetrated, the first of whom was Mr. LAMB, an Englishman, about seventy-five years ago, who has been followed by about half-a-dozen more of the same nation at different periods, and by one American. To this little corner of the earth the loving attention of England has of late been directed in a remarkable way. We know, of course, that enterprising John Bull has been thrusting his commercial proboscis into every part of the world for the last score of years, doing his best to smell out cotton, and especially putting it into Africa, but we cannot believe that any such motive controls his desire to look into the affairs of King BAD-JA-HUNG, because he knows well that only a very small quantity of that article is cultivated in his sable majesty's dominions, and that of a very bad quality, and Bull never yet did undertake to teach those whom he loves anything, rather preferring to find them producing what he wants ready to his hand. Therefore it cannot be cotton. That point being settled, we will take his own account for it, which is philanthropy. Looking around the world for some eligible spot whereon to bestow the overboiling of this virtue, John Bull spies the kingdom of his brother of Dahomey, the spot whereon is cultivated, not cotton, but a business in wool, or rather in human bones; and surely to crush out this business would be a sublime ambition, and would save the expense of a fleet upon that coast. To achieve this end we hear occasionally of the battering down of a coast factory or barracoon, and in the next breath of the sending an Envoy to BAD-JA-HUNG, in full toggery of gold lace, and loaded with presents, who stays a week or two with the King, hob-nobs and smokes the calumet, compliments his wives, and admires the five thousand Amazons of his body-guard; looks into his finances, counts up his profits in the Slave-trade, makes him an offer in shillings, pence, et cetera, to abandon it, which offer is invariably refused with a high order of diplomacy, and comes away brimming with wonderful stories of this really most wonderful nation of Africa. Of course it is not to be supposed that the labors of England will stop here, and, as a consequence, she is at this moment quietly looking around to see how to hammer a little common sense and morality into the thick skull of her brother of Dahomey; and this she is preparing to do by her agents upon the coast, who are looking into the best methods of attack and defence, for it will be no small job to invade a warlike people who keep a standing army of twelve thousand men and women, which can at any time be increased to forty thousand, and who are skilled in the use of the musket, and somewhat in the arts of war. It is therefore doubtful if England will attempt to land men enough on the seaboard to make an attack from the south; a plan that would require at least ten thousand troops. Her mode will rather be to send light draft steamers to the Lagos, a river to the eastward of Dahomey, and navigable one hundred miles from its mouth, to carry a couple of thousand or more men to Abe-ku-e-tah, and following out the traditional policy of England in wars with savages, enlist that people under her banners to destroy the Dahomiens, after which she can at her leisure destroy the Abe-ku-e-tahs, who are themselves slave-traders, and are governed by a King, placed on the throne by the Portuguese traders, whose barracoons lie principally to the eastward of the Lagos. This is the only mode by which England can with safety advance into Dahomey, and break up the Slave-trade in that part of Africa, or rather drive it to another locality; for so long as the demand exists, so long will there be found negro Kings to supply it, either upon the west or east coast, or from some part of the world where the human cargoes can be had.

abstract: A portion of JOE JOHNSTON's force, 8,000 to 15,000 strong, under RUGGLES, CHALMERS and LEE, have been threatening the Memphis and Charleston Railroad in the vicinity of Germantown and Colliersville. On Sunday a force under CHALMERS attacked the garrison at Colliersville, driving them into their fortifications. During the fight Major Gen. SHERMAN and Staff, with a detachment of the Thirteenth Regulars, arrived on a train en route to Corinth. They disembarked, engaged the enemy, and repulsed him with considerable loss.

abstract: An important movement has been initiated among the Germans, toward the formation of a National organization. The movement originated in the Washington German branch of the Union League. A Central Committee was appointed and an address issued, and the organization promises to do good work for the loyal cause during the coming year. Thus far fifteen State organizations, with a great number of other clubs and societies, have offered to cooperate. A general Delegate Convention of all the States will he held in Cleveland, Ohio, on the 18th instant, at which time and place a permanent Executive Board and a central point for action will be determined on. The purpose of the organization is to secure greater compactness of the liberal Germans, in order that they may act in concert with all loyal men more effectively. The Central Committee is as follows:
lead_paragraph: An important movement has been initiated among the Germans, toward the formation of a National organization. The movement originated in the Washington German branch of the Union League. A Central Committee was appointed and an address issued, and the organization promises to do good work for the loyal cause during the coming year. Thus far fifteen State organizations, with a great number of other clubs and societies, have offered to cooperate. A general Delegate Convention of all the States will he held in Cleveland, Ohio, on the 18th instant, at which time and place a permanent Executive Board and a central point for action will be determined on. abstract: It will be seen that the President has issued a proclamation calling for the voluntary enlistment of three hundred thousand fresh troops for our army.
lead_paragraph: It will be seen that the President has issued a proclamation calling for the voluntary enlistment of three hundred thousand fresh troops for our army. We earnestly hope that this call will be immediately and heartily responded to by the people, though it is not based on the immediate necessity for the service of these troops because of any special emergency. The first and indeed the only special reason set forth by the President for the new demand is, that "the terms of service of part of the volunteer forces will expire during the coming year." This of itself is reason enough. The lines of the rebellion are contracted, many of its strongholds have fallen, and its forces and power are greatly diminished from what they were; but it still controls a vast section, still possesses great armies, and is still tenacious of life and determined upon success. It would be a critical thing for the country to permit its armies to dwindle down at this time, and would certainly imperil all our gains. Even though ROSECRANS had defeated BRAGG at Chattanooga -- even though MEADE had met and discomfited LEE on the Rapidan -- even though Charleston, Savannah, Mobile and Wilmington were in our hands -- it would not be safe to permit our armies to lose their strength. We should still have heavy bodies of rebels posted through the rebel States, at points from the James River to the Mississippi, and even beyond it. We should still have our stupendous conquests to secure and retain; and we should still have to show a front of power in the midst of a rebellious and disaffected population.

abstract: Mr. SPENCE has another able letter in the Times, written in anticipation of the Africa's news. He pleads the cause of Mr. MASON, and thinks we have done ourselves injury by forcing that gentleman to retire. He declares that the reports of the destruction of Fort Sumter are much exaggerated, and later news confirms this opinion.
lead_paragraph: Mr. SPENCE has another able letter in the Times, written in anticipation of the Africa's news. He pleads the cause of Mr. MASON, and thinks we have done ourselves injury by forcing that gentleman to retire. He declares that the reports of the destruction of Fort Sumter are much exaggerated, and later news confirms this opinion. He then enters upon the subject of the detention of the Mersey steam-rams, and by inference confesses that they are intended for the Confederate Government. He points out that Chief Baron POLLOCK ruled that equipping a a vessel meant arming her, and that, therefore, these ships could not be lawfully detained. He warns us against substituting a "higher law" for national law, and thinks that now that he Washington Government has declined to accept our proposal of a mutual change of the law respecting the fitting out of war vessels for a belligerent, we cannot, consistently with our dignity, yield to the threats of the Federal Government. As to Mr. LINCOLN's emancipation proclamation, that, Mr. SPENCE holds, is now, upon its author's own confession, a mere measure of State policy, to be abandoned if occasion should require. Lastly, Mr. SPENCE combats the notion that the South has ever been unfriendly with us. It was Northern statesmen who dismissed Mr. CRAMPTON, it was not in the Southern interest that the Maine boundary was extended, the Oregon boundary disputed, the right of fishing on our coasts demanded, or the Island of San Juan appropriated. We are the competitors with the North -- we are the customers of the South. It is not unusual for men to hate their competitors, but it is somewhat rare to find them hating their customers.

lead_paragraph: THE OPENING OF BUSHWICK-AVENUE. -- The Brooklyn Board of Assessors on Friday passed a resolution fixing the district of assessment for the widening and opening of Bushwick-avenue, as follows: Beginning at the city line at the southerly side of Bushwick-avenue, and running southwesterly along said city line to a point 295 feet from Bushwick-avenue, and running thence northwesterly and northerly parallel with said avenue, as intended to be laid out, and Morrell-street; and distant 275 feet therefrom to North Second-street, thence easterly along North Second-street to Bushwick-avenue, and thence southerly and southeasterly along said Bushwick-avenue and Morell-street to the place of beginning; and also beginning at the northerly side of Bushwick-avenue at the city line; running thence northerly, northwesterly and easterly along the boundary line of the Cemetery of the Evergreens to a point in said boundary line distant 300 feet at right angles from the easterly side of said Bushwick-avenue, as intended to be laid down: thence northwesterly and northerly, parallel to Bushwick-avenue and Morrell street, 300 feet distant therefrom to Metropolitan-avenue, and thence westerly along Metropolitan-avenue to said Busnwick-avenue; thence northerly and northeasterly along said Bushwick avenue and Morrell-street to the point or place of beginning at the city line.

abstract: Earl Russell's Speech at Blairsgowrie on
snippet: Earl Russell's Speech at Blairsgowrie on
lead_paragraph: In the course of his speech at Blairgowrie on international affairs, Earl RUSSELL favored his hearers with a new aspect of the Polish question. "The conditions," said he, "which are contained in the treaty of Vienna, and by which Russia obtained the kingdom of Poland, have not been complied with, and without the conditions of the tenure, the title itself can hardly be upheld." The British Foreign Secretary uttered many excellent things on the occasion alluded to, but this is not of them. There are in fact almost as many fallacies as words in that extract. A person not acquainted with modern European history, would be apt to infer, from Earl RUSSELL's statement, that the Grand Duchy of Warsaw was a fief which the munificence of the Congress of 1815 bestowed on the First ALEXANDER; and that the Treaty of Vienna was an instrument of extraordinary sanctity, for contemning which Russia should be held criminal. But whoever would draw any such inference from his Lordship's language would be far from the truth. Why, two hundred thousand Russian troops occupied the Duchy at the time, and Europe merely confirmed to the Czar what she had no power to withhold; while, as for the Treaty of Vienna, it is at this day of no more validity than an old almanac.

abstract: Letter on the Death of His Son

lead_paragraph: Your readers will doubtless recollect having seen an announcement in the papers, a few days since, of the death of a little son of Major-Gen. W. T. SHERMAN, a bright, beautiful boy of 8 years, whose disease was contracted while in camp with his father, on the Big Black, twenty miles from Vicksburgh. The accompanying letter, addressed to the Thirteenth infantry, and by its officers ordered printed for distribution among the soldiers of the regiment, cannot but touch a tender chord in every heart. Stricken father, noble patriot, the hero of uncounted battles; let the nation pause in admiration of his gallant deeds, to weep with the mourner over the young life that no "bugle note will wake." X.

abstract: Rev. WM. H. MILBURN, the well-known blind preacher and orator, has commenced a course of Sunday evening lectures at Irving Hall, upon subjects connected with the early history of the Church, preceding and after the death of Christ. The lectures or sermons, as they may, perhaps, be more properly termed, are designed more particularly for the edification of young men and women. An association of young men called the "Irving Hall Association," has been formed, who have engaged the Hall for the Winter, and Mr. MILBURN will preach regularly on each Sunday evening. The seats are free to all, the expenses being defrayed by collections and voluntary contributions. The services are to be of the most primitive and simple nature, and the lectures brief, pointed, moral and instructive. The enterprise is one in which a large number of our Christian young men of various denominations are enlisted, and it bids fair to be the most useful and popular religious movement which has taken place for along time in this City. The second, lecture of she course was delivered last evening before a very large and intelligent audience. The subject was "The Temptations of Christ." The various occasions of temptation in the life of Christ were described, the manner in which they w[???] resisted, and the application which should be made of them to the temptations which beset young men at the present day. The discourse was replete with the fervid zeal, touches of eloquence, and graces of oratory, which characterize alt the efforts of the reverend orator.

abstract: BROOKLYN POLTICIANS. The Dominations of the different parties in this city will be completed during this week. Those Democrats who are dissatisfied with the city and county tickets as nominated by the Democratic Conventions, are making arrangements ...
lead_paragraph: BROOKLYN POLTICIANS. -- The Dominations of the different parties in this city will be completed during this week. Those Democrats who are dissatisfied with the city and county tickets as nominated by the Democratic Conventions, are making arrangements to hold a Convention on Tuesday evening, when they will present a new set of candidates for the public vote. Hon. MARTIN KAL[???]FLEISCH will undoubtedly be the candidate for Mayor, and Hon. SAMUEL GARRISON for County Judge. The Republican City Convention will meet on the same evening, and an effort is being made to put a straight ticket in the field, now that there is a certainty that two Democratic tickets will be fun. The Democratic Ward Conventions meet to-night to nominate Aldermen.

abstract: Church-goers and others who yesterday passed along Broadway, below Canal-street, were surprised by something unusual in that thoroughfare, especially for Sunday. From early morning until near dark a gang of several hundred men were engaged in [???]earing up the pavement, digging trenches and laying down a railroad track across Broadway in Walker-street. At noon Broadway was blockaded from White to Lispenard-street, and Walker-street was in the same condition from Church-street to Cortlandt-alley. At evening Broadway at that place presented its usual appearance, the track having been laid and covered with gravel in such a manner that no passer-by would suspect that the rails were lodged across our fashionable avenue. This is the first track of the gridiron road that has been laid across Broadway.

abstract: A Word in his Ear
snippet: A Word in his Ear
lead_paragraph: Gov. SEYMOUR has enjoyed during the past year the honor of being the only official champion of the Democratic party, and he assumed, without having received any formal appointment, the functions of general guardian of the public liberties against Federal encroachment. He and his friends have earnestly called the attention not only of this State, but of the whole North, to his career as a fair specimen of the manner in which popular rights would be taken care of if there were a Democratic Administration in Washington. In fact, if we might judge from the language of his organs, he looked on himself and wished to be looked upon by others as the real representative and mouthpiece of this afflicted nation -- a sort of shepherd of the people -- and President LINCOLN and his Cabinet were held up to odium as a herd of ravening wolves, playing havoc in all parts of the fold that our Governor was not able to look after.

abstract: The clash of arms between the opposing hosts in Virginia cannot be much longer delayed if the brief reports which are telegraphed from Washington may be depended on. The latest dispatch informs us that the Army of the Potomac is now within the defences of Washington, but the position ...
lead_paragraph: The clash of arms between the opposing hosts in Virginia cannot be much longer delayed if the brief reports which are telegraphed from Washington may be depended on. The latest dispatch informs us that the Army of the Potomac is now within the defences of Washington, but the position of LEE's army is not made known. We infer, however, that the rumored withdrawal of the rebel forces to the Rappahannock is not a fact, and that there is truth in the statement that the rebels are in force at Manassas Junction, and have sent reconnoitering parties thence into the Shenandoah Valley, though whether with a view to operations there, we cannot conjecture. There has already been some skirmishing with rebel cavalry in the Valley.

abstract: -- The wretched new Postal Currency, of which specimens have begun to appear here, was gotten up in Washington City, and none of our New-York artists or artisans are responsible for it. The entire work of designing, engraving and printing the notes was done in the Department at Washington -- which fact is recorded in a line at the bottom of the notes themselves. We hope it will not be allowed to go into circulation. We could better endure our present dirty slips a month or two longer than the substitution of such trash. -- if the notes we have seen are specimens of those that remain behind.

abstract: The President's Call for Soldiers
snippet: The President's Call for Soldiers
lead_paragraph: We rejoice that the President's Proclamation for three hundred thousand more troops leaves the alternative open of either volunteering or draft. It is an excellent thing that the Governors of New-York and New-Jersey, who have found such fault with the last draft as being an unnecessary resort, should show what they can accomplish in the line of volunteering. It is true that the latter functionary has had a chance already. His high-flown engagement to the President to supply the quota of his State with volunteers, if the draft upon it were postponed, did not turn out very successfully -- in fact it had what disrespectful people would call a somewhat "fizzling" termination. No man of feeling will grudge him another opportunity. As for Gov. SEYMOUR, his case is hit exactly.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. The performance of "Rigoletto" on Saturday, at the Academy, furnished another opportunity for Miss KELLOGG to win a genuine art triumph in the part of Gilda. The lady's voice has improved so vastly; her confidence before the public has increased so much, and her dramatic ...
lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The performance of "Rigoletto" on Saturday, at the Academy, furnished another opportunity for Miss KELLOGG to win a genuine art triumph in the part of Gilda. The lady's voice has improved so vastly; her confidence before the public has increased so much, and her dramatic grasp of the character is thereby so much fuller than it used to be, that we can hardly compare the impersonation with any of Miss KELLOGG's previous efforts. It exceeds in importance her thoroughly touching and beautiful ideal of Linda -- than which we hardly remember to have seen anything superior on the American lyric stage. The applause on Saturday was unequal to the occasion; it is generally so at the matinees, but we are convinced that every intelligent person left the establishment with a distinct and, we hope, adequate idea of Miss KELLOGG's admirable qualities as an artist of the highest rank. We trust that Mr. MARETZEK will give us many opportunities of hearing her.

abstract: There is a report from Washington that the Army of the Potomac has steadily fallen back until now it is planted within the defences of Washington. The rebel army, according to one dispatch, had massed a heavy force at Manassas; but another dispatch has it that ...
lead_paragraph: There is a report from Washington that the Army of the Potomac has steadily fallen back until now it is planted within the defences of Washington. The rebel army, according to one dispatch, had massed a heavy force at Manassas; but another dispatch has it that a cavalry reconnoissance was made yesterday to near Bristow's Station, some distance beyond Manassas Junction, and nothing was found but a few rebel scouts. This latter fact, and the general tenor of the dispatches, indicate that the prevalent opinion in Washington is, that LEE is fronting his forces toward the Shenandoah Valley. Already there has been some skirmishing with the rebel cavalry in that vicinity.

abstract: The Municipal Banquet is given to the Russian Admiral and officers, this evening at the Astor House. The number of guests will be about three hundred. The different foreign Ministers have been invited, as have the French Admiral and his officers. In view of the limited number, the Committe have had a delicate duty to perform in the matter of invitations to our celebrities, but have so managed in this respect, as to give to the banquet an official character. Mayor OPDYKE will preside. Gov. SEYMOUR is expected, and some representative of the General Government will be present.

abstract: -- Before Justice CLERK. -- This celebrated case was decided yesterday, on the motion to transfer the action to the United States Circuit Court, under the act of Congress of March 3, 1863, entitled, "An act relating to habeas corpus, and regulating judicial proceedings in certain cases." The defendant, it will be remembered, was arrested in this City on suspicion of treason, and incarcerated in Fort Lafayette, and now sues Mr. SEWARD. Justice CLERKE delivered an able opinion, defending the action of the Government, and concluded by denying the motion, without costs.

abstract: Some additional particulars have been received with reference to the stoppage of the ship Hahneman, on her way to Bombay, by a Confederate privateer, already mentioned. On the 1st of July, in lat. 25° 25′ S., and lon. 32° 48′ W., while in company with two Dutch barks -- one named the Bulgerstyn, the other name unknown -- they perceived a large brig bearing down upon them with all sail. She passed the two Dutch ships, exchanged signals with them, and then shaped her course for the Hahneman, which was then on the port tack, and heading to S.S.W., with the wind S.E. The brig then fired a blank gun, and the British colors were immediately hoisted on the Hahneman, but she still kept on her course. The American now fired a shotted gun, which, fortunately, fell astern; afterwards, another shot dropped just ahead. The Hahneman then lay to, and the bark rapidly gained upon her, and while she was hauling up her mainsail, the privateer again fired -- this time, two shotted guns -- and one of which very nearly reached the Hahneman, falling in a line with the foremast, and the other passed over the poop, close by the Captain and Mate. The Hahneman was immediately brought to, and waited the approach of the unwelcome stranger. When she was within about 400 yards, a boat was lowered, manned by an officer and four men, heavily armed, three of whom boarded the Hahneman, and demanded her papers. The officer was remonstrated with by the Captain as to his mode of procedure, who replied that if he was sure she was a Federal ship, they would have sunk her rather than let her escape. The ship's papers were strictly scrutinized, with which the officer expressed himself satisfied. The officer, upon inquiry, said his ship was the Tuscaloosa, Capt. LOW, and had run the blockade of Charleston after the defeat of the iron-clads, and had been 50 days out; she had not captured any vessels in that time, although several had been boarded by her. The officer, Mr. ST. CLAIR, a native of Virginia, then left the ship, together with his men, and the Hahneman proceeded on her way.

abstract: The Galway Packet Company have been again unfortunate. The Adriatic was detained forty hours when only 800 miles from Galway, in consequence of "a tender spot" in her steam-pipe, which gave way. She left New-York on the 22d, and reached St. John's on the 25th, having had a pleasant passage so far. She brought 69 passengers, of whom 20 were first-class. She had 19 mail-bags, which were not left at the railway till 3 o'clock, though she dropped anchor at 1:30. The Post-office authorities did not send them off, though there was a special train waiting, the reason assigned being that it would be impossible for them to be in time for the English mail, which leaves Kingstown at 7 P.M. Had the bags been on the platform a quarter of an hour earlier it is said the thing might have been done. But there was really no cause for haste, as the news was all anticipated by the Scotia, which arrived on Friday. The figures tell against the Galway line -- 8 1/2 days against 12; 100 mail-bags against 19; 121 passengers against 69. Of course, the delay was owing to an accident, but the frequent recurrence of accidents does not tend to strengthen confidence.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC.--An excellent and brilliant audience--the most metropolitan in character that we have seen this season--witnessed the performance of "Ernani" last evening, and testified its approval of the same by repeated and long-continued bursts of applause. The opera is one that peculiarly suits Mr. MARETZEK'S artists, whose voices are great and whose styles are vigorous. It is said that VERDI never wrote better...
lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- An excellent and brilliant audience -- the most metropolitan in character that we have seen this season -- witnessed the performance of "Ernani" last evening, and testified its approval of the same by repeated and long-continued bursts of applause. The opera is one that peculiarly suits Mr. MARETZEK's artists, whose voices are great and whose styles are vigorous. It is said that VERDI never wrote better than in this work; but it is perhaps sufficient to admit that he has provided a number of pieces that in energy and color are irresistible. "Ernani" is one of the few operas where finales as well as solos and concerted pieces are encoded. The furore last evening extended to everything, and the performance -- which was an average one -- may be set down as the most successful and enthusiastic of the season. On Wednesday "Macbeth" will be given.

abstract: This reverend gentleman, whose name is so widely familiar as that of an American politician and pulpit orator, preached on Sunday morning in Elgin-place Church -- Mr. BATCHELOR's. Though the notice given of his intention was very brief, the spacious edifice was densely crowded. He went through the preliminary service in a very devout and impressive manner, his reading being particularly distinguished by a clear enunciation and just emphasis that rendered the sound an effective aid to the comprehension of the sense. He chose as the subject of his sermon the necessity for cherishing a spirit of self-sacrifice as an essential part of a genuine Christianity -- founding upon the apostolic exhortation to cultivate "the mind that was in Christ." As might have been expected, his prelection was somewhat startling and peculiar. It certainly was not the production of a commonplace mind nor the effusion of an empty declaimer. On the contrary, it was full of thought and life, now presenting in bold relief some striking idea, now sketching several in succession with great distinctness; at one moment coming forth in a torrent of persuasive and impressive words; at another running into passages of real beauty and moving eloquence, which were anon alternated with touches of sententious vigor, and abrupt, homely, practical remarks, so expressed sometimes that an involuntary smile bespread the faces of the auditory. Confining himself purely to the subject matter of his discourse, he made, contrary possibly to what some of the audience expected, no allusion to the emancipation struggle in America. His text was Philippians, ii., 5: "Let this mind be in you which was also in Christ." The Rev. gentleman will, we understand, be entertained at breakfast this morning (Monday) in the Cobden Hotel, and, after a brief stay in the city, proceed on a tour in the Highlands.

abstract: The Confederate Cotton Loan to-day experienced a renewed rally of 3 per cent., closing at 24 to 22 discount. The recent movements in this loan and in the price of gold at New-York illustrate the partisan folly of those persons who a few weeks back, when gold at New-York, which has just touched 40 premium, was only at 22 premium, were indulging in congratulations at the losses sustained by the speculators in the loan. The speculators in United States currency are, it will now be seen, exposed to trials of a still more sudden and severe character. Both parties are taking the risks of war, and it is puerile to raise a cry of triumph at any of the fluctuations which may result from the turn of a battle.

abstract: No movement that the rebel army has ever made has been so well covered, as to its character, plan and purpose, as the late movement of Gen. LEE. His advance was unexpected, his object has never been discovered, and the numerical strength of his force seems never to have been clearly apprehended. By far the most intelligible account of the rebel march that has yet been given is the detailed letter from the correspondent of the Richmond Enquirer, which we gave in our issue of yesterday. By that it appeared that the whole of the two corps of Gens. HILL and EWELL took part in the movement; and each of the corps had their three Divisions -- RODE's, EARLY's and JOHNSTON's Divisions forming EWELL's corps, and HETH, ANDERSON and WILCOX forming the corps of A.P. HILL. It was on Friday, the 9th inst., that this army crossed the Rapidan River, and the rebel writer who accompanied them describes them as being provided with three day's cooked rations, as being in the "finest kind of spirits," and the only drawback to their good appearance was the fact that a number of men in each division were barefooted. They first moved in a northwesterly direction to Madison Court-house -- then in an easterly direction to Culpepper, then as we know up, to the Rappahannock, from whence they progressed along the line of the railroad as far as Manassas Junction. The whole movement is described as having been conducted with the greatest secresy, and various ruses were adopted to screen their advance from our view. It is evident that they meant to take MEADE by surprise, and that they also intended to flank him or to get in his rear.

abstract: A MYSTERIOUS BOX. -- On Monday night, about 10 o'clock, a man, carrying a heavy wooden box, got in one of the Seventh-avenue stages, near the corner of Twenty-eighth-street. He placed it at one end of the stage and sealed himself at the other. The odor from it soon became so exceedingly sickening, and so peculiarly offensive, that he was ordered to take it out. This he did with some demur, remarking, "It is only fresh meat." In attempting to place it on the top of the stage it fell down and broke, thereby exposing what seemed to be the intestines of a human body in a partially decomposed state. The rascal did not stop to collect the offensive substance, but made off with himself with little delay.

abstract: The Nineteenth Century will be handed down by history as one in which science has made greater progress than any other. Discovery upon discovery has changed almost our entire system of living, so much so that could our forefathers return to earth they would fully realize that a generation inventive and progressive had sprung up in the place of the one to which they belonged. Among them all, medicine has not been behindhand. Many operations, before considered impossible, are now performed with success, and diseases considered incurable, now yield readily under the hand of the skillful physician. A disease, than which there is none more deleterious and insidious, carrying to premature graves hundreds annually, and which has heretofore baffled the skill of the most eminent physicians, is Catarrh. Few realize the fatal consequences from neglecting it. Consumption, that terror of terrors, is but the effects of it in its advanced stages. As many may have it in its incipient stage and not be aware of it, we copy for their benefit the following paragraph from a treatise on it by Dr. ROWE, of No. 49 Concord-street, Brooklyn:

abstract: Last evening, at 5 o'clock, as the steamer Commonwealth, Capt. WILLIAMS, one of the Boston line of packets, was leaving her pier at the foot of Cortlandt-street, she came in collision with the English propeller Salidan, bound for Jamaica, and was considerably damaged. The Commonwealth, at the time of the accident, had just rounded her pier, and was stopped to permit the Flora, a Staten Island ferryboat, to pass, which was not done without the vessels striking each other. No damage, however, resulted from the first collision. Almost immediately after the Flora got clear of the Commonwealth, which at the time was lying still, the Salidan suddenly made her appearance, and apparently without any regard for consequences, struck the Commonwealth on her starboard wheelhouse, carrying away the guard and the "A" frame under the shaft. The damage to the vessel will probably not exceed $1,000. There was considerable excitement on board, but none of the passengers were injured. The English steamer, after the accident, backed off, and went on her way without stopping to inquire the extent of the injury she had done. The Commonwealth will probably be detained four or five days for repairs. The Commodore took her passengers and freight and will temporarily take her place on the line.

abstract: -- The banquet at the Astor House to the Russian Admiral and his officers was the most successful and creditable affair of the kind in this City for many years. For this the credit belongs to the Committee -- Aldermen Froment, Far- and ley, Hall, and Councilmen Keenan, McConne Murray. Alderman FARLEY took the laboring oar, and to his good taste and descretion is largely due the success and the satisfactory manner in which everything passed off. The amount of labor and perplexity endured was enough to have made even a more rotund Alderman than Mr. FARLEY thin, but good nature kept him "fat and hearty," and perseverence saw him through. This banquet was the initiative of a new order of things in the way of Municipal festivities. The Committee were valuably aided by Messrs. WILLIAM HINCHMAN, as Clerk, and TERRY B. SMITH, Sergeant-at-Arms.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- VERDI's celebrated dramatic opera of "Macbeth" will be produced here tonight without fall. The role of the heroine is said to be one of Madame MEDORI's best efforts, and it happens curiously enough that the public will have an opportunity of comparing it to-morrow night with CHARLOTTE CUSHMAN's fine impersonation of the part. This will be a week of Macbeth's, and the Academy of Music monopolises them all. Signor BELLINI has entirely recovered from his recent indisposition, and will sustain his celebrated part of Macbeth.

abstract: Mallon, Brig.-Gen. James E.
snippet: Mallon, Brig.-Gen. James E.
lead_paragraph: Acting Brig.-Gen. MALLON, (of the Third brigade, Second division, Second corps, Army of the Potomac,) killed in action at Bristoe Station, Wednesday, Oct. 14, was of Irish-American parentage, and born in the City of Brooklyn, Sept. 12, 1836. Having received a good commercial education, he was employed first, about eleven years ago, in the house of WRIGHT, GILLET & RAWSON, and subsequently in the firm of HOLCOMB & HARVEY, both in the wholesale commission business in this City. A few years antecedent to the outbreak of the rebellion, he commenced in the same line of business on his own account, and speedily secured for himself an honorable position on the floor of the old Corn Exchange, and of the new Produce Exchange. No one of the younger class of merchants was more widely known or more highly esteemed than Mr. MALLON. He was a most intelligent, energetic and upright business man, faithful in the performance of all his duties, and scrupulously exact in all his mercantile transactions.

abstract: The United States steamer Idaho is being constructed by Mr. HENRY STEERS, at his yard in Greenpoint. Her chief characteristic is speed. Her general dimensions are as follows: Length, 300 feet; width, 42 feet, and depth of hold, 24 feet. Her capacity is about 3,200 tons burden. The model of the Idaho is narrow, running out, both forward and aft, very sharp, and not unlike that of the famous Niagara, built by the lamented GEORGE STEERS. In a vessel designed to carry freight, as a merchantman, the model is very full and wide, while the reverse is the case with the Idaho. The model is so faultlessly rounded that a straight-edge could not rest on any part of the external surface of the vessel. She is strongly put together as a bridge, and a truss-frame go through the upper deck down to the keelson, and extend the whole length of the vessel. When afloat, her sides will present a surface twelve feet above the waterline, giving her a rather long and rakish appearance. She will he very buoyant, and will certainly be an excellent seaboat. The faster she is propelled the higher will her bows be forced up from the water. The cabin and wardrooms will be fitted up according to the latest style. They will be more than usually roomy for a vessel of her class, owing, in a great measure, to the comparatively small space the engines occupy. The cabin is 30 feet long, 18 feet wide, and 6 1/2 feet high. The wardroom is 30 feet long, very spacious and nicely filled up. The ventilation of the vessel will be accomplished according to the best method -- by means of two blowers, driven by engines, with air-tubes communicating with the wardrooms and other parts of the vessel. The magazines are placed one forward and the other aft of the vessel. The gun-deck is 4 1/2 inches thick of yellow pine. The frames of the decks are white and live oak. There are three decks 6 1/2 feet between them -- the gun deck, the berth deck and the orlop deck. The battery is on the gun deck; the berth deck is occupied by the sailors, where hammocks are swung on each side of the whole length of the craft, sufficient to accommodate the full complement of men, which will be 300 souls. Under canvas alone, she could lake the palm over any other vessel of her class that floats on the ocean. She will carry 20,000 feet of canvas, and this will make her go in a good breeze 12 knots an hour. She will be bark rigged. The mainmast and foremast are 90 feet high, and the mizzenmast 80 feet high; the topmast and gallantmast are all in one. The fore and main yards are 85 feet. There will be no yards on the mizzenmast, being bark rigged. She will have the improved wire rigging. Her armament will be very heavy, consisting of 14 broadside puns, the ports being situated at regular intervals along the whole length of the vessel; their calibre is nine inches, PARROTT's design. She will also carry one 200-pounder gun forward and one aft. The engines fur this splendid vessel are being constructed at the Morgan Iron Works in this City, and will be completed in about 2 1/2 months. They are of peculiar construction, direct-acting and have a creator speed of piston than was ever thought could be obtained -- the piston traveling 11,000 feet a minute. An important objection among naval people for the construction of vessels in which almost everything is sacrificed for speed, is the fact that their engines being so powerful and large take up an immense amount of room in the ship. In the Idaho this objection is removed, as the engines take up less room than is usual in vessels of her class, and weigh only 450 tons. On the other hand, Government has ordered engines for the Wambanoga and another vessel whose chief characteristic will be speed, whose engines will weigh 1,200 tons. The cylinders of the Idaho will be four in number, each thirty-six inches in diameter, and eight feet stroke of piston. The dimensions of the cylinders of the iron-clad Puritan, will be 100 inches in diameter, and are indicative of the expected speed of that vessel. The Idaho it will be seen surpasses that amount. Another new feature is the situation of the propellers -- one on each side of the stern-post. Each propeller will be worked by a small and a large screw, for the reason that there is a light draft of water and it is necessary to have more surface than usual to develop the power.

lead_paragraph: It is becoming more and more apparent every day that the gravity of the crisis through which the country is passing, has greatly relaxed the old bonds of party discipline and left private judgment once more free to act in the selection of candidates for public offices. The Democratic party, which was for so long famous for the perfection of its organization, has since the outbreak of the war diminished down to the wretched rump, which received its quietus in the late elections, owing mainly to the determination of the vast majority of the people to vote in accordance with their own notions of right and wrong, and not under the dictation of "managers."

abstract: The sixth discourse of the Rev. C.C. GOSS, on the Moral Aspects of our City, was delivered in the Tabernacle of the Christian Alliance, Broadway, Sunday. It was replete with statistical information in respect to the past and present condition of our city. While lawyers and other professional men have kept up in numbers with the population, ministers have been greatly behind. We have 1,400 lawyers, 1,300 physicians, 2,000 policemen and only 300 ministers. The increase also of our population from 1830 to 1840 was 54 per cent., while that of our churches was much less; in 1850 we numbered 515,394 -- an increase of 64 per cent. The same year we had 214 churches -- an increase of 41 per cent. In 1860 our population was 814,264 -- an increase of 56 per cent.; while our churches only numbered 253, or 31 per cent. This calculation includes all the sects. Catholics have increased in ratio exceeding the population. In 1830 they had four churches. In 1840 -- 7, or 75 per cent. increase; in 1850 -- 18, or 171 per cent. increase; in 1860 -- 32, or 70 per cent. increase. The average per cent. of the population during these decades was 60. Protestants are much behind; all their churches in 1830 numbered 90; in 1840 -- 146, or 63 per cent.; in 1850 -- 203, or 39 per cent.; in 1860 -- 246, or 22 per cent. Catholics also attend church better than Protestants. The census of 1855, reports 194,600 persons in the habit of attending churches -- 100,000 of these are reported as Catholics, and 94,600 as Protestants. Colored people attend better than the whites. In Liverpool, on a bright Sunday morning, 102,092 persons were reported as being in church, out of its 400,000 population. It has 154 churches, accommodating 135,200 persons. London is worse; only 800,000 of its 3,000,000 can be accommodated in churches, and only 17 per cent. are regular attendants. We have 286 churches at present of all denominations, and 250 pastors, with 30 ward missionaries laboring among 1,000,000 of people. Our moral efforts have not kept pace with the growth of the population. Our present agencies are inadequate to the work to be accomplished. They are not inefficient, but insufficient for all that is to be done. Why should we augment our police force annually and not also our moral force? Is not the persuasive influences of the Gospel of as much importance as the coercive power of the police? We pay to the one $400,000, and to the other $1,500,000. We must roll back the tide of sin that has been gaining upon us. "Crime and its cure," was the subject announced for next Sunday evening.

The same year we had 214 churches -- an increase of 41 per cent. In 1860 our population was 814,264 -- an increase of 56 per cent.; while our churches only numbered 253, or 31 per cent. This calculation includes all the sects. Catholics have increased in ratio exceeding the population. In 1830 they had four churches. In 1840 -- 7, or 75 per cent. increase; in 1850 -- 18, or 171 per cent. increase; in 1860 -- 32, or 70 per cent. increase. The average per cent. of the population during these decades was 60. Protestants are much behind; all their churches in 1830 numbered 90; in 1840 -- 146, or 63 per cent.; in 1850 -- 203, or 39 per cent.; in 1860 -- 246, or 22 per cent. Catholics also attend church better than Protestants. The census of 1855, reports 194,600 persons in the habit of attending churches -- 100,000 of these are reported as Catholics, and 94,600 as Protestants. Colored people attend better than the whites. In Liverpool, on a bright Sunday morning, 102,092 persons were reported as being in church, out of its 400,000 population. It has 154 churches, accommodating 135,200 persons. London is worse; only 800,000 of its 3,000,000 can be accommodated in churches, and only 17 per cent. are regular attendants. We have 286 churches at present of all denominations, and 250 pastors, with 30 ward missionaries laboring among 1,000,000 of people. Our moral efforts have not kept pace with the growth of the population. Our present agencies are inadequate to the work to be accomplished. They are not inefficient, but insufficient for all that is to be done. Why should we augment our police force annually and not also our moral force? Is not the persuasive influences of the Gospel of as much importance as the coercive power of the police? We pay to the one $400,000, and to the other $1,500,000. We must roll back the tide of sin that has been gaining upon us. "Crime and its cure," was the subject announced for next Sunday evening.

abstract: About 2 o'clock yesterday afternoon the colors ordered by the City, for the Fifth regiment N.Y.S. N.G., were presented by President WALSH, of the Board of Aldermen, who was acting as Mayor, in the absence of Mayor OPDYKE.
lead_paragraph: About 2 o'clock yesterday afternoon the colors ordered by the City, for the Fifth regiment N.Y.S. N.G., were presented by President WALSH, of the Board of Aldermen, who was acting as Mayor, in the absence of Mayor OPDYKE. The regiment, in heavy marching order, entered the Park by the east gate, and formed in a line, stretching across the entire length of the grand avenue in front of the City Hall. Acting Mayor WALSH then appeared in front of the Hall, accompanied by a number of the members of the Common Council, preceded by Mr. GEORGE W. ROOME, Keeper of the City Hall, bearing the new colors. The colors were taken to the front, and there waved while the municipal deputation reviewed the regiment, the band meanwhile playing "Hail to the Chief." After this, President WALSH made the presentation in a few remarks, taking occasion as well to compliment the regiment for their promptness in responding to the calls of duty.

abstract: Vote Against Copperheads
snippet: Vote Against Copperheads
lead_paragraph: Will some Anti-Administration man, who is wont to protest that his party is very sharp-set against the rebellion, have the goodness to tell us why the vote of the soldiers, when they have the chance to vote, goes so overwhelmingly against its candidates? Don't the soldiers know what good, stiff loyalty is? Don't they go for it when they see it? Either they must be very dull in apprehension, or very deficient in public spirit -- or there must be some screw loose in Copperhead patriotism. Now, how is it? Are the soldiers fools? Or are they renegades? Will some Copperhead tell us which? If they are neither, what then are we to think of their judgment of the Copperheads?

abstract: At the meeting of the Board of Supervisors yesterday, Mr. BLUNT presented a preamble and ordinance relative to the call for volunteers made by the President, and proposing to turn the present Substitute and Relief Committee into a recruiting agency, in order to fill out the City's quota by voluntary enlistments, with power to grant a special bounty of $300 to each volunteer. The subject was referred to the Substitute and Relief Committee. The amount proposed to be raised for the new fund is $2,000,000. Of the $2,000,000 voted to relieve conscripts from the draft, only about $650,000 is likely to be used, and already over 1,700 cases have been acted upon, and over 1,600 substitutes furnished.
