abstract: The Seventeenth New-York Volunteers Veteran regiment leaves on the 21st inst. for the field. This is the only regiment of the two years' men raised in 1861, that returns with its numerical designation. Having raised more men in the reorganisation than any other regiment, it was filled in the consolidation. This regiment was raised in the Spring of 1861 by Col. H.S. LANSING, at present commanding NewYork troops in process of organization.
lead_paragraph: The Seventeenth New-York Volunteers Veteran regiment leaves on the 21st inst. for the field. This is the only regiment of the two years' men raised in 1861, that returns with its numerical designation. Having raised more men in the reorganisation than any other regiment, it was filled in the consolidation. This regiment was raised in the Spring of 1861 by Col. H.S. LANSING, at present commanding NewYork troops in process of organization. It bore a conspicuous part in the Peninsular Campaign, and returned with its flags well riddled, but preserved with honor. This veteran regiment is well officered by veterans. Col. WM.T.C. GROWER went out in 1861 as Captain of Company "D," in the original Seventeenth, and returned as Major. At the battle of Groveton, 30th August, 1862, while in command of the regiment, he was wounded in the leg, which confined him six months to his bed, and from which he is still suffering. Lieut.-Col. EDWARD JARDIN, formerly Major of the Ninth, ("Hawkins' Zouaves,") was wounded severely during the recent riots, and still lies upon his back, but is recovering. Major J.O. MARTIN went out in the original Seventeenth as First Lieut. of Company H, and returned a Captain. He was shot through the cheek at Groveton, Aug. 30, 1862, in the same engagement in which Col. GROWER received his wound. The Adjutant, J.P. HOLLERS, went out in the original Seventeenth as a Sergeant; returned a First Lieutenant. The Quartermaster, A.M. WHALEY, went out in the original Seventeenth as Second Lieutenant of Company K; and returned a Captain. At the battle of Fredericksburgh he had a piece of his skull carried away by a mime bullet, now covered only by a thin membrane. His life was saved by the skill of the then and present Surgeon of the regiment, Dr. JAMES C. STUART, who again returns with it.

abstract: Jones against Seward case
snippet: Jones against Seward case
lead_paragraph: The decision of Judge CLERKE, denying the motion in the case of JONES against SEWARD to remove the cause into the United States Courts, is one which we think will hardly be maintained as good law. Congress, as will be recollected, in March, 1863, enacted that if any suit should be commenced against any officer, civil or military, for any arrest or other trespass committed during the rebellion "by virtue or under color of authority derived from or exercised by or under the President of the United States, or any act of Congress," the defendant might remove the cause into the United States Circuit Court. Mr. JONES, the Ex-Minister to Bogota, was arrested and sent to Fort Lafayette, and now sues the Secretary of State for false imprisonment in having caused such arrest. And the motion was made on behalf of the defendant to remove the cause to the United States Circuit Court, under that act of Congress, on the ground that the alleged arrest and imprisonment was "under authority derived by him from the President of the United States," thus bringing his case exactly within the language as well as the intent of the Act of Congress.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. The revival of VERDI'S opera of "Macbeth" last night must be recorded as the best success, so far, of Mr. MARETZER'S season, Intrinsically there is no interest attached to any Haliar, version of SHAKESPEARE'S plays and least of all to those that have been prepared for the operatic stage.
lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The revival of VERDI's opera of "Macbeth" last night must be recorded as the best success, so far, of Mr. MARETZER's season, Intrinsically there is no interest attached to any Haliar, version of SHAKESPEARE's plays and least of all to those that have been prepared for the operatic stage. A fine soliloquy has not yet been superseded by a grand scena; indeed, the mere touching on the original situations of the great dramatist is attended -- In the minds of the Anglo-Saxons -- with a certain sense of the ridiculous. For reasons such as these the Shakesperian repertoire of the opera has never been a favorite with the public of America or of England. "Othello," "Macbeth," "Romeo and Juliet," "The Merry Wives of Windsor," are all works of undoubted merit, yet how rarely do we find them on our bills? In the selection of "Macbeth" as a subject, VERDI has been more fortunate than any of his predecessors. The characters in it are easily reduced to the required number for the musical stage, white the strength of the plot and the superb directness of the action can hardly be spoilt even by a librettist. The composer has seized his opportunity with avidity, and has accomplished a work of very great emotional interest and still greater musical merit. What situations are retained of the original work are manipulated with all the dramatic skill for which VERDI is remarkable, and are presented by the artists of Mr. MARETZEK's troupe with great gusto. We are disposed to agree with the manager that if the creations of the poet are ever to be interpreted in lyric form, it is probable that VERDI is the composer who will accomplish the task in the most powerful way. There are combinations in "Macbeth" and flashes of feeling that are really worthy of the theme. Greater praise can hardly be bestowed, but it is no exaggeration to say that the work contains some of the happiest ideas that have ever come from the prolific brain of the composer. There is a youthful freshness and vigor in many of the numbers that we shall look for in vain in more recent and better known works. Even in the treatment of the orchestra and chorus there is striking originality. The Witches' music throughout is singularly fitful and weird; whilst the instrumentation in the last act is almost exceptional in its suggestiveness and propriety.

abstract: In New-York; Foundation Stone Laid at New-York; New-York Na ional Academy of Design; foundation stone laid
snippet: In New-York; Foundation Stone Laid at New-York; New-York Na ional Academy of Design; foundation stone laid
lead_paragraph: The new Academy of Design, of which the cor. net stone was laid on the 27th June last the ground for the excavation having been broken in the Spring of this year, Will be one of the handsomest buildings in the United States, and different from any other edifice in the City. It will combine many novel and beautiful characteristics in the highest style of art and taste. The main front extends along Twenty-third-street 80 feet, the side front having a depth of 100 feet on Fourth-avenue, both facades to be of beautiful variegated marble from Tuckahoe, in Westchester County, the white mingling with the grey material in rich and curious designs. The building will comprise a basement and three stories, and the cost of the whole structure amount to about $130,000. The sum has been raised chiefly by subscription, many of our most intelligent, liberal and wealthy citizens uniting in the good work. The facings of the basement will be different from the general frontage and consist of grayish Hastings marble rimmed with bands of North River graywacke stone. This portion of the edifice will be arranged for the accommodation of the janitor and other officers connected with the building. In the upper stories will be the exhibition, lecture and school rooms, with studios and galleries on the second floor.

abstract: The latest reports from the Army of the Potomac report it to be in full pursuit of the retreating rebels. Yesterday the advance of our right column had reached the town of Warrenton and the left column was at Greenwich.
lead_paragraph: The latest reports from the Army of the Potomac report it to be in full pursuit of the retreating rebels. Yesterday the advance of our right column had reached the town of Warrenton and the left column was at Greenwich. Contrary to general expectation no serious opposition was encountered and it is, therefore, very natural to suppose that LEE declines battle. The railroad is in perfect order to Manassas Junction and Gainesville on the Manassas Road. Earlier dispatches announce that on Monday and Tuesday there was considerable cavalry fighting, in which our forces drove the enemy from Gainesville to beyond Buckland Mills. Our lost on the first day were about 200 in killed, wounded and missing, beside several wagons, one of which contained the official papers of Gen. DAVIS' brigade. The enemy were said to be in force at Buckland Mills, four miles beyond Gainesville, and a great battle was considered imminent.

abstract: THE DRAFT IN NEW-JERSEY. -- Col. BUCHANAN, Provost-Marshal-General for the State of New-Jersey, has directed that the draft commence on the 28th inst. The draft will be made in the following order: First, Second, Fifth, Third and Fourth Congressional Districts. The Districts and Sub-Districts will be credited with the volunteers mustered into service previous to the commencement of the draft. Contrary to expectation, the quota of Jersey City is not yet filled, the quota called for being 593 men, and only 500 have been furnished. It is claimed that the apportionment was unequal, and the parties having the matter under control therefore only raised 500 men, with the expectation that that number would suffice. Hoboken is also short quite a number of men, and the draft to make up the deficiency will undoubtedly be enforced.

abstract: RE-ARREST OF AN ESGAPED BURGLAR. A  young German, named CONRAD SCHMIDT, alias Schnelder, well known to the Police as a burglar, was arrested yesterday by Officers RODGERS and SHANGLE, of the Eleventh Precinct, charged with having committed a burglary at the store of Mr. STRAUSS, in Avenue D. a few weeks since.
lead_paragraph: RE-ARREST OF AN ESGAPED BURGLAR. -- A young German, named CONRAD SCHMIDT, alias Schnelder, well known to the Police as a burglar, was arrested yesterday by Officers RODGERS and SHANGLE, of the Eleventh Precinct, charged with having committed a burglary at the store of Mr. STRAUSS, in Avenue D. a few weeks since. This prisoner is the man who succeeded in making his escape from the Tombs about a month ago, by greasing his head and crawling through a small aperture, a full account of which appeared in the TIMES. He was confined there awaiting his trial on two charges of burglary. Since his escape he has concealed himself until a few nights ago. On Monday a store in Avenue D was broken open and robbed of about $500 worth of silk goods. The entrance was effected by forcing off one of the window shutters. The thieves were disturbed in their operation, and in making their escape they dropped a portion of their plunder on the street. Capt. MOUNT immediately instituted an investigation, and finally found a piece of figured silk and a cloak, which was stolen on Monday night, in the possession of a German woman to whom SCHMIDT was about to be married. Most of the stolen property has since been recovered. SCHMIDT was recommitted to the Tombs for trial.

abstract: The Navy Department having contracted with Mr. J.S. UNDERHILL, of New-York, to build a light-draft iron-clad, similar to the Cohoes and Naubuc, that gentleman has commenced the vessel at Green-point, and is progressing rapidly with her. Mr. UNDERHILL is the builder of the Keokuk, and the excellent workmanship of that vessel procured for him from the Navy Department this contract. The keel of the Modoc was laid several weeks ago, and her frame is now assuming shape. The number of alterations ordered in all the light-draft vessels; will prevent their completion before nine or ten months, although it was originally intended to have them afloat in six. Lieut. LARNED has been appointed by the Government as local Inspector of the vessel, and attends every day at his poet. From present appearances it is probable that the Modoc will be one of the fastest vessels of her class.

abstract: Brougham, Lord, on the American War
snippet: Brougham, Lord, on the American War
lead_paragraph: waxes quite rhetorical in discoursing to the Social Science meeting on the American war. But his speech is full of the misrepresentations and falsehoods that he has learned from the London newspapers, and these, mingled with his own bile, make his speech foully atrabilious. It is a dreadful thing for an octogenarian, tottering on the verge of the grave, whose language should have truth as well as authority, to say that the Union people have "exulted in wholesale bloodshed," have "actually gloried in it as a proof of their higher nature," and are "not only unsatisfied with the destruction of half a million, but are vain of the slaughter" -- when he might know that there never were a people so adverse to war with another as the people of the North were to war against the South; and that there never were a people at war who were so anxious to terminate it speedily and honorably, and who would make so many concessions to that end as the people of the North. Everybody in the country remembers the feeling of horror that spread among the people in the Spring of 1861, in prospect of war; and no one outside of the country could conceive the feeling of exultant joy that would now spread over the land on the arrival of the day of peace. But the war was and is an unavoidable necessity; and the Union is absolutely necessary for the permanent security of peace. Though Lord BROUGHAM and the "whole world stand aghast" at this war, neither of them have any conception of the sorrow with which it fills the people of these United States.

abstract: The seventh annual fair and festival of the Society of St. Vincent de Paul opened at the City Assembly Rooms, No. 446 Broadway, on Tuesday, and will continue every day and evening this week.
lead_paragraph: The seventh annual fair and festival of the Society of St. Vincent de Paul opened at the City Assembly Rooms, No. 446 Broadway, on Tuesday, and will continue every day and evening this week. The following Churches are represented at the fair, each having stands filed with the most tempting luxuries, both artistic, ornamental and useful: St. Peter's, St. Joseph's, St. Patrick's, St. James', St. Andrew's, the Nativity, the Transfiguration and the Holy Cross. The attendance during the last two clays has been very large, both day and evening, and the prospects are that this year's fair will be quite as successful as any of the previous ones. There is no place on Broadway where one can spend an evening more pleasantly than here, and certainly none more deserving of the liberal patronage of our citizens. No charitable association in the City accomplishes a greater amount of good during the year than the Society of St. Vincent de Paul. It has the strongest claims to the support of our citizens at all seasons of the year, and at this time par[???][???], when Winter is approaching, should the contributions be liberal. Its annual festivals are unsurpassed in the entertainment offered to the public, and there is not that superlative extravagance that often accompanies those exhibitions, but the purchaser, in addition to the consciousness of having aided a charitable object, almost invariably gets his money's worth. An excellent band of music is in attendance every evening.

abstract: The Removal of
snippet: The Removal of
lead_paragraph: As we are not of the number of those who think that the President ought to take the vote of the people and of the army before removing or appointing a General, we have no fault to find with the dismissal of Gen. ROSECRANS from his command in Tennessee. We are bound, at least in courtesy, to suppose that there are good reasons for a step in many respects so grave, and that in this, as in other things, the President has been guided, in the exercise of an undoubted prerogative, by a sense of duty, and by nothing else. What these reasons are it would be idle now to inquire. It would be just neither to Gen. ROSECRANS nor to the Government to discuss seriously the dozen rumors which are flying from lip to lip touching the General's alleged mistakes, or shortcomings, or misfortunes. We may be sure that we shall know in due time whatever he considers it necessary for the vindication of his own fame that we should know, and until that time comes we may well be spared the task of investigating the probability or improbability of every bit of camp gossip that is offered to us in explanation of one of the most untoward incidents of the war.

abstract: His Proclamation for Volunteers
snippet: His Proclamation for Volunteers
lead_paragraph: We are heartily glad to see the indication which this Proclamation affords, that the Governor will in good faith cooperate in supplying the quota of this State, in response to the last call of the President. It is true that it would be hard -- in fact, in the present temper of the State toward him, almost morally impossible -- for him to do otherwise. The fact is now put beyond all question that it is politically ruinous for any State functionary to refuse or neglect to work with the Government in such objects. The elections of the year have demonstrated that completely. Gov. SEYMOUR would have been infatuated not to heed it. It is also true that some parts of his Proclamation are not free from a bad spirit. The old factious bent shows itself in the odious use of the word "conscription," and the harsh terms connected with it. Whatever may be Gov. SEYMOUR's private opinions of the Enrollment bill, and however fitly he might express those opinions in his own personal capacity, it does not become him in such an official appeal as this, thus to obtrude them upon the public notice. It was wholly unnecessary, not at all dignified, and directly provocative of ill feeling. The National Enrollment act was passed by Congress and sanctioned by the President, as a wise, and just, and needful measure. The great majority of the people so believe it to have been; and that it may yet prove a very potent, if not decisive, instrumentality, in securing the final success of the war. Though Gov. SEYMOUR may honestly think otherwise, this is no reason for his "injecting a stump speech" against the Government measure into a proclamation, ostensibly intended to rally soldiers to the defence of the Government. It is neither good grace, nor good policy, to try to embitter and alienate the people in their relations to the President, and at the same time invoke them to respond to his appeal. The public spirit which stimulates volunteering is largely dependent on trust and faith, and yet these are the very qualities which the harsh language of Gov. SEYMOUR tends to break down.

abstract: one or both of LAIRD'S rebel steam rams, it would seem, has had the "broad arrow" put upon it, or them, and been seized and detained by the British Government.
lead_paragraph: one or both of LAIRD's rebel steam rams, it would seem, has had the "broad arrow" put upon it, or them, and been seized and detained by the British Government. "The vessel is exchequered," says our London correspondent, "and cannot leave until the verdict of a jury, as in the case of the Alexandra, has released her. This will gain time and prevent mischief, and by that time Parliament will be in session or the danger passed away." This action is in accord with the policy indicated in the late speech of Earl RUSSELL at Blairgowrie. The "Southern Club," however, is not pleased with it, and has forwarded a protest to Earl RUSSELL, which is quite worthy of a rebel pen. The Club first declares that "there is no proof of the destination of these vessels," and at once follows this up by saying, "that by detaining the vessels the wishes of those who were fighting to subjugate and extirpate the brave people of the South would be as much complied with as if the vessels were delivered up to them." The statements of the Southern Club, and its great anxiety in the matter, certainly furnish moral, if not legal proof as to the destination of LAIRD's rams.

abstract: The news brought to this port yesterday by the steamship Scotia, two days later, contains one item of vast interest, which will give great satisfaction to the people of this country.
lead_paragraph: The news brought to this port yesterday by the steamship Scotia, two days later, contains one item of vast interest, which will give great satisfaction to the people of this country. The Government of Great Britain has at last come to the decision, dictated no less by its own interests than by the principles of common justice, of detaining the steam rams built at Liverpaol for the rebels. The formal act of seizure was performed on the 9th inst., at least in the case of one of the vessels, and report says that the "broad arrow" was on that data put upon both. A telegram from Constantinople states that the Sublime Porte has offered to purchase the rams, and Earl RUSSELL favors such a disposition of them. The rebel organ in London, the Index, asserts that the Jeff. Davis Government will in future grant no clearances to blockade runners, unless one-third of the outward cargo is taken on Government account. It is urged, moreover, by business men that this measure is not sufficient to remedy the abnormal price of foreign exchange in the Confederate States, and that the Government should take the purchase of supplies exclusively into its own hands, prohibiting the exportation of cotton on private account, except such as is pledged to holders of the Confederate loan. Rev. HENRY WARD BEECHER was publicly welcomed at the Free Trade Hall in Manchester, on the 9th inst., by the Union and Emancipation Society. An opinion prevailed to some extent in France that the Archduke MAXIMILIAN had civilly refused to wear the Mexican Crown, by asking conditions of acceptance that will be difficult to satisfy. A sanguinary engagement is reported to have taken place between the Russians and Poles at Roczanow, but neither results nor particulars are given. The aspect of the Schleswig-Holstein difficulty grows more warlike. Earl RUSSELL had written a conciliatory note to the German Diet, proposing an arbitrament by Powers not concerned in the dispute, and saying that England could not look with indifference upon the military occupation of Holstein. The proposition, thus far, has not been heeded. The latest Liverpool commercial advices announced a buoyant Cotton market, at on advance of 1/4d.@1/2d. per pound. Breadstuffs and Provisions were quiet. Consols for Money closed at 93@93 1/2.

abstract: The Damocratic Ratification Meeting held last night in Cooper Institute, was a large gathering of the "Unterrified." Judge GILBERT DEAN
lead_paragraph: The Damocratic Ratification Meeting held last night in Cooper Institute, was a large gathering of the "Unterrified." Judge GILBERT DEAN presided, and elaborate speeches were made by Judge AMASA J. PARKER and PETER Y. CUTLER, Esq. Outside, on Astor-place, calcium lights and bonfires aided the eloquence of a number of speakers who addressed the crowd from three different stands, one of which was surrounded by a German audience. The feature of the evening was the furious interruption of Judge DEAN by his auditors, dissatisfied with his expressions of strong War Democracy. He was indignant, and so declared himself, offering to retire from the chair, if his Union sentiments did not please them. They called to him in response, "Retire, retire!" He did not do so, but continued his speech, turned a short corner with wonderful agility, and marked ingenuity, and in few minutes was all right again with his hearers. Those who witnessed the performance of the Judge say that aerostation was as nothing to it.

abstract: In the telegraphic summary of European news received from St. John's, N.F., will be found an announcement of the death of JOHN SINGLETON COPLEY, Baron Lyndhurst, whose serious illness was before reported. This eminent British statesman was born in 1772, at Boston, Mass., where his father, COPLEY, the artist, then resided. He was sent to Trinity College, Cambridge, to be educated, and in 1804 was admitted to the English Bar. Having, from 1819 to 1827, successively filled the offices of Solicitor-General, Attorney-General and Master of the Rolls, in the latter year he was elevated, under Tory auspices, to the Lord Chancellorship of England, continuing in office during three Administrations, and afterward accepting the judicial seat of Lord Chief Baron. He resumed his seat on the Woolsack on the formation of the first Peel Ministry, and on the defeat of that Administration became a formidable Opposition leader. His speeches at this time were characterized by power, brilliancy, bitterness and sarcasm, particularly his annual review of each session, and they are considered as having exercised an enormous influence in reanimating the Conservative party, which in 1841 restored power to Sir ROBERT PEEL, and the Great Seal to their author. In 1846, at the fall of the Peel Ministry, Lord LYNDHURST declared himself to be "at the close of his public, almost his natural life," but his voice has since been often heard in the House of Lords. In personal appearance Lord LYNDHURST was remarkably handsome, and although he was not less than 90 years of age, his vigorous and graceful mien gave him a very much younger bearing. For the last eight years Lord LYNDHURST has not been seen in public life, but to the day of his death he continued one of the most trusted advisers of the Crown, and the conduct of the leaders of the party in power is understood to have been greatly influenced, if not entirely guided, by his counsel.

abstract: Washington telegrams assert that the bulk of LEE'S army is again south of the Rapidan, and the Army of the Potomac is once more holding the country east of the Rappahannock. The retreat of LEE is attributed to his inability to obtain supplies, and his advance, take it all in all, must
lead_paragraph: Washington telegrams assert that the bulk of LEE's army is again south of the Rapidan, and the Army of the Potomac is once more holding the country east of the Rappahannock. The retreat of LEE is attributed to his inability to obtain supplies, and his advance, take it all in all, must have been anything but profitable. Gen. MEADE and Staff were yesterday at Washington, and their presence caused a rumor to be circulated that the army was to have a new Chief. Of the truth of it there is neither confirmation nor denial. The extra published last evening by one of the City papers, giving an account of another raid by the rebels at Chambersburgh, Penn., proves, upon inquiry by telegraph, to have had no foundation whatever.

abstract: -- "An emphatic and distinct affirmation that the people of these States intend to fight the rebellion as long as there is any rebellion to fight." This, Hon. HENRY J. RAYMOND, in his late eloquent speech, justly declares to be the meaning of the elections in Maine, California, Indiana, Iowa, Ohio, and Pennsylvania. He is right in believing that an equally emphatic and distinct affirmation will be made in New-York next month. Pennsylvania must take her part in that campaign; for, to the eminent speakers and loyal journals of our sister State we largely owe much of our own success. The Union men in Pennsylvania have not forgotten the noble services of Mr. RAYMOND, of Mr. DICKINSON, of Gen. BUSTEED, of the TIMES and the Tribune, and of other men and journals equally loyal and influential. -- Philadelphia Press, Oct. 18.

abstract: Yesterday afternoon a collision occurred on the North River, opposite the City, between the two large steamers, the City of Boston, of the New-York and Norwich Line, and the Oregon, of the New-York
lead_paragraph: Yesterday afternoon a collision occurred on the North River, opposite the City, between the two large steamers, the City of Boston, of the New-York and Norwich Line, and the Oregon, of the New-York and Hudson Line. The former had left her dock with passengers and freight for Norwich, and the latter with same for Hudson. The collision resulted in the sinking in a few minutes of the Oregon, which was cut nearly in two. Providentially, miraculously as it appears to those on board, no one was lost, and but one slightly injured. The following are statements of the occurrence:

abstract: The Board of Aldermen met yesterday. Resolutions were adopted condoling with the family of Acting Brig.-Gen. JAS. E. MALLON in their bereavement, he having fallen at Bristoe Station.
lead_paragraph: The Board of Aldermen met yesterday. Resolutions were adopted condoling with the family of Acting Brig.-Gen. JAS. E. MALLON in their bereavement, he having fallen at Bristoe Station. A communication was received from City inspector BOOLE, relating mainly to the cost of street-cleaning. The document will be found in full in another column. Mr. BOOLE shows that the present good condition of the streets is maintained at a cost less than the day system involved in 1859, notwithstanding the fact of increased cost of labor as compared with the wages paid at that time. Mr. BOOLE takes occasion to recommend the building of public markets on the Gansevoort and Lowber grounds. The resolution to increase the salaries of fire bell-ringers to $1,000 per annum was concurred in. The Committee on the claims for damages caused by the great powder explosion at the foot of Ninety-eighth-street, East River, of which Alderman FARLEY is the Chairman, reported in favor of paying the claimants various sums, amounting in all to about $50,000, which is a reduction of more than $15,000 from the sum total claimed. The report was laid over under the rule. The Board adjourned to Monday.

abstract: The steamship Hibernia yesterday arrived at St. Johns with advices from Europe two days later, fully confirming the news brought on Wednesday by the Scotia, of the seizure of the
lead_paragraph: The steamship Hibernia yesterday arrived at St. Johns with advices from Europe two days later, fully confirming the news brought on Wednesday by the Scotia, of the seizure of the rebel rams at Liverpool. With the exception of the London Herald, the journals commend the action of the Government, and say the question will now have to be tried upon its legal merits. LOUIS NAPOLEON has sent an autograph letter to MAXIMILIAN, expressive of his satisfaction at the reply made to the Mexican Delegation. Poland has applied to the Western Powers to be recognized as a belligerent, but France at present refuses to accede to the request, and the decision of England is not announced. In the Liverpool Cotton market, on the 12th, sales were made of 30,000 bales at an advance of 1d. Breadstuffs and Provisions remained steady, and Consols closed at 92 7/8@93 for money.

abstract: This valuable historical record of the stenes and incidents connected with the great draft riots of July last, in this City, has only been published for a few days, and nearly the whole of the first edition is
lead_paragraph: This valuable historical record of the stenes and incidents connected with the great draft riots of July last, in this City, has only been published for a few days, and nearly the whole of the first edition is already exhausted. No period in the history of this City will be more memorable than the riot week. It will not be forgotten by this generation, and the stories of it will be transmitted to the generation that follows us. The whole world seems to have listened to the tales of horror, blood and arson -- to the tales of our humiliation and shame. The newspapers all over this country published the details -- fuller details of the riots than they usually do or great battles; and for many weeks after the riots had passed away, the facts were resurrected for us every day by the receipt of newspapers from distant parts of the country. Subsequently the European papers reproduced them and brought them back to us, and only a few days ago we had them once more in the journals of California and the North Pacific coast. We wish that were the last of it, but we are in daily expectation of receiving our exchanges from the Sandwich Islands with the same facts, and then those from the East Indies, from Hong Kong, and from Australia -- until the story shall have rolled round the world and sent all its echoes back to this City, where they and the scenes they depict originated. Worldwide, indeed, has been the interest manifested in the great social and political eruption of July.

abstract: As, at the fall of Vicksburgh in July last, the three great armies which the rebels had long maintained were reduced to two those of BRAGG and LEE so now, the three firstclass armies which we have maintained for
lead_paragraph: As, at the fall of Vicksburgh in July last, the three great armies which the rebels had long maintained were reduced to two -- those of BRAGG and LEE -- so now, the three firstclass armies which we have maintained for nearly two years have been reduced to two -- those of GRANT and MEADE. That splendid army, eighty thousand strong, which in the first months of the year was planted in front of Vicksburgh, and in May, June and July last lay in its rear, exists no more as a unit. Part of it has gone down the Mississippi to Gen. BANKS, part has gone up the Arkansas to Little Rock, part is in East Tennessee, a large part has gone to join the army of Chattanooga, and many detachments are scattered at the various military posts along the line of the Mississippi River. But nearly, if not quite all of these troops are in the new Military Division or Department of Gen. GRANT, and to the old army under his command is now added the late army of Gen. ROSECRANS. This will give Gen. GRANT a very large army -- at least twice as large as that under Gen. MEADE, and six times as large as that under any other General in the country.

abstract: THE NEW ENROLLMENT. Before the new enrollment is commenced here, the Sixth District should receive the attention of Provost-Marshal-General FRY. The difficulties and embarrassments which have prevailed there have brought discredit on the
lead_paragraph: THE NEW ENROLLMENT. -- Before the new enrollment is commenced here, the Sixth District should receive the attention of Provost-Marshal-General FRY. The difficulties and embarrassments which have prevailed there have brought discredit on the Government and created delay in business. The question as to the responsibilities of the majority of the Board, whether they are bodies or nobodies, should be decided; and so, too, should the question whether in doubtful claims of alienship to evade the draft, the Commissioner and Surgeon are right in insisting on going beyond the mere affidavit, and seeking proof from the record. These and other questions must be settled ere the Board can get in working order.

abstract: The rebels dolefully referred to the great fatality of the action at Chickamauga upon their general officers; but if, fortunately, we lost comparatively fewer of them upon the field, its fatality upon us did not then terminate, for not only our chief officer in command, but two out of his three corps commanders have since fallen victims, and only Gen. THOMAS remains. The Confederates, likewise, beside their heavy losses in the action, have through it lost the services of Gen. LEONIDAS POLK; and, from the authentic stories they tell us of the bickerings between officers in BRAGG's army that have occurred since the battle, we should not be surprised if it lost that army, Gen. BRAXTON BRAGG himself, and one-half of his subordinate commanders.
lead_paragraph: The rebels dolefully referred to the great fatality of the action at Chickamauga upon their general officers; but if, fortunately, we lost comparatively fewer of them upon the field, its fatality upon us did not then terminate, for not only our chief officer in command, but two out of his three corps commanders have since fallen victims, and only Gen. THOMAS remains. The Confederates, likewise, beside their heavy losses in the action, have through it lost the services of Gen. LEONIDAS POLK; and, from the authentic stories they tell us of the bickerings between officers in BRAGG's army that have occurred since the battle, we should not be surprised if it lost that army, Gen. BRAXTON BRAGG himself, and one-half of his subordinate commanders.

abstract: Our readers may recollect a letter which we recently published, written from Richmond by the Southern correspondent of the London Times, in which the position and
lead_paragraph: Our readers may recollect a letter which we recently published, written from Richmond by the Southern correspondent of the London Times, in which the position and prospects of the Confederacy were depicted with a glowing pen. Of arms and money they had all they wanted; and there was "another element in the Confederate future so full of hope and promise" that the enthusiastic letter-writer could not pass it by, and that was "the bountiful and redundant harvest of the current year in the Confederate States." He declared "the abundance of cereals to be such that it would supply the whole population for three years to come." We dislike, of course, to throw discredit upon anything which any correspondent of the Times from this country, whether at the North or South, may write; but we have found it rather difficult to reconcile this statement with the prices in the Richmond markets, with the intimations from the South that they were threatened with famine, and with the frequent news of bread-riots in various parts of the Confederacy. And then, still further to increase our disbelief, comes the Chattanooga Rebel, now published at Atlanta, which has notoriously been as truculent, as defiant, as confident as a rebel could be, which declares that ROSECRANS must be driven out of Chattanooga, because, as it says, "food and raiment are our needs. We must have them. Kentucky and Middle Tennessee can only supply them. Better give up the sea coast, better give up the Southwest; aye, better to give up Richmond without a struggle, and win these, than lose the golden fields whose grain and wool are our sole hope."

abstract: HUDSON COUNTY COURT. The Grand Jury of Hudson County adjourned, yesteray, after finding 64 indictments in all. The following named persons were arraigned: James M. Hall, assault and battery;
lead_paragraph: HUDSON COUNTY COURT. -- The Grand Jury of Hudson County adjourned, yesteray, after finding 64 indictments in all. The following named persons were arraigned: James M. Hall, assault and battery; pleaded not guilty. Margaret Cooper, malicious mischief; guilty. Patrick Sullivan, petit larceny; pleaded former conviction. John Warren, petit larceny; not guilty. Chas. E. Gulick, attempting to pass a forged check; not guilty. Patrick Murphy, murder of John Kennedy, at Bayonne; not guilty. Ann Kennedy, assault and battery; not guilty. Jas. McHale, perjury; not guilty. Benj. Ralph, petit larceny; guilty. James McCormick, grand larceny; guilty. John Bell, grand larceny; not guilty. Margaret Cooper, assault and battery; guilty. John Waldron and Michael McKennahan, assault and battery; not guilty. John Mallory, manslaughter of Ann Riley, at North Bergen; not guilty. The trial of Murphy for the murder of Kennedy, is set down for Thursday next. The trial of Mallory, indicted for the manslaughter of Ann Reiley, at North Bergen, is set down for Monday. The trial of Francis Vincent, for robbing, beating and setting his dogs on a German at East Newalk, is also set down for Monday next.

abstract: The steamship Etna passed Cape Race yesterday morning, bringing advices two days later than those received by the Hiberma. There is no important news. A correspondent of the London Post writes from Paris that Louis NAPOLEON has...
lead_paragraph: The steamship Etna passed Cape Race yesterday morning, bringing advices two days later than those received by the Hiberma. There is no important news. A correspondent of the London Post writes from Paris that Louis NAPOLEON has no intention of recognizing the rebel Government. The Mersey rams had been placed under charge of a detachment of marines, and the London Times asserts that though nothing had been decided in regard to them, yet, being suspected, they would not be allowed to slip away as the Alabama did. Queen VICTORIA had availed herself of the occasion of the inauguration of Prince ALBERT's statue at Aberdeen to reenter public life. The shareholders of the steamship Great Eastern have determined to liquidate all claims against the vessel, and put her in the India or Australian trade. There was no change in Polish affairs. The Spanish elections had occurred, resulting in favor of the Government. Sweden declines an alliance with Denmark. The Liverpool Cotton market remained buoyant at advancing prices. Breadstuffs and Provisions continued steady. Consols closed at 93 for money.

abstract: The Fall campaign of Gen. LEE, which has, been in progress for nearly a fortnight past,  and about which we have known so very little and speculated so much, is probably already closed.
lead_paragraph: The Fall campaign of Gen. LEE, which has, been in progress for nearly a fortnight past, and about which we have known so very little and speculated so much, is probably already closed. His army crossed to the northern bank of the Rapidan with cooked rations for fourteen days, on the 9th inst., and it recrossed the river on Wednesday of this week, and returned to the point from which it had started -- having been gone almost the precise length of time for which provision had been made. During that time they made a march which, by the line they took, could not have been short of sixty miles, had a number of heavy skirmishes, and fought an action in which one-half of their force was engaged.

lead_paragraph: Gov. PARKER, of New-Jersey, has issued a proclamation in response to the call of the President for 300,000 volunteers. The quota assigned to the State is 9,441; the quota of each township and ward will be ascertained and published by the AdjutantGeneral at an early day. Credits for all volunteers furnished by each township or ward, will be allowed up to the 4th of January next. The deficiency then existing will be made good by draft. No draft will he made for the deficiency under the former call before the 5th of January: the draft then to commence will be for the deficiency on both requisitions. The Governor urges the people to use every proper effort to fill the quota assigned us by voluntary enlistment, and enforces the call by pointing out the necessity.

abstract: We were obliged, the other day, to condemn in strong terms the spirit of Governor SEYMOUR'S proclamation for volunteers, in response to the new call of the President. While the practical line of conduct which he urged upon the people was the right one, the...
lead_paragraph: We were obliged, the other day, to condemn in strong terms the spirit of Governor SEYMOUR'S proclamation for volunteers, in response to the new call of the President. While the practical line of conduct which he urged upon the people was the right one, the attempt to excite prejudice against the Administration, by indirect reflections, was miserably out of place, and such as could come only from a very poor quality of patriotism. A Governor of a leading State, however much he might, in time past, have dissented from the policy of the National Executive, was bound, when professing to cooperate with that Executive in an act whose necessity he recognized, to avoid studiously every allusion of an invidious character, and to do his best to harmonize and inspirit the hearts of the people. Gov. SEYMOUR failed to do this. Even on so momentous an occasion as this, he did not succeed in rising above his low partisan propensities. It was not a pleasant exhibition, yet Gov. SEYMOUR's character is so well known that it excited no particular disappointment.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. The opera of "Martha" was the attraction last evening. The house, although not crowded, was brilliant, and the ready and discriminating applause testified that it was composed of the right material. We have rarely heard FLOTOW'S favorite work given to greater advantage.
lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The opera of "Martha" was the attraction last evening. The house, although not crowded, was brilliant, and the ready and discriminating applause testified that it was composed of the right material. We have rarely heard FLOTOW'S favorite work given to greater advantage. Of Miss KELLOGG's performance of the leading role we have so frequently spoken, that there is only an opportunity now of recording that its repetition was a complete success. There is no artiste in America who could play and sing the part so well, and we doubt if there is one in Europe who, in simple grace and quiet skill, could render it better. Mlle. SULZER, who was the Nancy, sang and acted with great spirit. Signor LOTTI was received with warmth, and improved the very favorable and even enthusiastic impression which he created in "Macbeth." Signor BIACHI was thoroughly excellent in the great role of Plunkett. We have not heard a better interpretation since the palmy days of Herr FORMES. The whole performance, indeed, was much above the usual standard.

abstract: Our special correspondence from the Army of the Potomac gives a very comprehensive account of the recent military movements in Virginia, and the present situation of the opposing armies. A dispatch from Washington informs us that Gen. MEADE yesterday returned to the front, and the report that he had been superseded by Gen. SEDGWICK seems to have had no foundation.
lead_paragraph: Our special correspondence from the Army of the Potomac gives a very comprehensive account of the recent military movements in Virginia, and the present situation of the opposing armies. A dispatch from Washington informs us that Gen. MEADE yesterday returned to the front, and the report that he had been superseded by Gen. SEDGWICK seems to have had no foundation. Our cavalry now reconnoitre as far as the Rappahannock, and the Army of the Potomac is planted on a line of defence from which there is no possibility of displacing it. The entire losses on our side in the recent movements are estimated not to exceed 1,500.

abstract: As the time approaches wheat New-York is to pronounce her verdict on the great issues now pending between the supporters of the Government and the lovers of the Union, and those who would embarrass the one, even at the risk of destroying the other  the meetings called by the Union Central Committee grow in force, and their interest deepens.
lead_paragraph: As the time approaches wheat New-York is to pronounce her verdict on the great issues now pending between the supporters of the Government and the lovers of the Union, and those who would embarrass the one, even at the risk of destroying the other -- the meetings called by the Union Central Committee grow in force, and their interest deepens. The talent and position of the speakers who appear on each occasion would at any time draw together a large audience, irrespective of the all-absorbing topics of which they treat. Last evening the fourth call of the series was responded to by an assemblage which, for numbers and respectability, vies with any that ever met in the Hall of Cooper Institute. From the platform there was no "uncertain sound," and among the audience no division of sentiment, such as marked the gathering of the pseudo Democracy on Wednesday, but from every part of the house came the true ring of "unconditional" support of the great Union cause, indorsing the sentiment which was emblazoned on a banner in front: "No compromise with traitors; no neutrals in this war; the flag of the Union shall float over Sumter."

abstract: At the Peace Convention of and the New-York riots
snippet: At the Peace Convention of and the New-York riots
lead_paragraph: The Opposition party and the Peace party, if not one and the same, have a very suspicious resemblance to each other. Let any one recall the events of the first three months of 1861. The Southern States, bold and defiant, claiming to have become a separate nation; loyal men at the North astounded and almost paralyzed by the audacity of the traitors; our political fabric seemingly crumbling into ruins. A class of men among us were not in the least surprised nor offended by the action of "their Southern brethren." They scouted the idea of attempting to "coerce Sovereign States." "The chivalry" would never submit to the indignity of coming under "a Black Republican" Government. It was an outrage, and if blood was shed in such a cause it would be in the Cities of the North and not South; and mobs and insurrections would devastate us till we should implore "our Southern brethren" to come and give us the security of a strong Government.

abstract: On Saturday at the Court of Sessions, held by Justices CONNOLLY, WELSH and STEERS, a case was tried in which Mr. PURDY, who keeps a public house at Eighty-first-street and Bloomingdale Road, was complainant, and one MULLIN defendant. It was charged that during the July riots the prisoner and a companion entered Mr. PURDY's house, threatened to close him up with a crowd or "clean him out;" also that they demanded oysters and liquors without pay; that upon Mr. P. refusing them they set upon and beat him; that a boy was sent for an officer, but MULLIN prevented him from going by threatening to kill him. MULLIN was convicted. A difference arose in the Court as to his punishment. Justice WELSH was for giving him four months in the Penitentiary; Justice STEERS was for one month, and Justice CONNOLLY for making it still lighter.

lead_paragraph: The Lexington (Ky.) Union gives an account of the shooting of Dr. BENTON, at Marshall. Saline Country, on the 6th inst. He was tried by a Drum Head Court-martial on the charge of being engaged in various robberies and depredations perout, and is also supposed to have been at the sacking of Lawrence. He was a man of education, a good physician, and about thirty years old. He was quite neatly dressed in a suit of black cloth. One of the soldiers, a few moments before he was shot, knelt in prayer with the doomed man; he was then ordered to take his coat off, his arms pinioned behind, and seated on his coffin. Sixteen men fired, killing him instantly.

abstract: The Tactics of Parties and Bismarck
snippet: The Tactics of Parties and Bismarck
lead_paragraph: As the time for the elections approaches, the policy and tactics of Ministerialists and Nationalists become more clearly defined. The rumors about the King's sudden conversion to liberalism were all fictions. Despite the warnings he has received of his waning popularity, and of the consequences of persisting in his career of despotism, he has taken his stand by VON BISMARK, and indorsed all the unprincipled devices of that reckless statesman. It now appears that the dissolution of the last Diet was, in a great measure, the effect of terror. Both Monarch and Minister shrank from the ordeal of having to give an account to the Lower Chamber of their evil deeds, and so they decided to get rid of it. But what if the obnoxious and dreaded Deputies should be returned at the coming election? What if the popular party should present themselves in still greater force, and with still more determined aspect in the new Diet? To prevent this, every means, right or wrong, is being employed by the Court. A circular has been addressed to all the provincial Presidents by the Minister of the Interior, instructing them to warn all persons holding office under Government that they must give their unqualified support to the Crown candidates, if they would not incur the royal displeasure. For "whoever has sworn as an official," adds the Minister, "to be submissive, faithful, and obedient to the King, his most gracious sovereign, is not relieved from this oath, either as elector or elected."

abstract: A man named MAURICE BURKE, aged 62 years, residing at No. 62 Mulberry-street, died yesterday from the effects of injuries accidentally received on the Third-avenue Railroad, under the following circumstances.
lead_paragraph: A man named MAURICE BURKE, aged 62 years, residing at No. 62 Mulberry-street, died yesterday from the effects of injuries accidentally received on the Third-avenue Railroad, under the following circumstances. On the 30th of September last, the deceased, with his wife and two children, one aged 11 years and the other 4, were riding down town, on their return from Jones' Wood, in a Third-avenue car. A dispute arose between BURKE and the conductor in reference to the fare. BURKE insisted that he should be charged nothing for the ride of his youngest child; the conductor on the contrary was steadfast in his purpose to charge half fare for this child, in pursuance, as he said of the established rules of the Company. BURKE became very excited upon the subject, and in his zeal to defend his rights, he blocked up the platform so that passengers could not get on or off. The Conductor finally became impatient, and told BURKE he must either get off me car or take a seat inside, at the same time making a movement to compel him to do one or the other. BURKE then caught the Conductor by the beard and the coat collar, and in the struggle they both fell from the platform to the ground. BURKE had one of his legs fractured and he was otherwise so much injured, that he died at Bellvue Hospital, yesterday, from the effects. Coroner COLLIN held an inquest on the body, when the above facts were elicited. The jury rendered the following verdict. "We find that deceased, MAURICE BURKE, came to his death from a fracture of the leg received while being removed from a Third-avenue car, and we exonerate the Conductor from all blame in the matter." The number of the car upon which this accident occurred did not transpire. The deceased was a native of Ireland.

abstract: Guns and Naval Supremacy
snippet: Guns and Naval Supremacy
lead_paragraph: The English Press, for the past few months, has been over-lavish of hints and groans, bearing upon the non-success of certain artillery and prorjectile experiments, the initiation of which, two or more years ago, with the most fearful boasting, was calculated to make all the world shake in its shoes at the threatened tripling and quadrupling of John Bull's shooting ability. Heretofore they have given way only to hints and groans, but now the Birmingham Morning News, of Oct. 5 -- a paper of high authority upon all matters of manufacture or mechanics-comes out flat-footed, and declares all the Armstrong guns failures, giving data for its opinions, and pointing with a steady finger at each monster piece of ordnance, recites in unmistakable words the history of its birth, life and death --not even hesitating to declare the whole Armstrong contract a job, and a gross imposition upon the British people.

abstract: FOREIGN RELATIONS OF THE CONFEDERACY. -- JEFF. DAVIS, as he was returning from his visit to BRAGG's army, made a speech at Selma, Ala., on the 18th inst., and we find a telegraphic abstract of it in our Southern files. In the course of it he touched upon the foreign relations of the Confederacy, and remarked: "Self-reliance and energy is now our only duty; we should not look to Europe for aid, for such is not to be expected now." So JEFF. DAVIS has at last given up what has been one of his fondest hopes ever since the rebellion broke out -- hope of aid from abroad. We do not doubt that, in saying this, JEFF. "spoke by the book," or rather by the dispatch, and that it was based upon information derived from his emissaries in Europe. Even on the outside, Confederate foreign relation look less hopeful now than ever before. The withdrawal of MASON from London; the dismissal of British Consuls from the Confederacy; the seizure of the rebel rams; the coldness of NAPOLEON, and the almost impossibility of his aiding the rebels; these and other known facts are not cheerful. But JEFF. DAVIS knows still other things than these, and when he dashes the hope of the rebels for foreign aid, we may be sure that he had reason for doing so.
lead_paragraph: FOREIGN RELATIONS OF THE CONFEDERACY. -- JEFF. DAVIS, as he was returning from his visit to BRAGG's army, made a speech at Selma, Ala., on the 18th inst., and we find a telegraphic abstract of it in our Southern files. In the course of it he touched upon the foreign relations of the Confederacy, and remarked: "Self-reliance and energy is now our only duty; we should not look to Europe for aid, for such is not to be expected now." So JEFF. DAVIS has at last given up what has been one of his fondest hopes ever since the rebellion broke out -- hope of aid from abroad. We do not doubt that, in saying this, JEFF. "spoke by the book," or rather by the dispatch, and that it was based upon information derived from his emissaries in Europe. Even on the outside, Confederate foreign relation look less hopeful now than ever before. The withdrawal of MASON from London; the dismissal of British Consuls from the Confederacy; the seizure of the rebel rams; the coldness of NAPOLEON, and the almost impossibility of his aiding the rebels; these and other known facts are not cheerful. But JEFF. DAVIS knows still other things than these, and when he dashes the hope of the rebels for foreign aid, we may be sure that he had reason for doing so.

abstract: An informant of the Era, who derived his facts from Mr. T.C. HAGGERY, just arrived from Matamoras, via Galveston and Sabine Pass, says: "The armament of Galveston consists of forty guns. The guns are mounted on cars leading to the fortifications, and so arranged as to be moved from one point to another, as contingencies may require, and taken from the island if necessary. The novelty of this manner of concentration of fire by the car arrangement is clever indeed, to say the least of it. The rebels firmly believe that their guns have sufficient calibre to repel any movement by our army or navy."

lead_paragraph: The canvass in this State promises the most satisfactory results. It is carried on everywhere with the utmost vigor on the part of the Union men, and from every section of the State we have assurances of substantial gains for the Union cause. We have not yet heard of a single county which is likely to increase the Democratic vote over that given last Fall; while in New-York alone it is confidently believed the Union ticket will gain quite enough to overcome the majority by which Gov. SEYMOUR was elected a year ago.

lead_paragraph: Notwithstanding the enormous proportion of men heretofore sent to the field by the State of Indiana, it is expected that its quota under the new call will be raised without a resort to draft. The Indianapolis Journal of Friday last says that the new regiments are filing up rapidly, and that some of them will be ready for the field in a month, if not sooner. There is not the same promise in all the districts, but in none is the work falling behind what was expected. The evident and acknowledge exhaustion of the rebellion, and the certainty that a large increase of our army will crush it almost without an effort, are impelling young men into the ranks that they may share the glory of the victory in the greatest civil war in the history of the world. This motive, in spite of all the weariness and distrust that slow movements and numerous blunders have made, is still strong, and still, as new regiments are called for, fills up the ranks, and sends out fresh energy and spirit to the fight. There are other influences at work, no doubt, but we have seen and heard enough of the feelings of our soldiers, not officers, but privates, to feel certain that many a heart enters the ranks with a warmer thought of the glory it is to gain than of the pay it may get. And while this is cherished we shall not abandon a jot of our confidence in the speedy raising of our new regiments, nor the certain defeat of the rebellion.

abstract: It can do possible harm to say that Gen. MEADE and Staff reached this place last night, and pitched tents on the Culpepper road, near where headquarter were located in the latter part of July last. This is the third time the headquarters of the army have been located in Warrenton within a year.
lead_paragraph: It can do possible harm to say that Gen. MEADE and Staff reached this place last night, and pitched tents on the Culpepper road, near where headquarter were located in the latter part of July last. This is the third time the headquarters of the army have been located in Warrenton within a year. Where the army is to go next I do not know, and would not tell if I did. Supplies for the army are now received via Gainsville, which involves a land carriage of ten miles, and the probabilities are that no advance will be made, at least, until such time as a more convenient point for receiving supplies can be hit upon. Whether that will be Culpepper -- which will involve the reconstruction of that portion of the Orange and Alexandria Railroad, recently destroyed by the enemy -- or some other point, I do not believe has yet been decided upon. The opinion advanced by me in a letter during the early part of the recent movement, to the effect that LEE did not mean fight unless he could secure some great advantage of position, or find an opportunity to whip this army in detail, is now generally coincided with. That the enemy had some ulterior motive other than anything immediately connected with a northern campaign, is now also quite apparent. Whether or not it was from sheer desperation produced by the failing fortunes of the affairs of the so-called Southern Confederacy, which rendered apparent offensive operations necessary, and an effort to prevent an advance upon Richmond or a cover, as some profess to believe, for a further reinforcement of BRAGG, are among the questions to be answered in the future. The evidence is constantly accumulating that Richmond has been at the merey of this army for the last two months, and is so now. Why the opportunity has not been improved, is one of the mysteries that puzzles all those who have nothing else with which to occupy their attention, and who do not profess to know the line of policy adopted for this army. Whatever might have been LEE's object in advancing as far as Warrenton, he was completely foiled and out-generaled by MEADE, so far as the actual movements were concerned. Twice LEE was offered battle: once on Monday of last week, on the right bank of the Rappahannock; and again on the following Wednesday, at Manassas, where the Second corps was attacked. These offers of battle were both declined, and the bulk of LEE's army was employed in destroying the Orange and Alexandria Railroad. Aside from the attack on the Second corps, the attack upon Gen. BUFORD's command, near Brentsville, the following day, while guarding the rear of the army-train -- when quite a severe fight occurred, in which the division fully sustained its character as an efficient organization -- and the one on KILPATRICK's cavalry, at and near Buckland's Mills, no others of consequence have been made by the enemy. There are those who believe that the destruction of the Orange and Alexandria Railroad indicates that JEFF. DAVIS proposes for the future to abandon to its fate all that portion of Virginia north of the Rappahannock, as well as by that act to retard the advance of the Union army. I do not feel competent to offer any opinion as to the plausibility of any of the theories advanced in this letter, but give them as advanced by others.

abstract: ATTACK UPON COLORED WOMEN. -- On Saturday night last a colored girl, named HARRIET NEAL, was attacked at the entrance of Jackson's Court, corner of Front-street, by a gang of half-drunken fellows, and severely beaten, without any provocation whatever. She ran home, and a physicion was called to her assistance. Her mother, JULIA NEAL, subsequently went out with a pail to get some water from the pump, when she was set upon by the same fellows, who kicked and beat her in the most brutal manner. She was escorted home by a colored man named ROBERT SMITH, who was attacked, and in defending himself inflicted a severe, though not dangerous wound upon MICHAEL SPELLMAN, one of the assailants, with a knife. SMITH, who is better known as "Friday," was arrested by Sergeant CRAFT of the Forty-second Precinct Police, and locked up to await examination.

abstract: The United States gunboat Tennessee, Lieut. Commanding WIGGINS, arrived yesterday from a cruise off Galveston. It appears that our gunboats in the Gulf have been after the rebel blockade-runners in an active manner. On the 12th inst., when about ten miles off San Luis Pass, a schooner was discovered in sight. Chase given immediately; and on coming up, she proved to be the rebel blockade-runner Friendship, bound from Havana to Matamoras. But, as she was evidently steering for Valasco, and was heavily laden with munitions of war, the Captain acknowledged he was a fair prize. The Friendship was taken in tow, and the Tennessee proceeded on her cruise. In half an hour more a sail was made about ten miles off. Chase was given; and on coming up within about three miles she was discovered to be on fire. A boat was sent out to board and try and save her; but when the launch came within about 400 yards, the schooner blew up with a terrific explosion. From the magnitude of the noise and concussion, it was thought the schooner was heavily laden with powder. The missiles from the destroyed vessel were scattered around on the sea for hundreds of yards. There were also a quantity of percussion caps included in the cargo, which was evidenced by the sound of small and continuous explosions heard after the grand flareup. The wreck proved to be the Jane, of Nassau, N.P.

abstract: Judiciary, Duty of Honest Citizens
snippet: Judiciary, Duty of Honest Citizens
lead_paragraph: There will be next week a capital opportunity for those patriots who are anxious to serve their country without doing to the war, to do so in a very effectual manner, by the vote they will cast in electing the judges for the Superior, Common Pleas, and Marine Courts. We therefore beg respectfully to remind our readers that next to fighting for one's country comes the duty of keeping the country worth fighting for. It is a very fine thing to shoulder a musket and march to the field, but it is almost as fine to use one's influence for the protection of the life, property, and reputation of one's fellow-citizens at home; and this can in no way be done so effectually as by maintaining the respectability, independence, purity, and learning of the judiciary.

abstract: Ireland and its Condition
snippet: Ireland and its Condition
lead_paragraph: The condition of Ireland is again attracting unusual attention in England. It may be summed up by saying that emigration is steadily increasing, population steadily diminishing; that the grain crops are decreasing every year, as are also the green crops; that pasturage, fallen woods, plantations, bog and waste land are spreading over a wider and wider area. In other words, there is every possible indication of steady decline. Men are disappearing, and wealth is not accumulating; on the contrary, the sources of wealth are fast drying up.

abstract: The unexpected intelligence comes to us from our special correspondent with the Army of the Potomac, that the rebel army in force has again crossed the Rappahannock. This movement took...
lead_paragraph: The unexpected intelligence comes to us from our special correspondent with the Army of the Potomac, that the rebel army in force has again crossed the Rappahannock. This movement took place on Saturday morning, when a body of the enemy's infantry made the transit of the river on two pontoon bridges, near Rappahannock Station of the Orange and Alexandria Railroad, and driving back GREGG's cavalry division, which suffered severely, had a short engagement with two of our infantry brigades. These in turn seem to have fallen back, as the rebel force pressed forward seven or eight miles and attacked the cavalry under Gen. DIVEN, near Bealton Station. At this point we are told that the fighting was severe, but the result is not announced. Our correspondent says that the rebel left is now in position near Bealton Station, and stretches away in the direction of Stafford Court-house. What this movement means is at present a mystery. It is scarcely to be supposed that LKE will retrace the ground he has so recently abandoned, after the costly expenditures which his late experiment occasioned. In the fight near Bealton Station, Major TAGGART, of the Second Pennsylvania cavalry, formerly a member of Gen. KILPATRICK's Staff, and reputed to have been the best swordsman in the army, was killed.

abstract: Chattanooga a Vital Point to the Rebels
snippet: Chattanooga a Vital Point to the Rebels
lead_paragraph: The rebels appreciate the value of Chattanooga quite as well as we do. They know that it is really the most important position now held by our armies -- important in its military bearings, important in its bearing upon the question of supplies, and also in its political aspect. Look how it fronts upon Georgia and the Carolinas; see how it defends Tennessee and Kentucky -- how it flanks Alabama and Mississippi; observe how, through BURNSIDE's line, it furnishes us a back door entrance into Virginia itself. It is a central, a pivotal point; and our army can swing round upon it in such a way as to assail any part of the Confederacy as it now exists. If we continue to hold it, and to maintain a great army there, we could afford, so far as the purely military view of the case is concerned, to take our leisure, and take our own way by which to proceed to the ultimate demolition of the Confederate power.

abstract: INVALID CORPS. -- Yesterday afternoon about 4 o'clock, two soldiers doing duty at the Provost-Marshal's office in Broome-street, while returning with dispatches from the Provost-Marshal General's office, were run over by lager-bier wagon, on the corner of Canal-street and Broadway. One of the soldiers, CHAS. WHITE, late of the Twenty-seventh Massachusetts, had his leg broken in two places; the other, THOMPSON S. SIMPSON, One Hundred and Third Pennsylvania, was also severely hurt, although Dr. FAY, of the Soldier's Home, said he had no bones broken. Two much praise cannot be given to the officers in charge of the Soldier's Depot for their prompt attention to the wants of the soldiers, for in less than five minutes after the accident happened, while both men were waiting for the police to take charge of them, Col. NEVILLE, Superintendent of the Soldiers' Depot, accompanied by Courier MCMAHON and DUNLEAVY, were promptly on the ground with conveyance to take charge of the injured soldiers, who were taken to the corner of Howard and Mercer streets, where their wounds and wants were attended to.

abstract: A paragraph in one of the Atlanta papers, giving an account of the suspension of Gen. POLK from his command, has done injustice to the veteran soldier. We learn, says the South Carolinian, from the best authority, that the suspension was unnecessary and hasty, and that upon investigation he will be entirely vindicated from the charges against him. In fact, there is every reason to believe that the charges will be withdrawn, and the Court of Inquiry dispensed with. In expressing this conviction we are sure that it will give satisfaction to the country, which has the highest confidence in the military ability of Gen. POLK. -- Savannah Republican.

snippet: Reply to the Missouri Delegation
lead_paragraph: The President, in his manner of meeting the appeal of one of the parties in the Missouri quarrels, has displayed a broad-souled patriotism that every loyal man in the country ought to take as a model. While aiming to do justice in the premises, he refuses to identify himself with either side in the controversy. Having in vain done his best to reconcile the conflicting views and policies, he readily takes the responsibility of enforcing his own independent convictions.

abstract: On the New-York Riots and the TIMES
snippet: On the New-York Riots and the TIMES
lead_paragraph: The World has seen fit to comment on a recent communication in our columns, with regard to the riot, as inconsistent with the charges so habitually made through the country against the Peace Democrats for instigating this fearful outbreak. It is quite natural that both the presses and leaders of the Opposition should feel very sensitive with respect to this exhibition of Copperheadism in our City. There were circumstances connected with it which the public -- especially the rural public -- will not easily forget. For months, the Copperhead Press of this City had been stigmatizing a National act of legislation, which was indispensable to the very preservation of the Government, as a proceeding of measureless tyranny. A provision which was designed to cut off all competition in purchasing substitutes, and which was thus, in fact, the protection of the poor man, was denounced as favoring the rich and crushing the laboring class. All the arts of sophistry and eloquence were exhausted to depict the draft as a means for relieving the upper classes of their burdens and throwing them on the lower. The Union and Republican leaders were pictured as rich and fortunate men, gorged with contracts, who were seeking to make the laborer and foreigner do the fighting while they carried off the profits. The orators in the "Democratic" meetings, with the skillful touch of unprincipled demagogues, played on this dangerous class-prejudice before their ignorant and passionate audiences. They were boldly called on "to resist despotism;" to submit no longer to this atrocious tyranny of wealth and office, and "to strike for their liberties." Prophecies were cunningly made in those base organs which are read in rum-shops, and at corner "groceries," where "the people" congregate, that the execution of these odious acts of oppression by the rich would call forth a second French Revolution of blood and carnage. Exciting pictures were drawn of the revenge which the poor and honest laboring people might wreak, in return for these wrongs inflicted on them by the powerful. It was assumed that the lowest classes of New-York -- "the people" -- were all-powerful, and that any law attempted to be executed against their will would utterly fail; that no force in the Government could possibly control them. Bold and straightforward men like ANDREWS, and more cunning and dangerous men who go yet "unwhipt of justice," thus for months before the draft, in bar-rooms, caucuses, political meetings and newspapers, busied themselves in doing the devil's work of firing the passions of "the people" against the better classes. And what was this "people?" Our correspondent, as the World now admits, has only too clearly described them.

abstract: Two of our cotemporaries yesterday published articles aiming to show first that the route by the Peninsula is the only one by which we can ever hope to reach Richmond, and, secondly, that it is impossible the Administration should adopt this route, for the reason that it was the one chosen by the General of whom these journals have constituted themselves the especial champion  McCLELLAN.
lead_paragraph: Two of our cotemporaries yesterday published articles aiming to show -- first that the route by the Peninsula is the only one by which we can ever hope to reach Richmond, and, secondly, that it is impossible the Administration should adopt this route, for the reason that it was the one chosen by the General of whom these journals have constituted themselves the especial champion -- MCCLELLAN. Now we were not aware that Gen. MCCLELLAN had taken out a patent for the Peninsular line of operations against Richmond, though we had supposed that the lamentable failure he made in his attempt to reach the rebel capital by this route, would not prove a very powerful temptation to infringe any right he may have to its exclusive possession. We rather fancy, however, that it will be found that the chief obstacle to our gaining Richmond by any of the half-a-dozen attempts we have made against it, by both the overland and the Peninsular lines, has been the rebel army that has obstructed our path, rather than anything in the path itself. If we could only discover a method of eliminating LEE's army we imagine "On to Richmond" would be an easy task. Until that is done there will be a very serious obstacle to our getting there by any route. On the face of the map there is certainly nothing in either the overland or the Peninsular line to Richmond that need much embarrass an advance. They are both good enough, and we do not know that there is much to choose between them. From the line of the Rappahannock, now held by our advance cavalry, the distance to Richmond is but sixty miles, with the advantage of a railroad and several rivers by which to supply an army -- a task which, put into comparison with ROSECRANS' great march from Murfreesboro to Chattanooga is but child's play. In the mere matter of the territorial march the Peninsular line is, undoubtedly, the shorter, but this route has the counterbalancing disadvantages which always attach to military operations dependent on a water-line for connection with the base of supplies. We take it that the question of an advance to Richmond is one which will be decided purely by military contingencies. If LEE ventures on the further subtraction of another corps from the army of Northern Virginia for reinforcement to the army fronting Chattanooga it will open to Gen. MEADE an opportunity which he will quickly seize. If he does not venture to make this subtraction, owing to the menace of MEADE's presence, the Army of the Potomac will still be serving the purpose of keeping that force in check and thus lessening the task of our army in Tennessee. Whether or not Gen. MEADE should at present attempt a new campaign against Richmond, is, therefore, simply a question of the relative strength of the two armies, and the cant about the "road to Richmond," and the ascription of any special magical virtues to that by the Peninsula, is the dictate either of an unintelligible stupidity or of a very intelligible factiousness.

abstract: The Governor has offered a reward of $500 for the apprehension of RUCKER, who escaped from the Pittsylvania County jail on the night of Sunday last. It is believed that a "woman was in the case," as one was in the neighborhood with a buggy the day previous, pretending to buy up specie among the negroes. Immediately after RUCKER's escape, search was made for the woman, but she and buggy too had disappeared. We conclude that RUCKER, by this time, is safe within the friendly lines of the enemy, and we shall never see his like again. The law's delay, in this instance at least, has favored the culprit.
