abstract: Both Boards of the Common Council had long sessions yesterday, and acted upon a large num  ber of minor matters.
lead_paragraph: Both Boards of the Common Council had long sessions yesterday, and acted upon a large number of minor matters. The Aldermen adopted Mr. OTTIWELL's ordinance increasing the salaries of the Mayor's clerks -- a very proper measure, in view of the fact that their pay at present is the same as it was fixed years ago, when the duties of the office were far less than now, and prevailing prices for all things were very much lower. The Councilmen concurred in adopting the resolutions of respect to the memory of Brig.-Gen. MALLON, and also concurred in adopting the resolution directing the Corporation Counsel to proceed against all parties who have put down railroad tracks in the City without municipal authority. Both Boards adjourned to Thursday.

abstract: Mr. MARETZEK may be congratulated on the frequent successes which he is now winning, During the first and second weeks of the season, the very plague itself seemed to have descended upon the company, Disappointments were of frequent occurrence ...
lead_paragraph: Mr. MARETZEK may be congratulated on the frequent successes which he is now winning, During the first and second weeks of the season, the very plague itself seemed to have descended upon the company, Disappointments were of frequent occurrence, and neither the opera nor the singer could be depended upon for more than an hour at the time. If the weather and the press had not been equally favorable there is no knowing what might have happened to the management. All these little troubles are now happily at an end. Two unquestionable successes were achieved last week. "Martha," with Miss KELLOGG, and "Macbeth," with Mme. MEDORI. The latter of these works was repeated last night for the second time. An admirable attendance was present, and testified its approval of the opera in the heartiest way. The performance was much better than on the first night. It is always so when the company feels confident of success, and knows that it is directly contributing to it. Mme. MEDORI sang and acted with great dramatic power and skill. In a work like this there is scope for the varied abilities of this veritable prima donna. Her large voice is amply provided for by the composer, and there are opportunities for rolling it out in a highly impressive way. Mme. MEDORI was received with enthusiasm, and had to repeat her principal morceaux. Signor BELLINI was again in excellent voice. We have no recollection of ever having heard him to greater advantage. The entire performance was much above the average.

abstract: Capt. PETER SQUIRES, of the Second Precinct, died yesterday morning, at his residence in Second-avenue, after a long and painful illness. He was about 48 years of age, and a native of this State. Capt. SQUIRES was appointed under the administration of Mayor BRADY, in 1847, and was therefore one of the oldest Captains on the force. He was first sent to the Eleventh Ward, where he served in the capacity of Captain for several years, to the entire satisfaction of all concerned. He was then sent to the Second Precinct, where he was at the time of his death. A family, consisting of a wife and six children, are left to deplore his loss. His funeral will take place on Thursday next, at 11 A.M., from Dr. SMITH's Church, corner of Ridge and Broome streets. It will be attended by the officers of the Department generally.

abstract: A little over three years ago, says the Register, the present site of Oil City could only boast of one business house, that of J.P. HOPEWELL. The balance of the land was cultivated as a cornfield. The mouth of Oil Creek was only known as a stopping-place for raftsmen, on their way from the famed lumber region to Pittsburgh. The oil discovery, occurring about that time, brought the energetic, enterprising men of every State to the piece. How well they have done is shown by the present business aspect of Oil City -- fifteen stores, besides numerous establishments classed as pipe, harness, shoemaker and other kinds. Three first-rate restaurants, two billiard saloons, enough places where "boomerang whisky" is vended to kill the whole Southern army, strong as their stomachs are, and two drug stores. The buildings along the main street are substantially, and in some cases, elegantly built. There is only one thing lacking, that is a good paved street. The present one is a disgrace to any civilized community.

abstract: A sad accident occurred on Sunday last, at No. 167 Third-street, whereby Mrs. AUGUSTA SCHMIDT, wife of JOHN SCHMIDT, lost her life. The following are the circumstances as testified to yesterday upon the inquest held by Coroner NAUMANN on the body of Mrs. S.: About a week since SCHMIDT loaned his revolver...
lead_paragraph: A sad accident occurred on Sunday last, at No. 167 Third-street, whereby Mrs. AUGUSTA SCHMIDT, wife of JOHN SCHMIDT, lost her life. The following are the circumstances as testified to yesterday upon the inquest held by Coroner NAUMANN on the body of Mrs. S.: About a week since SCHMIDT loaned his revolver to a friend, and on Sunday last he went for it and took it home with him in the evening. Mr. HARK, the friend, had been threatened on Saturday night by some rowdies, and loaded the revolver, but having no occasion to use it, he left it in that condition. The latter was not at home when SCHMIDT called for it on Sunday, and a servant handed it to him. The husband took the pistol out of his pocket in his wife's room, and was about to hang it up, when it was by some means discharged. One ball entered the back of his wife, passed entirely through her body, and lodged in the groin just under the skin. From the effects of this wound she died soon after. Just previous to her death she made an affidavit before Coroner NAUMANN, in which she stated the circumstances substantially as above set forth. Mr. SCHMIDT has been ill for the last two years, and this calamity has affected him very deeply, rendering him almost beside himself. The mother has left four children, the eldest only seven years of age.

abstract: "M. BILLAULT was successively President of the Corps Legislatif, Minister of the Interior several times, and Senator; but he did not play a really important part until the decree of the 24th of November, 1860. In the full possession of his means M. BILLAULT surpassed public expectation; he performed a laborious and fatiguing task with sustained brilliancy, and it is only justice to attribute to him the greater part of whatever lustre was reflected by the institution, now abandoned, of the ministers without portfolio. When it was resolved to take another step toward the preliminary system, and no longer to send to the Chambers mere government orators, like the ministers without portfolio, but such politicians as were the most intimately familiar with the controlling idea, and the most capable of formulating it, nobody was surprised to find M. BILLAULT, selected for this eminent and special post. He seemed naturally intended for it; the new ministry of State as defined by the decrees of the 24th of June, appeared made for him. The death of M. BILLAULT has therefore all the significance of a political event; and no one will protest if we say that it leaves a considerable void which it will be very difficult to fill up."

abstract: Gov. YATES, of Illinois, has issued a proclamation in response to the call of the President for Volunteers. He fully coincides in the necessity of increasing the army, expresses pride in the patriotism of the people of the State, who have never been appealed to in vain to come forward to the rescue of the country, forbids all recruiting in the State except for its own regiments, and announces that the crisis of the war is rapidly approaching, to be passed in safety to the Republic and triumph to our arms, if the additional forces asked for are promptly marshaled for the occasion.

abstract: BEECHER AROUND. -- All England seems to be stirred and agitated with the American question. Orators from North and South are traversing the country, rousing enthusiasm and opposition, and trying to enlist the support of the people, and vast meetings are held in all the great cities to listen to them. By the European news of this morning, we observed that HENRY WARD BEECHER, who had previously spoken to multitudes in Glasgow and Manchester, has held forth to a dense crowd in Liverpool, and that he would next mount the platform of Exeter Hall, in London. Beside BEECHER, Col. LAMAR, of Georgia, has been speaking in Liverpool, defending Southern institutions, (Slavery and rebellion,) and bespeaking the sympathy of England for the Confederacy. Mr. BERESFORD HOPE, Mr. LINDSAY and Sir ROUNDELL PALMER have also just delivered their views of the war -- the two former pro-rebel, and the latter (the Solicitor-General) ministerial or neutral. A recent arrival brought us the speeches of Lord WHARNCLIFFE and Hon. Mr. FORSTER -- the first rebel, the other Union. Mr. BEECHER, in his Manchester speech, paid particular attention to poor WHARNCLIFFE, who, we believe, is the first titled nobleman of Great Britain that has ever spoken distinctively and publicly for the South; and the way in which the noble Lord was handled by the noble American will be a "caution" to him for the future. We rather like this commotion that is going on in England; and though we doubt not Mr. BEECHEER's congregation are very anxious to have him back in Brooklyn, we think they would do well to give him a furlough until the close of the year, that he may thoroughly stir up the stolid souls and thick blood of Englishmen, and give the London Times something to talk about.

abstract: Our correspondent at headquarters of the Army of the Potomac writes that the enemy continue demonstrations in our front. On Monday, the Sixth and Ninth New-York cavalry regiments were attacked by the rebels with artillery, near Bealton Station, as they were going to relieve other cavalry regiments on picket. A brisk engagement ensued, continuing several hours, and our forces were compelled to fall back upon our infantry line. There were few casualties on either side. The woods are infested with guerrillas and robbers, who make it exceedingly hazardous for our men to stray beyond camp limits. Gen. MEADE's headquarters are still at Warrenton, and the enemy's camp fires indicate that they are in force beyond the Rappahannock. The work of reconstructing the railroad, which the rebels destroyed, is being prosecuted vigorously.

abstract: -- A serious stabbing affray took place at a late hour on Saturday night last between some workmen employed in MARCHA's looking-glass manufactory, in Twenty-sixth-street. The workmen, it seems, were on a strike. Two of them had a contract to work for a year at a stipulated price, and they refused to join the strikers. One of the latter, named DAVID R. THOM, while passing along the street, was attacked by a party of the strikers, headed by PATRICK WINN. A general fight ensued. THOM was knocked down and beaten, and WINN was stabbed in eight different places. THOM was arrested and is held to await the result. WINN is not expected to recover.

abstract: -- The second lecture of Dr. LIEBER's course was delivered last evening at the Columbia College Law School, to a very large and fine body of students of law. His theme was the character, origin and growth of International Law, and the learned lecturer elucidated and elaborated the subject with admirable skill. The study of such topics, under such a teacher, indicates the inception of a more liberal and comprehensive course of study for practitioners at the bar; and the fact that the opportunity has been so widely taken advantage of speaks well for the future prospects of the profession. No student of law, who would attain to eminence, should fail to enjoy the benefits of Dr. LIEBER's course of lectures.

abstract: Some of the Richmond papers are attempting to gloss over LEE's failure, in his last campaign to achieve the annihilation of the "Yankee army," on the ground that he could not get a fight out of MEADE. This apologetic statement is in ridiculous contradiction with what every man in either army cognizant of the movements of the respective Generals, knows to be the real state of the case. That the rebel commander, under certain favorable circumstances -- as for example if he had been able to plant his army on MEADE's communications and secure possession of the fortified heights of Centreville -- would have been willing to stand an attack, is not beyond the bounds of belief; but that, in the language of the Richmond Sentinel, "Gen. LEE, after diligently pursuing battle, was unable to obtain it because his fugacious adversary was too fleet," is drawing the long bow to a length which even a Richmond rebel ought to be ashamed of. Gen. MEADE invited battle at every point along the line of march that admitted of battle. He sought it at Sperryville, at Warrenton, and at Bull Run. In each case the wily rebel General, instead of accepting the proffered gage, attempted strategy and a turning movement, and this of course made a retrograde movement on the part of the Union commander necessary in order to meet him. In this the rebel officers themselves, when hurrying back across the Rappahannock, confessed that MEADE had "completely outgeneraled" them. We confess we think it would have been still better generalship had MEADE been able to compel LEE to fight; but that he did not succeed in doing so was through no lack of willingness on his part, for he was most eager for it throughout, and bitterly exclaimed afterward that it was "like having his eye-teeth pulled out to have lost the chance of a battle."

abstract: -The Democracy of this district, which comprises the whole of the Eleventh Ward, had a large meeting on Monday evening, at the Corner of First-avenue and Eleventh-street, and ratified the nomination of JOSEPH A. LYONS for Assembly, and LUKE F. COZZENS for Senator -- this Ward being a part of the sixth Senatorial District. Mr. EDWARD HARE presided, and Mr. SAMUEL W. SMILER acted as Secretary, Hon. WM.J. GILBERT and Messrs. THOMAS J. CREAMER, J. DAGGETT HUNT, and JOHN H. HARRINGTON addressed the meeting, urging the Democracy to stand firm and present a united front in order to regain the former ascendency of the party. Mr. LYONS himself appeared, and was very flatteringly received. He declined speaking further than to say that he was unpledged to anybody or anything but his party.

abstract: On Judicial Nominations; Judges and Political Shysters
snippet: On Judicial Nominations; Judges and Political Shysters
lead_paragraph: Vastly important as is the election of the Union State ticket next Tuesday, it would not be saying too much to declare that New-York and Brooklyn are at least equally concerned in the success of the right candidates for the local judiciary. There has never before been so distinct an issue presented in this region -- whether political legerdemain shall or shall not control the administration of justice. If this be determined in the affirmative, it is a blow shuck at the vital principles of society quite as serious, to say the least, to these great communities, as would be any sanction which the State at large could give to the flagitious civil administration of HORATIO SEYMOUR.

lead_paragraph: A fuller synopsis of the European news, left by the Canada at Cape Race, on Monday afternoon, has been forwarded. The American war had been the subject of public discussion. Two meetings for the consideration of this topic were held on the 16th, at Liverpool, one of which was addressed by Rev. HENRY WARD BEECHER, who had an immense audience, but whose remarks were stamefully interruped by secession sympathizers. The reverend gentleman, of course, could not be intimidated, and triumphantly continued his address to its proper conclusion. But BERESFORD HOPE had also reiterated his Pro-Southern sentiments to the Liverpool Southern Club, and Sir ROUNDELL PALMER had made a speech in which he asserted that England could not recognize the South until her independence was fully assured. Troubles have again broken out in India and New-Zealand, which the British have sent troops to quell. The Mexican Delegation were to be received by LOUIS NAPOLEON on the 17th inst. Russia has commenced detaching parts of Poland and incorporating them into the Russian Empire. The Poles had made overtures to the Sublime Porte of an alliance, defensive and offensive, and Russia had notified the Ottoman Empire that any recognition of the Poles as belligerents would be considered a declaration of war. The English Cabinet had not yet decided to recognize the Poles as belligerents. The Liverpool cotton market was buoyant on the 17th, and holders demanded an advance. Provisions and Breadstuffs were steady. Consols closed at 93@93 1/8 for money.

abstract: George Bowman vs. Matthew S. Moloney, Administrator, &c. of James R. Moloney, deceased. -- This is an action brought by the plaintiff to recover $3,260 15, for services rendered as attorney and counsel for James R. Moloney in his celebrated suits against the members of the California Vigilance Committee. The defence deny the indebtedness, and allege that an agreement was made with plaintiff, by the terms of which he was to conduct the suits and pay the disbursements, and in event of success to receive one-half of the amount recovered, and that having failed to obtain anything from the Vigilance Committee, there can be no claim against the estate of Mr. Moloney. Case still on.

abstract: -- The opponents of the Government in this State have just failed in one of their most cherished schemes. They had counted largely on the aid of Gov. BRAMLETTE, of Kentucky, and announced him to speak at several Democratic meetings. Gov. BRAMLETTE, however, discovered that he could not fulfill these engagements, and has announced that fact to the Democratic State Central Committee. The rebel raids which disturb the public peace in Kentucky are assigned as the reason. They may have had something to do with his declining, but we suspect other considerations had at least equal weight. Gov. BRAMLETTE is an unconditional Unionist, and sustains the Government in a vigorous prosecution of the war, whatever he may think of the specific measures it may adopt. No man in the country has denounced more warmly than he the conduct of those who, pretending to advocate the war, resist and attack every measure by which the Government seeks to carry it on. And this is precisely the position of the Democratic party in this State. When Gov. BRAMLETTE ascertained this fact, and came to understand what use was to be made of his Union speeches, he came to the very natural and just conclusion that he could better serve his country at home.

abstract: London Times on the Russo-American Alliance
snippet: London Times on the Russo-American Alliance
lead_paragraph: Whoever recommended the Russian Emperor to send a squadron of frigates to New-York, may congratulate himself on a great success. Now that it is none we see that it was exactly the thing to do, and almost wonder that it never occurred before to the astute politicians of St. Petersburg. The resemblances between the United States and the Russian Empire have not only been remarked by every one who has thought on the present and probable future state of the world, but they have created a sympathy between the two Powers which is becoming stronger under the influence of calamity, disappointed ambition, and the rebukes of the civilized world. Both in their arrogance and petulance of a few years since and in their present tone of more limited pretensions the Americans and Russians have shown an accord which indicates the gravitation of the two Powers to a permanent alliance. In the palmy days when NICHOLAS affected to be the arbiter of the Old World, and the American Presidents were conquering provinces in the New, the constant theme of congratulation between the Republic and the Despotism was the decadence of all Powers but themselves, and the certainly that they would subject all the countries about them, one after the other, to their dominion. They both had enormous territory, and regions still more immense, which they could make their own when they would. They were both new Powers, unincumbered with the debts, the traditions and the inferior social organization of their older rivals. They had a manifest destiny, and were to fulfill the designs of Providence by plundering and subjugating all who were not strong enough to resist. And who should resist fifty years hence, when the populations of the two aggressive empires should have doubled and tripled in a fashion impossible to the crowded inhabitants of Western Europe? From these dreams Russia was roused by a war which showed how unable she was to face the Western Powers, which forced her to dismantle a fortress and cede a portion of her territory, and which, if it had continued another year, would certainly have deprived her of valuable provinces. The pride of the United States has still more lately met its fall. The disruption of the Republic, the proof that a large part of the people had ceased to care for the Union -- nay, had imbibed a strong hatred against the rest of their countrymen -- the gloomy prospect of lingering warfare, to be ended at the very best only by the extirpation of the Southeners and the ruin of their country, -- these things are weighing on the spirits of the Federal patriots, whose Fourth of July orations used once to paint such a transcendent future.

abstract: -- There was no Court held yesterday in consequence of Justice CONNOLLY, who was in the vestibule, being absent from the bench. A large number of cases had to go over, and a large number of lawyers and witnesses to be dismissed and annoyed in consequence. Justices WELSH and OSBORN were in their seats, but Justice CONNOLLY, the presiding Justice, had other business to transact, though its importance did not carry him beyond the walls of the building. The Court is adjourned over to Thursday. Meantime, to prevent a recurrence of such a delay, the Board of Police Justices will convene and make an assignment of Justices for this Court who will be present and discharge their duty.

abstract: THEATRE FRANCAIS. -- This charming little establishment was reopened for the season last night under the very competent management of M. PAUL JUIGNET. There was an audience present of which any establishment in the City might have felt proud. It was simply limited by the capacity of the house. The piece selected for the opening was the charming comedy of the "Battaille de Dames." It was placed on the stage in a style of creditable elegance and luxury. We need scarcely add that it was acted with much ability; M. JUIGNET seldom selects a piece where the accident of a different result is to be encountered. Mlle. ANNA HAMBURG was excellent as Leonie, and met with a hearty reception; Mlle. LEVASSEUR, who was heard for the first time, appears to be a careful and well informed artiste; M. FAYE, another addition, is a capital young lover, and M. ROCHE, the pire noble, is unquestionably a very superior performer. The success of the evening was in fact won by this gentleman. M. DONATIEU, the premier comi[???]uc, was received with favor. We shall probably see him to greater advantage. A great deal of merited applause was bestowed on the performance. The evening was a complete success.

abstract: Rudolf Schaaf vs. Jacob Peier. -- This is an action brought to recover $5,000 damages for an assault by Peter upon Schaaf, in which plaintiff's leg was broken. Defendant is the keeper of a saloon. Some time in March, 1862, plaintiff, with some of his friends, went into defendant's saloon to get a drink. After drinking several schoffens of Rhine wine, plaintiff got happy, sang a song, was noisy, and finally excited the ire of Peter by abusing his dog; whereupon defendant, in defence of his dogs, made an assault upon plaintiff, throwing him to the ground with such violence as to break his leg. The defence denies the allegations of the complaint, and claim that defendant was only playing with plaintiff, and the injury was accidental.

abstract: -- ONE MAN BADLY STABBED -- At a Democratic Ratification meeting, held at "Mozart Garden," in Columbia-street, on Monday night, a quarrel arose between two rival candidates for the Assembly, and after a short time the row became general. Each candidate was ardently sustained by his followers, and many were the black eyes and bloody noses which resulted. One of the party was seriously stabbed, and but for the interference of the Police of the Thirteenth Precinct, who came down upon them in a body, many more would, doubtless, have been badly injured. No arrests were made.

abstract: JOHN L. MANNING, a native of this State, aged about 30 years, committed suicide at his boarding-house, No. 176 Bleecker-street, at 5 o'clock on Tuesday afternoon last, under the following circumstances: For some time past the deceased had been employed as a book-keeper by the firm of Messrs. CLAFLIN & MELLEN, of this City. About ten days ago he complained of being ill, and a day or two after he informed his employers that he was unable to attend to business, and must go home to recruit, and for a week previous to his decease he was confined to his room. Soon after 4 o'clock on Tuesday afternoon he requested his attendant, who was a young woman named Miss ELIZABETH Q. RICE, to go out and pay a doctor's bill; at the same time he gave her some money for the purpose. ELIZABETH was absent a little over half an hour, and when she returned she found the door of his room locked upon the inside. She knocked repeatedly, but receiving no answer she at length became suspicious that all was not right, and went in pursuit of the landlady of the house. The two went up to the room and tried to gain admittance by the door. Being unsuccessful in that, they, after much difficulty, entered through an adjoining room. They found MANNING suspended by the neck from the foot-board of his bed by a handkerchief, his lower limbs resting on the floor. He was dead, and from all appearances life had been extinct for several minutes.

New Democratic parties are springing up like mushrooms after a moist night; whether any of them will last until after election is somewhat doubtful.

abstract: The Israelites of this City are now about completing their beautiful New Orphan Asylum on the corner of Seventy-seventh-street and Third-avenue. The success of this enterprise is regarded by our Hebrow population as marking an epoch in the progress of Judaism in America and hence awakens their deepest interest.
lead_paragraph: The Israelites of this City are now about completing their beautiful New Orphan Asylum on the corner of Seventy-seventh-street and Third-avenue. The success of this enterprise is regarded by our Hebrow population as marking an epoch in the progress of Judaism in America and hence awakens their deepest interest. The edifice has been constructed under the auspices of the Hebrew Benevolent Society, into which the German Hebrew Benevolent Society was merged in 1859. Ground was broken in August, 1862, and on the 30th September, in that year, the corner-stone was laid with imposing ceremonies in the presence of Rabbi RAPHALL and the Jewish clergy, a large concourse of the Hebrews resident in this vicinity, and very many noted citizens of all denominations. The building is about finished, and within as well as without is one of the best appointed Asylums, and most beautiful structures in the country. Set back 125 feet from the avenue, it has a principal frontage of 120 feet on Seventy-seventh-street by 60 feet in depth and 90 in height to the top of the ornamental cupola. It consists within or cellars, basement, three stories and an attic. There are wings and projecting gables to the main building, the whole being in the Romanesque style of architecture, after the plans of H. FERNBACH the architect, the mason-work by Wm. LAMBEER, Jr., and the carpenter-work by HENNESSY & GIBSON. The cellars are built in the most substantial manner, of the best quarried bluestone, with hammered facings; the basement front is of Connecticut brown-stone, with rustic joints, and the remaining upper frontage of the best Philadelphia pressed brick, with brown-stone trimmings. The principal entrance, on Seventy-seventh-street, is reached by a handsome flight of brown-stone steps, with railings of the same material, and pedestals representing at the top the globe and bands, typical of charity spanning the earth. Over the doorway is an arched slab bearing the inscription, "Hebrew Orphan Asylum;" and in the centres of each of the projecting gables is a Mogen David, or David's shield, of double triangles, with the date "1862" on the main projection. The interior is arranged in vast halls for school-rooms, play-rooms, dormitories, hospital apartments, with a library, grand reception saloon, chapel, and the apartments of the superintendent and his family. The arrangements for the laundry, bakery, kitchen, bathing, heat, light and ventilation are of the most improved kind. The accommodation is ample for 200 orphans. The edifice and its fittings are now nearly complete, at a cost of about $50,000, and reflect great credit, not only upon the architect and contractors, but also upon the Building Committee -- Messrs. M. Rossman, Philip Frankenheimer, Samuel Hackes, Jacob Goldsmith, Henry Lewis, H.B. Herts, Jr., S.M. Cohen, M. Cooper, W. Heller and Seligmau Adler.

abstract: On the Stump
snippet: On the Stump
lead_paragraph: Gov. SEYMOUR has taken the field, and is stumping the State on behalf of the Democratic ticket. He spoke at Buffalo on Monday evening, and an outline of his remarks will be found in another column. Just now the Governor is a decided war man. He renews, with increased fervor and solemnity, the vows which he made just before the election last year, of entire devotion to the prosecution of the war, the overthrow of the rebellion, and the restoration of the Union. We doubt whether these protestations will have the same effect now as they had then. The people then had nothing by which to test their sincerity; now they have. They naturally took them then to mean precisely what their language implied; now they know that they mean something very different.

abstract: Needy Bohemians, it seems, sometimes foist themselves upon the continental public as correspondents of the newspapers, a trick not unknown on this side the water. The London Times, for instance, thus sketches the experiences of a gentleman, all connection with whom it disclaims:
lead_paragraph: -- Needy Bohemians, it seems, sometimes foist themselves upon the continental public as correspondents of the newspapers, a trick not unknown on this side the water. The London Times, for instance, thus sketches the experiences of a gentleman, all connection with whom it disclaims: "It seems that a Mr. Apel or Appel -- for the heroic syllables are ambiguously spelt -- has been accepted on the scene of the Polish insurrection as the correspondent of this journal, and has found himself not a little indebted to the importance with which this imaginary capacity invested him. Whoever he may be, or on whatever errand he may be bound, he did actually join one of the insurgent bands on Polish territory, and in that company he went into battle. We may hope that he conducted himself becomingly, but it appears that at the end of an engagement he was found, not metaphorically, but actually, 'up a tree.' In that proverbially awkward Position he was descried by a Cossack, who endeavored to bring him down by a bullet, but who missed his mark. Judiciously declining to risk a second shot, Mr. Appel descended from his eyrie, made terms with the Cossacks below, and surrendered at discretion. The predicament might have been an exceedingly unpleasant one but for his official reputation. It is painful to think what might have become of plain Mr. Appel, taken with arms in his hands, but 'our correspondent' was reserved for a different treatment. The distinguished captive was escorted with especial ceremony to the town of Lublin, and there brought into the presence of the Russian Commander, by whom, instead of being handed over to a file of soldiers, he was invited to dinner. That he should drink the health of the Emperor Alexander was, under such circumstances, perhaps, a pardonable proceeding, but we trust it is untrue that his politeness induced him to abuse and malign the cause of his late comrades."

abstract: Yesterday Rear-Admiral PAULDING, commanding the naval station in New-York, accompanied by this Aid and Capt. lead_paragraph: Yesterday Rear-Admiral PAULDING, commanding the naval station in New-York, accompanied by this Aid and Capt. MEADE, of the North Carolina, embarked on the steamer Vanderbilt, and proceeded down the bay to the anchorage of the French flagship Guerriers, where the steamer stopped, and the Admiral's barge rowed the distinguished party to the frigate. The Admiral was received on board the vessel with the courtesy characteristic of Frenchmen, and was warmly entertained while there. On leaving the ship an Admiral's salute was fired by the Guerriere, which was returned in a few moments afterward by the receiving-ship at the Navy-yard. Admiral PAULDING was highly pleased with his visit, and speaks in the highest terms of the discipline and character of the French officers and sailors.

abstract: PARADE AND REVIEW OF THE ELEVENTH BRIGADE. -- The Fall parade and review of the Eleventh brigade N.Y.S.M., under command of Gen. JESSE C. SMITH, took place yesterday. The regiments consist of the Twenty-third, Col. PRATT; Forty-seventh, Col. MESEROLE; Fifty-second, Col. COLE; Fifty-sixth, Col. ADAMS, in all numbering about twelve hundred men. They formed at their respective armories and marched through Willow, Cranberry, Fulton, Clinton, Atlantic and Court streets, arriving at the City Hall about noon, where they passed in review before the Mayor and Common Council. Resuming the line of march, the brigade proceeded along Fulton and Flatbush avenues to Polhemus Grove, near the city line, where they were inspected and afterwards reviewed by Major-Gen. DURYZA and Staff. They subsequently executed a number of field movements, in which several of the regiments showed great proficiency. Several hundred spectators were present, the ladies largely predominating. The brigade returned to the city about dark.

lead_paragraph: A CORNER-STONE LAID. -- The corner-stone of the Reformed Dutch Church at Tompkinsville, Staten Island, was laid on Tuesday last. The exercises were opened with an invocation by Rev. DR. MATTHEWS, who subsequently made a brief address. Then a historical sketch of the enterprise was read by the pastor, Rev. E.W. HITCHCOCK, who laid the stone, and the exercises were concluded with an address by Rev. A.R. THOMPSON, Rev. WM. TAYLOR and Rev. MR. STYKER also officiated. Among the articles placed in the corner stone were copies of the Orthodox religious publications of the day, a copy of the Fulton-st. Prayer Meeting Hymns, the Order of Exercises and Hymns sung at the laying of the stone, Phototographs of Rev. A.R. THOMPSON, Rev. P.M. BRETT and Rev. E.W. HITCHCOCK, Postage Currency of various denominations, American silver coins and over 70 varieties of copper coins and tokens, a memorial sketch of the former pastor, Rev. J.E. MILLER, with resolutions of the Consistory published after his death; also a similar memorial of Rev. DR. BRETT. The proposed dimensions of the building in the clear are as follows; Length, 87 feet 10 inches; width, 53 feet 4 inches. The building is to be wood filled in with brick; the style of architecture is to be gothic, and it is an interesting fact that the condition made by the donor of the lot upon which the church is building, -- that the structure should not be mortgaged, is likely to be met, as the entire amount necessary to complete it is now in bank awaiting the draft of the architect.

abstract: Gen. THOMAS FRANCIS MEAGHER lectured in in Boston, on Monday evening, on "The Army of the Potomac," referring in his introductory remarks to the historical relations of Ireland and America, in view of which, he observed, no one could be surprised by the fact "that in the war, which now tested her highest qualities as a nation, America should have had from Ireland some of the best hearts and strongest arms to aid her. He would not stop to vindicate the loyalty of the Irish born citizens in this crisis. It required no vindication. Founded in strict justice, confirmed by the pride as it was enforced by the sworn obligations of citizenship, the criticism that assailed it was the growth of ignorance or the baser offspring of faction." At a banquet given in honor of the lecturer, on the same evening, at the Fremont House, Gen. MEAGHER remarked. "Most of the foreigh-born citizens who have come to these shores have come because in the old world they were the sincere and devoted friends of Republican Government, and it devolves upon each and all of them, in this great crisis of the American Republic to show that whilst empires and monarchies and such forms of Government in the old word arrogate to themselves the divine privilege and the infallible authority of maintaining themselves, that there rests in the free hearts and willing arms of Republican citizens the power to maintain and perpetuate the national honor of the first and foremost Republic of history. [Applause.] With these convictions I bid you all a good-night, saying to you that as for myself, I did not quit the field of battle until I had no command. I did not quit it, however, without explicitly and distinctly telling the Government that whilst I would not imperil the reputation of the brigade by leading them myself, that my services and my life were at the call and disposal of the Government in any capacity whatever. I repeat here, and I say, that at any moment I am prepared to enter the field and to stand or fall by this Republic in the humblest capacity which an honest man can occupy, and that will be a capacity of honor."

abstract: The Memorial Diplomatique, of Paris, a semiofficial organ of the Austrian Government, in its issue of Oct. 11, publishes a letter from Trieste, which says the sole cause of the Arch duke MAXIMILIAN having authorized the Mexican deputation to present itself at the Chateau of Miramar, to communicate the vote of the nobles conferring upon him the diadem, was too significant to allow of a doubt as to his acceptance of the throne, it proceeds:
lead_paragraph: The Memorial Diplomatique, of Paris, a semiofficial organ of the Austrian Government, in its issue of Oct. 11, publishes a letter from Trieste, which says the sole cause of the Arch duke MAXIMILIAN having authorized the Mexican deputation to present itself at the Chateau of Miramar, to communicate the vote of the nobles conferring upon him the diadem, was too significant to allow of a doubt as to his acceptance of the throne, it proceeds: "It is not the Archduke MAXIMILIAN, whose noble character is heightened by unsurpassed urbanity, who would have allowed the Mexican deputation to undertake so long a voyage if it were to result in disappointment. In an autograph letter written by Napoleon III, to the Archduke, after the memorable vote of the Mexican nobles, his Majesty dwelt upon the necessity of having the wish of the capital ratified by the Mexican nation. It is to this wish and far-seeing suggestion of NAPOLEON that the Archduke wished to openly allude, as may be seen on reading the reply of the Archduke, which reveals the perfect accord existing on this point between the Emperor of France and himself. After having given his reply to the allocution of M. GUTIERREZ DE ESTRADA, the Prince entered into a long and intimate conversation with the members of the deputation. I have very attentively followed (said his Imperial Highness) the monarchial movements now proceeding in your country. Through the official reports which the Emperor of France has been kind enough to communicate to me, and in the information contained in the English journals, I have been enabled to clearly observe its progress. Here is a map of Mexico, upon which are exactly marked the points which nave adhered to the vote of the nobles. You see that only comprises a fourth part of Mexico, although I am convinced that the French army will very soon deliver the other portion from the pressure put upon them, and that then (as you assure me) an immense majority will sanction the vote af the 12th of July. Inform me that the majority has really adhered to my election, and in less than twenty-four hours I shall be ready to depart. Consider me as a soldier determined to respond to the call of Providence; for I recognize in an infallible manner the finger of God in the mission which has just fallen to me. I must have the National will manifest itself in terms permitting no legitimate doubt upon the unanimity of my election. The deputation could not have been impressed in a greater degree than it was by the justice of this sound reasoning, and, respecting the elevated character of the Archduke's sentiments, unanimously declared that the Mexican people only desired for the present to obtain the acquiesence of his Imperial Highness. With regard to the realization of the vote, the deputation considers itself bound to leave entirely to the wisdom of the Archduke the choice of the epoch. The Mexican deputation relinquish the idea of going to Vienna to solicit the honor of being presented to the Emperor FRANCIS JOSEPH. It is considered that to hasten the departure of the Archduke for Mexico, it is necessary to profit by the sailing of the next packet from St. Nazalre, on the 15th inst., in order to dispatch some of its members to Mexico.

abstract: Generals, The Removal of
snippet: Generals, The Removal of
lead_paragraph: When the axe of official authority falls and takes off the head of the commander of an army, there is little for the public to do but to fall back on faith, believe that it is wisely and properly done, and rest assured that the future will clear up much that is now mysterious. The removal of a commanding General is strictly an executive act. We can seldom know the reason prompting it, and it would generally be neither wise nor politic that we should know it. At the same time, it is important that the conduct of those in authority should be such as to inspire public confidence that, in changing the command of an army, only the highest sense of duty prompts the action. Aside from the special reasons governing the removal of individual commanders, there is a general policy of the matter, and this should be large, discreet and well considered. It should not be hard to find a just mean between the wild policy of the rulers of revolutionary France, who (literally as well as metaphorically) cut off the head of a General the moment he was unsuccessful, and the Austrian inertia which kept hoary-headed imbecility and proved incapacity, systematically in command.

abstract: -- Gen. ROSECRANS made two brief and most excellent speeches at the public reception given to him in Cincinnati. They breathe the spirit of genuine and thorough loyalty by which all his action has hitherto been marked. He called upon all to remember that it is the right and the duty of the Government to remove, promote and change its Generals in its own discretion, and that it is the duty of the people to assume that there are good reasons for whatever is done in this way until the contrary is shown. Acting on this principle he declined to raise any question as to the action of the Government in his own case, and was quite willing to leave the future to decide as to its propriety and necessity. This is manly and loyal, and may well serve as an example for general imitation.

abstract: -Mr. SINCLAIR TOUSEY has published a second part of the New Gospel of Peace. It is longer than the first, and though, as a matter of course, it lacks the charm of novelty, which contributed not a little to the success of its predecessor, it is exceedingly clever and readable. It relates the history of the riots in New-York and of the defeat of the rebels at Gettysburgh. This is by far the most successful political pamphlet of the day. Its authorship is a matter of a good deal of speculation, and has thus for been very admirably kept.

abstract: A meeting of the association having in charge the matter of urging the extension of the Eighthavenue Railroad to Harlem River, was held at Bright's Hotel, Manhattanville, on Tuesday evening last. A deputation from Westchester County was present. The Westchester County men are beginning to take the matter up, as they feel deeply interested in the completion of the project, and they stated that at the next meeting they would send a large deputation.

abstract: The success of the Union ticket next Tuesday has come to be considered almost an absolute certainty. Undoubtedly there is good ground for this confidence, yet it insures nothing.
lead_paragraph: The success of the Union ticket next Tuesday has come to be considered almost an absolute certainty. Undoubtedly there is good ground for this confidence, yet it insures nothing. Our political annals abound with instances of just as great confidence bitterly dashed by the result. The future can never be discounted with absolute security. But even were an inspired seer to foretell the election of the Union candidates, it would not justify a relaxing of effort one tittle. The fortunes of the Union candidates are nothing. Good men though they all are, we are not combatting at all to gain honors for them. There are hundreds, if not thousands, of men in the State just as deserving, and to whom these honors are just as much due. Nor is the difference between the fidelity with which the ministerial duties of the various offices would be discharged by the two series of candidates, a matter of particular consequence. Either of the candidates for Treasurer, doubtless would keep the public funds securely; either of the candidates for Secretary of State, doubtless would keep the public records truly; either of the candidates for Judge of the Court of Appeals would, we are sure, discharge his high duties with great learning and perfect probity. So far as the mere material interests of the State are concerned, we are not at all afraid to concede that the election of every man on the so-called "Democratic" ticket would produce no serious damage.

abstract: Party lines are pretty well destroyed in Kings County, in some instances none but Democrats being in nomination; but, in the Second Senatorial District the War Democrats and Republicans have united on a decided Republican, while the Peace Democrats have nominated an undoubted Democrat of their own virulent stripe, a recreant Van Buren Freesoiler. DEMAS STRONG, the candidate of the Union party, is well known to the people of Brooklyn for his integrity of conduct while a member of the Common Council, for his thorough loyally and consistent Republicanism; while his opponent, SAMUEL E. JOHNSON, who, in the Legislature last Winter, acted in concert with TOM FIELDS, and consistently showed himself willing to sacrifice the highest interests of the State to the success of his faction. There could be no question of the election of Mr. STRONG, if the loyal people of his District would be at the trouble of giving him their votes, and this they will not fail to do if they can but be made acquainted with the importance of defrating his opponent. Mr. JOHNSON has influential family relations which will operate to a certain extent in his favor, but the district is too large to be controlled by a family clique. We understand that the friends of Mr. JOHNSON are attempting to injure Mr. STRONG, by urging against him his action while an Alderman in giving relief to a Catholic Orphan Asylum, whose helpless inmates had been deprived of their shelter by a conflagration. But, if they can find nothing worse against him than this, he must be a very strong candidate indeed.

abstract: "Hon. BENJ. F. MANIERRE has declined the Independent Union nomination for Senator from the Sixth District, leaving WILLIAM LAIMBEER, Jr., the only anti-Copperhead candidate, Mr. MANIERRE once represented that District in the Senate, and served with eminent fidelity and efficiency. At the last election he was the leading Union candidate, though his rival had the great advantage of being accounted the regular nominee. Yet we believe he has now acted wisely as well as patriotically in withdrawing and doing all he can to elect Mr. Laimbeer, whose popularity is decided, and success, we trust, is no longer doubtful."

abstract: A cotemporary  says that "the rebels never change the commanders of their armies," and contrasts, in this respect, their policy with ours. This is a great error. Their main army in Virginia has had three commanders BEAUREGARD, JOHNSTON and LEE. Their army on the Mis- ...
lead_paragraph: says that "the rebels never change the commanders of their armies," and contrasts, in this respect, their policy with ours. This is a great error. Their main army in Virginia has had three commanders -- BEAUREGARD, JOHNSTON and LEE. Their army on the Mississippi, which was finally driven into Vicksburgh and captured, had repeated changes of commanders; and the same was the case with nearly all their minor armies. Their Tennessee or Central army has remained under BRAGG for a long time; but if we had retained a General in command who had retreated as often, lost as much territory and suffered as many defeats, we should have had no end of denunciation of our military authorities.

lead_paragraph: It is said, on apparently good authority, that at least seventy thousand Democrats in Pennsylvania voted for Gov. CURTIN at the recent election. In Ohio the number of Democrats who gave their suffrages to JOHN BROUGH was still larger in proportion. Gov. CURTIN was a Republican in his antecedents, JOHN BROUGH a Democrat; but this difference was not thought of in the two canvasses. It was enough that they were both staunch friends of the war, and the regular Union candidates.

lead_paragraph: THE LOCAL MILITIA. -- Yesterday there was an inspection and review of the Thirteenth and Twentyeighth regiments, infantry, and the Seventieth regiment, cavalry and artillery, by Brig.-Gen. CROOKE and Staff. The Seventieth, Col. CROPSY, formed at the State Arsenal in Portland-avenue, and after parading about a number of the streets of East Brooklyn, formed in line on Cumberland-street, opposite Fort Greene Park. The Lancers came first, the cavalry next and the artillery brought up the rear. They presented a fine appearance. After inspection they marched into the Park and were exercised in a number of field movements, after which they were dismissed. The Twenty-eighth regiment also mustered at the Arsenal where they passed inspection, and after parading through several streets broke ranks. The cavalry mustered about 250 men, and the infantry about the same. The Thirteenth regiment was inspected at the City Armory, and made no parade.

lead_paragraph: A telegram from Chattanooga, dated Wednesday last, conveys the important intelligence that the enemy's position on Lookout Mountain has been flanked and their evacuation is a necessity. The honor of the achievement is credited to a detachment of the Eleventh Ohio regiment, under Col. STANLEY, who floated fifty pontoons down the Tennessee River in face of the rebel sharpshooters, landed at Brown's Ferry and drove the enemy from the ridge on the south side, thus opening communication with Bridgeport. A later dispatch says that 2,000 of Gen. PALMER's division, under Gen. HAZES, had succeeded in driving the enemy from Lookout Mountain. Our special correspondent at Chattanooga says, in a dispatch slated Wednesday, that the intelligence respecting BRAGG's movement to get between BURNSIDE and. Chattanooga, though generally believed, is not altogether reliable.

abstract: We notice that a final decree was entered yesterday in the case of the prize ship Hiawatha and her cargo, in the United States Circuit Court. The case has been noticeable as ...
lead_paragraph: We notice that a final decree was entered yesterday in the case of the prize ship Hiawatha and her cargo, in the United States Circuit Court. The case has been noticeable as being one of the first, if not the first, of the prize cases which came before the District Court at the breaking out of the rebellion. At that time great doubt prevailed as to the principles which the Courts would lay down in reference to the law of prize as applicable to the state of things then existing. Eminent counsel were engaged on behalf of the vessel, and professed themselves not a little disappointed when Judge BETTS decided the case in accordance with the principles which have since become the settled law. An appeal was taken by the Circuit Court, and then to the Supreme Court at Washington, where the decree was affirmed, and now, in less than two years and a half from the commencement of the case, the final decree is entered in the cause. It would be a great public benefit if a final decision could be reached in as short a time in the Courts of this State.

abstract: The grand Russian Ball, the anticipated splendors of which agitate the dreams of all Japonicadom, is close at band, the date having been fixed for Friday, November 5. The banquets, junketing, speech-making and excursions that have preceded it ring through the length and breadth, not only of America, but even of Europe; and the Cossack sentry, tar away on the borders of Caucasia, has by this time caught the rumor of the wonderful friendship displayed by the people of the West for his Supreme Hetman, the Czar. It is quite in place then, that there should be a special flutter here about the crowning festival, and we are happy in being able, this morning, to communicate some highly interesting particulars on the subject.

abstract: making a great deal of noise about the amount of liquor drank, or at least ordered, by Maj.Gen. BLAIR, while he was in command of a division in the rear of Vicksburgh. Now, we ...
lead_paragraph: making a great deal of noise about the amount of liquor drank, or at least ordered, by Maj.Gen. BLAIR, while he was in command of a division in the rear of Vicksburgh. Now, we don't see any sense in this. In the first place, the packages of brandy and bitters for which BLAIR's order has been found, never reached that officer. In the second place, if they had reached him, the quantity ordered was moderate; for the horrible water that our troops had in the Summer months while in the rear of Vicksburgh, was unusable unless there was "something mixed with it." When some one charged Gen. GRANT, in the President's hearing, with drinking too much liquor, Mr. LINCOLN, recalling Gen. GRANT's successes, said that if he could find out what brand of whisky GRANT drank, he would send a barrel of it to all the other commanders. In like manner, Gen. BLAIR's liquor, or orders for it, seem never to have affected his efficiency at the head of his gallant and victorious division.

abstract: Three candidates are in the field -- BENJAMIN PRINCE for the Copperheads, Col. A.M. WOOD for the Unionists, and MARTIN KALBFLEISCH, Independent. All these are of Democratic antecedents; but the Republicans unite with a large number of War Democrats in giving Col. WOOD their enthusiastic support. Between them, we trust it will be found that there is staunch patriotism enough in Brooklyn to elect him. It will be an anomaly if a city which has derived so much lustre from the gallant conduct of its soldiers in this war, should prefer an unmitigated Copperhead to be its executive officer over the leader of its own famous Fourteenth. Col. WOOD is, to say the least, every whit the equal of his chief competitor in ability and personal character, while he as much excels him in patriotic sentiment and service as one Northern man can excel another.

lead_paragraph: The arrival yesterday of the steamships Germania and City of Washington off Cape Race, gives five days' later advices from Europe. The most interesting item of news refers to the rebel pirates and Federal cruisers at the Cape of Good Hope. The United States steamer Vanderbilt had safely arrived at that point in pursuit of the Alabama, and was repairing at St. Simon's Bay. Her presence seems to have been known to Capt. SEMMES, who will avoid an engagement if possible. He is of opinion that she is much faster than the Alabama, and if it happens that his vessel is blockaded, he will endeavor to slip cut unobserved as he did when watched last year by the San Jacinto at Martinique. HENRY WARD BRECHER had addressed an immense audience at Exeter Hall on American affairs. Great Britain, after all the recent glorification of her iron-clad channel fleet, does not seemto be satisfied that they are quite the thing, and the Admiraly Board has determined to build a new squadron of gunboats, armor-plated, to carry two Armstrong guns. _ England and Austria, according to the Paris Pays. are still in consultation respecting an identical note on the Polish question, and France will abide by every act necessary to meet the demands of public opinion in Europe. The Russian troops in Poland had bee reinforced, and the Black Sea flotilla was to be fully equipped. Denmark was massing a large body of troops on the Schleswig Southern frontier. The stipulations of a treaty of alliance between Sweden and Denmark had been agreed upon, but would not be ratified until the German troops advanced into Holstein. The Ionian Islands were to be annexed to Greece immediately upon the dissolution of the Senate. The Liverpool Cotton market was excited on the 21st, and prices had advanced 1/2d.@1d. lb. Breadstuffs and Provisions remained steady. Consuls closed at 93 1/8 for money, and 931/8@93 1/4 for account.

lead_paragraph: United States Marshal MURRAY, on Wednesday, arrested four residents of this City and committed them to Fort Lafayette on a charge of being engaged in the business of running the blockade of Southern ports. One of the persons arrested is a sea Captain and the other three are engaged in mercantile pursuits in this City. A large number of letters and documents were also seized, which, so far as they have been examined, relate mostly to the business in which the parties were engaged -- viz., fitting out vessels at this port to run the blockade. They also establish the fact of collusion between the blockade runners and the traitor VALLANDIGHAM in his escape from Dixie. The Marshal does not deem it prudent to divulge the names of the parties arrested as yet. The information brought to light by the letters and documents will doubtless lead to further arrests.

lead_paragraph: Late on Wednesday night Mr. MICHAEL WHITE, of Carbondale, Lucern County, Penn., temporarily stopping at Sweeney's Hotel, was assailed in the vicinity of the Apollo Rooms in Broadway, and a valuable gold watch and chain taken from him. The robbers are named RICHARD CONWAY and FRANCIS MCCOY. The theft was effected by one of them seizing WHITE, and holding him as quietly as possible while the other caught the guard chain which was hanging on his vest, tore it from its fastening, and with that and the watch attempted to make his escape. Officer KAVENY, of the Sixth Precinct, was, however, at hand, and WHITE pointed out MCCOY and CONWAY as the thieves. This was a signal for an onslaught on the Policeman. By means of a well-known signal, several other members of the gang were speedily brought to the scene, and KAVENY being overpowered by numbers, was compelled to send for reinforcements. Fifteen or twenty Metropolitans were soon on the ground, the thieves were overcome, and MCCOY and CONWAY were taken into custody. Yesterday Justice CONNOLY committed them both to the Tombs. The watch was not recovered.

abstract: Senor ROMERO was yesterday re- ...  ceived by the President as Envoy Extraordinary and Minister Plenipotentiary of the Mexican Republic; and he made a very neat speech on the occasion, to which Mr. LINCOLN neatly responded. Senor ROMERO said that ...
lead_paragraph: -Senor ROMERO was yesterday received by the President as Envoy Extraordinary and Minister Plenipotentiary of the Mexican Republic; and he made a very neat speech on the occasion, to which Mr. LINCOLN neatly responded. Senor ROMERO said that "the Government and people of Mexico entertain the greatest friendship and consideration for the Government and people of the United States of America, and fervently desire the prosperity, aggrandizement and welfare of the country;" and to this the President replied that the Envoy knew "how sincerely and how profoundly the United States desired that Mexico might always enjoy the blessings of domestic and foreign peace with perfect security, prosperity, independence and freedom." Such sentiments of mutual esteem between the representatives of the two North American Republics are gratifying.

abstract: The admirable stroke by which the four independent armies of the West, (BURNSIDE'S, ROSECRANS', HOOKER'S and GRANT'S,) operating on different lines, and toward different aims, have been consolidated into one, should be immediately imitated in the case of forces ...
lead_paragraph: The admirable stroke by which the four independent armies of the West, (BURNSIDE's, ROSECRANS', HOOKER's and GRANT's,) operating on different lines, and toward different aims, have been consolidated into one, should be immediately imitated in the case of forces in Virginia. We have now in that State two independent armies -- the Army of the Potomac, under Gen. MEADE, and the "Army of Virginia," under Gen. FOSTER, with its headquarters at Fortress Monroe -- both of which have Richmond as their objective, and yet each, seemingly, too weak to accomplish the desired work. Can any man tell the wisdom of thus keeping these two forces divided in fruitless inaction? The army on the Peninsula is too strong merely to garrison Fortress Monroe, and yet too weak to attempt an advance to Richmond. The Army of the Potomac also is thought to be insufficient for this end, and yet it is certainly unnecessarily strong for the mere faineant duty of "covering Washington." With the consolidation of these two forces, a serious effort might be made on the one or the other line -- by the Peninsula or the overland route -- to capture the rebel capital.

lead_paragraph: MONSTER SERENADE TO GEN. SICKLES THIS EVENING. -- The gentlemen who proposed the dinner to Maj.-Gen. SICKLES, mention of which was made yesterday, finding he is in town, and determind, in default of accepting a dinner, that he shall receive a serenade, give him one this evening at 9 o'clock, at the Brevoort House. It will be a monster affair, DODWORTH's full and splendid band "doing the music," and in such style as has not been rivaled even by JULIEN; in short, it will be the most imposing musical demonstration ever given in New-York. As the firemen composed a large proportion of the Excelsior Brigade, and as Chief DECKER is among those giving the serenade, we presume the Department will make this the occasion for an ovation from them also, to one whom they so well know and esteem. The affair may be called impromptu, as but late yesterday was it known that the General was in town. There will be an immense audience undoubtedly, of whom the fair will form a large proportion, in equipages or among the welcoming throng.

lead_paragraph: Most of our neighbors in Brooklyn have, like the rest of us, been reporting their annual income for the year 1862, and show, particularly on "the Heights," an exalted view of their ability to live comfortably. Several report their income at $100,000 and upward. The highest amount reported is $200,000 on which the tax is $10,000, for which sum the gentle man -- a New-York merchant, residing on the Heights -- sent his check yesterday to the Collector. The smallest income reported is one dollar -- tax three cents -- by a New-York broker. The Assessor, WM.E. ROBINSON, Esq., returned his annual assessment list to the Collector the present week, and it fools up $480,773 73, of which $438,983 60 is the tax on income. This, taken with the monthly returns made in the past year, foot up considerably over a million.

abstract: -- About as exhilarating a bit of reading as we have seen for some time is the speech of HENRY WARD BEECHER, delivered at Liverpool, England, on the 16th inst., which we give in our columns this morning. All Mr. BEECHER's raciness, readiness, skill, wit, courage and eloquence were exhibited in their perfection to his English audience. The rudest and noisiest interruptions could not daunt him; to the sharpest interrogatories he had the most poignant retorts; of every situation he was the master. The vulgar fellows who thrust their bad breeding before the audience were made to feel the power and see the effects that appertain to calm self-possession, intellectual superiority, imperturbable humor, and the manners of a gentleman. It must do these Englishmen good to see how a live American can talk.

abstract: Mr. BROUGH, the Governor elect of Ohio,  who was elected by a majority almost without precedent for its magnitude, made a brief speech the other day at a meeting of congratulation, in which he said that the great political triumph in Ohio was "not a triumph of any man no man could have won it...
lead_paragraph: -- Mr. BROUGH, the Governor elect of Ohio, who was elected by a majority almost without precedent for its magnitude, made a brief speech the other day at a meeting of congratulation, in which he said that the great political triumph in Ohio was "not a triumph of any man -- no man could have won it; nor was it a triumph of any party, as we have heretofore classified and understood them -- for party lines to a great extent were obliterated, and masses of both parties joined to swell the great triumph. The lines of division," he continued, "were between those who were friends of the Government and country, on the one hand, and the opponents of these on the other."

lead_paragraph: The canvass is now nearly closed. It has not been conducted with the same system and thoroughness as in some of the other States. There seems to have been a general feeling, upon the part of the Union men, that the right result is sure enough without any special effort -- that the acts of HORATIO SEYMOUR, during the year, are enough of themselves to convince every reasonable man of his duty, and to stimulate every patriotic man to its performance. The evils of factious opposition to the Government have been brought home to the "business and bosoms" of the people of the State, in a manner nowhere else experienced, and this fact has been relied upon to play the chief part in securing the victory.

lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The performance last evening, being the twelfth, was the final one of Mr. MARETZEK's first subscription season. Of the general results we know nothing, but we presume that the campaign has been moderately successful. There was no lack of energy on the part of Mr. MARETZEK, and although the artists were sick and unreliable at the commencement of the season, they came up to time at its close, and in two or three operas achieved as many successes. The manager announces a fresh subscription. It will commence on Monday, when "Lucrezia Borgia" will be played for the first time this season, with special attractions in the second parts. Those who intend assisting Mr. MARETZEK and themselves (for in paying for twelve nights in advance they do the one, and in securing the best seats they do the other) should remember that the new subscription opens to-day, and that the rule is first come first served.

abstract: CONTINUED BRU  TALITIES OF THE CHIVALRY. It is a shocking tale that is told, and they are most painful exhibitions that are made, by the Union prisoners who have just come down the James River from Richmond; and the unfortunate...
lead_paragraph: -- CONTINUED BRUTALITIES OF THE CHIVALRY. -- It is a shocking tale that is told, and they are most painful exhibitions that are made, by the Union prisoners who have just come down the James River from Richmond; and the unfortunate men themselves are living, or rather dying, witnesses to the truth of their statements. These prisoners of war (181 were on the boat) were maltreated and starved by the rebel authorities, until, when they came within our lines, they had been reduced to living skeletons. Eight of the number died on the boat on its way down -- being actually starved to death. Of the remainder, every man had to be sent to the hospitals, and the surgeon gave his opinion that more than one-third of them must die, being beyond the power of nourishment or medicine. They all say their condition was brought on by the treatment they received in Richmond -- having both been starved and exposed to the weather.

abstract: This is the last day of the sessions of this Committee. At noon the Committee will pay off and discharge all their employes, and after that no business will be transacted further than to pay for the obtainment of substitutes for such drafted men as have had their application papers signed by the acting Chairman, Supervisor BLUNT, and have not yet furnished substitutes.
lead_paragraph: -- This is the last day of the sessions of this Committee. At noon the Committee will pay off and discharge all their employes, and after that no business will be transacted further than to pay for the obtainment of substitutes for such drafted men as have had their application papers signed by the acting Chairman, Supervisor BLUNT, and have not yet furnished substitutes. This class of persons do not exceed twenty-five. We hope to be able to give a statement on Monday of the entire results of the Committee's labors. The new $2,000,000 ordinance to provide substitutes in advance on the next draft is yet before the Mayor.

abstract: The United States vs. The Schooner Tampico and her Cargo. This vessel was captured by the Cayuga, on April 3, 1863, off the coast of Texas, just after she had escaped from Sabine Pass, which was then blockaded.
lead_paragraph: The United States vs. The Schooner Tampico and her Cargo. -- This vessel was captured by the Cayuga, on April 3, 1863, off the coast of Texas, just after she had escaped from Sabine Pass, which was then blockaded. The British Consul appeared in the suit, and claimed vessel and cargo in behalf of British subjects, but no further steps were taken to defend the cause, and the case was submitted by the District Attorney to the Court for decision. The evidence showed that the vessel escaped from Sabine Pass about 12 o'clock at night, and was captured about 5 A.M., next morning. The vessel's papers showed that she was built in New-York, in 1856, and there was no other proof of any change of ownership, except an informal statement of one David J. Jolly, at Tampico, that he is a British subject, and a declaration of the British Consul at Tampico, that Jolly had purchased the vessel.

abstract: LINCOLN has made various proclamations since the commencement of the war, some of which have s[???]med to the world scarcely less unreasonable than those of the Chinese Emperor. The latest performance of this sort is the call for three hundred thousand men. These enormous figures formerly possessed considerable potency. They starled the imagination and bewildered the judgment. Like over indulgence or excess in other things, they have now lost hteir power. Like a reckless spead[???], or an injudicious showman, LINCOLN has exhausted his resources, and stated the palate of the audience. They have now become familiar with these enormous bravados and their insignificant results. A call for three or four hundred thousand men fails to elicit a note of admiration from the jaded sensibilities of the world. Even LINCOLN -- dead as he appears to be to all sense of the ridiculous, except in the form of a bar-room story -- shrinks from the absurdity of calling for a million. He has used up his stock of novelties, and the manager is obliged to repeat his stale exhibitions.

abstract: -- We give the speech of Sir ROUNDELL PALMER, the British Attorney-General, as another example of the fairer, or rather, less bitterly partisan, views which have of late been expressed by official persons in Great Britain. The speaker is not a man of remarkable strength, or ability, or eloquence, but his position gives to his opinions a certain importance. In almost every particular, he follows in the wake of Earl RUSSELL's Blairgowrie speech; and there have recently been numerous signs that that speech set forth what is likely to be the fixed policy of the British Government as regards their treatment of American questions.

abstract: The frequent strikes at the different Navy-yards, and the no less frequent applications of workmen for increase of pay, having embarrassed the Government very much of late, the Secretary of the Navy has issued an important order which promises to settle the matter.
lead_paragraph: The frequent strikes at the different Navy-yards, and the no less frequent applications of workmen for increase of pay, having embarrassed the Government very much of late, the Secretary of the Navy has issued an important order which promises to settle the matter. Instructions were yesterday forwarded from the Navy Department, as we learn from our Washington correspondent, to the commanding officers of the Navy-yards at Boston, Portsmouth, N.H., Philadelphia and New-York, requesting them to appoint each a Board of officers for the purpose of investigating the rates of pay at the different ship-yards and workshops in the cities named, with the view to equalize the wages paid by the Government and by private parties. The following officers will be ordered to-day to visit the different workshops in New-York for the purpose indicated: Lieut.-Commander PAULDING, Chief Engineer DELUCE, Assistant Naval Constructor DAVIDSON, Master Blockmaker MITCHELL and Foreman of Smiths DICKERSON. These officers are to visit the depots of employment in the City and report to Admiral PAULDING the wages paid for mechanics and laborers. Of course the pay given to the latter will be regulated by that paid to 'longshoremen.

abstract: From Charleston Harbor we have the exciting news that on Tuesday last Gen. GILLMORE brought three of his heavy guns to bear upon the city, and flung shells laden with Greek fire into its very heart. Other guns were being trained upon it, and were expected to open on Tuesday afternoon. The batteries on the islands also were active, and four monitors were in position, ready for work.
lead_paragraph: From Charleston Harbor we have the exciting news that on Tuesday last Gen. GILLMORE brought three of his heavy guns to bear upon the city, and flung shells laden with Greek fire into its very heart. Other guns were being trained upon it, and were expected to open on Tuesday afternoon. The batteries on the islands also were active, and four monitors were in position, ready for work. The rebels were surprised, and replied to our fire with some reserve. It does not appear whether or not Gen. GILLMORE purposes to make this the grand and general assault. We have rebel papers, with news from Charleston up to Tuesday, but they make little mention of the attack.
